<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Tries for Tax Relief in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Facing a money crunch, Republican senators  
Thursday began sorting through options for a phased-in package of 
targeted tax cuts as prospects dimmed for significant reductions in 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike last year's ``April surprise,'' the Congressional Budget  
Office will not raise projections for this year's budget surplus 
until July 1 at the earliest, a spokesman said. That dashes GOP 
hopes for an immediate infusion of cash for election-year tax cuts, 
particularly important as Yugoslavia war costs rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's zip for 2000,'' said Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., a  
member of the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Senate Republicans met behind closed doors  
Thursday to discuss proposals ranging from cuts in capital gains 
taxes to relief from the so-called marriage penalty in which many 
two-earner couples pay more income taxes than if single. 
</P>
<P>
	No final decisions were expected, but Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla.,  
said it was a chance for Republicans to ``share their views ... 
about what the plan ought to look like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., chairman of the Senate Budget  
Committee, said he told the group that tax relief totaling about 
$15 billion was possible for 2000. But others said it would be a 
mistake to concentrate on small-bore cuts and to push hard for a 
huge 10-year cut of nearly $800 billion, even if its full impact is 
delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to focus on the total amount, not a token tax cut,''  
said Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans began the year touting broad tax relief such as a 10  
percent across-the-board income tax cut, but there are now 
obstacles even to modest cuts. First, the budget surplus for the 
next few years is driven by Social Security funds, money both 
parties have promised not to touch. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also a reluctance to cut government programs already  
strapped by caps on spending and the unknown future costs of the 
conflict over Kosovo. But the GOP is determined not to give up on 
its signature political issue, even if a major tax cut must be 
phased in slowly over the next decade as the non-Social Security 
budget surplus grows. 
</P>
<P>
	They are scouring the budget for ways to offset the costs of tax  
relief in the early years, including serious consideration of 
President Clinton's proposals to close several corporate tax 
shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking to see where there are opportunities to raise  
revenues so we can give the working people a tax cut,'' said Sen. 
William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance Committee. 
``We want to give as large a tax cut as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the House, Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer,  
R-Texas, has asked the committee's members to each submit three tax 
relief ideas to lay groundwork for a tax bill likely to move 
through the panel in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Most lawmakers believe it will include several items that appeal  
to specific groups as well as extend popular expiring business 
provisions. Clinton took a similar approach in his tax plan with 
proposals such as credits for stay-at-home parents, breaks for the 
steel industry and credits for buyers of fuel-efficient cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Mack unveiled a bill Thursday that embraces several GOP  
priorities: phasing out estate taxes, cutting capital gains tax 
rates, increasing the standard income tax deduction for married 
couples and singles and making the soon-to-expire business research 
and development tax credit permanent. 
</P>
<P>
	Total cost over five years is roughly $140 billion -- partly  
because capital gains tax cuts actually raise money as investors 
sell more securities -- but it balloons to about $750 billion over 
10 years once all the provisions kick in. This will enable 
Republicans to say they are passing a monumental tax cut before the 
2000 elections, even if voters won't see all the results for years. 
</P>
<P>
	But it doesn't appear there will be much Democratic help in  
passing a GOP-crafted bill. ``I frankly doubt that we are likely to 
support what they're going to produce,'' said House Minority Leader 
Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
