<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Networks Nix Forbes' Kickoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steve Forbes has scuttled secret plans to  
broadcast the kickoff of his Republican presidential campaign live 
on national television, according to an adviser who said TV 
networks would not sell the wealthy businessman air time for the 
Waldorf-Astoria gala. 
</P>
<P>
	The posh and pricey New York hotel will still be the site of his  
first fund-raiser, a June 16 event scheduled to raise $1 million. 
But don't look for it on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes originally hoped to broadcast the June 16 event as part  
of a 30-minute campaign kickoff, according to a senior adviser. The 
aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said plans included: 
</P>
<P>
	--A famous actor introducing a video biography of Forbes.  
</P>
<P>
	--Using satellites to broadcast cheering crowds at Forbes  
fund-raisers in New Hampshire, California and Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	--Forbes, his family in tow, delivering a scene-setting campaign  
speech from the Waldorf. 
</P>
<P>
	But the TV networks refused to sell time to the campaign,  
apparently worried about complicated equal-time election laws, the 
adviser said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This being a live infomercial, it wouldn't be something  
national networks do. National networks don't do infomercials,'' 
said CBS News spokesman Kevin Tedesco. ``We have never broadcast an 
infomercial. That's the province of local stations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of other networks were not immediately available for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Unable to broadcast the show, Forbes dropped the idea of  
producing a formal kickoff; he has already announced his campaign 
on the Internet. The June 16 event will be strictly a fund-raiser, 
though Forbes will speak and it will be open to the press. 
</P>
<P>
	The adviser said Forbes may produce a nationally televised show  
later in the campaign, if he is allowed to purchase the time. 
</P>
<P>
	He will travel to Iowa on June 17 and New Hampshire on June 18  
to open campaign offices in the two critical presidential states -- 
a sign that his campaign is heading into a new stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be the kickoff fund-raiser, the first of more than 200  
fund-raising events between June and February of next year,'' 
campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the symbolism of beginning a new chapter of his campaign  
at the Waldorf, she said, ``This is a kickoff fund-raiser and 
nothing else. Holding a fund-raiser at the Waldorf-Astoria is not 
unusual when you're looking at raising upwards of $1 million. It's 
a hotel rich in political history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and other Democrats have held fund-raisers at  
the hotel. A Forbes official said President Reagan once broadcast a 
Waldorf-Astoria fund-raiser to a few cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
