<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Strong in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Most national retailers enjoyed robust sales for  
a third straight month in April, many topping expectations, as 
shoppers remained confident about the economic backdrop. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the strong showing should translate into healthy  
profits for the recently ended quarter -- Limited and Ann Taylor, 
among others, have said they will exceed analyst forecasts -- retail 
shares fell sharply on Wall Street Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts noted that because April's sales increases weren't as  
strong as those in preceeding months, investors grew worried that a 
slowdown may be setting in. 
</P>
<P>
	Gap shares tumbled $5.12 1/2 to $64.25 and Wal-Mart fell $2.18 3/4 to  
$42.87 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the underlying tone of business is good,'' said Wayne  
Hood, a retail analyst at Prudential Securities in Atlanta. ``But 
Wall Street doesn't measure things in terms of good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A surprisingly resilient U.S. economy, with low unemployment and  
tame inflation, has kept consumers confident about their personal 
finances and their ability to spend. 
</P>
<P>
	The mood has also been bolstered by the stock market, which  
continued its record-setting pace this week with the Dow Jones 
industrial average crossing the 11,000 mark just amonth after it 
breached 10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most Americans are working and feeling pretty good, and that  
is driving traffic into the stores,'' said Steve Paspal, senior 
retail analyst at Sovereign Asset Management, a subsidiary of John 
Hancock Funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The big winners in April were specialty clothing chains, while  
department stores also fared well, especially discounters such as 
Wal-Mart and Kmart. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest sales data shined despite comparisons with the  
stunning performance of April 1998, when sales jumped 9.5 percent 
from year-earlier levels, according to the Merrill Lynch retail 
index. 
</P>
<P>
	The index, the investment firm's barometer of sales performance  
at department stores and discount chains, was up 2.9 percent in 
April compared with the same month last year. The index rose 8.4 
percent in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Some merchants, including Dayton Hudson and the Gap, were hurt  
by the early Easter holiday this year, which shifted most of the 
holiday buying into March. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite some hints of a slowdown, analysts remained confident  
that retailers would report healthy profit gains for the first 
quarter. Most will begin to release their earnings in the coming 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most retailers have had to make minimum markdowns to push out  
merchandise,'' said Walter Loeb, who runs the retail consulting 
firm Loeb Associates. ``I am very optimistic about this quarter and 
about the spring into summer season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, reported that sales  
from stores open at least a year rose 4.6 percent from a year 
earlier, while total sales rose 11.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales from stores open at least a year, known as same-store  
sales, are considered the most accurate measure of a retailer's 
strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Other retailers' reports:  
</P>
<P>
	--Sears: Same-store sales down 0.9 percent, total sales down 4.3  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kmart: Same-store sales up 5.7 percent, total sales up 7.3  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--J.C. Penney: Same-store department store sales fell 0.2  
percent, same-store sales at Eckerd drugstores rose 7.7 percent, 
total sales rose 6.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dayton Hudson: Same-store sales down 1.3 percent, total sales  
up 2.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Federated: Same-store sales rose 1.5 percent, total sales up  
12.9 percent. Federated's total sales included revenues from the 
Internet and catalog seller Fingerhut, which it acquired in March. 
</P>
<P>
	--May Department Stores: Same-store sales up 7.7 percent, total  
sales up 12.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Limited: Same-store sales up 5 percent, total sales were flat.  
</P>
<P>
	--Gap: Same-store sales up 1 percent, total sales up 21 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	--Ann Taylor: Same-store sales up 10.3 percent, total sales up  
17.5 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
