<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Death Toll Rises After Tornadoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Wearing hand-me-down clothes and driving  
borrowed cars, residents struggled to put their lives back together 
Thursday from the ruins of this week's twisters. The death toll, 
meanwhile, rose to 46 in Oklahoma and Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Kimberly Taylor wore a plaid overshirt, striped T-shirt and blue  
sweatpants as she collected clothes for her six children at a Del 
City church. She laughed at her mismatched outfit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our house was destroyed,'' she said. ``I don't have a car to  
even drive around in. Everything is just borrowed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 3,000 homes and businesses were destroyed in  
Oklahoma. About 1,500 buildings were destroyed in Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	The smell of hamburgers and sauteed onions wafted down one  
ravaged street in Moore, where volunteers served up free meals to 
residents picking through the ruins of their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Bulmer, a pastor at Oakcrest Church of Christ, handed out  
sandwiches, water and gloves to people with nothing left. Some were 
so grateful, they were speechless, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of times we have to insist they take things,'' he said.  
``These are proud people. They're not used to being on the 
receiving end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Incredible stories of survival came from hospital beds Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Angie Todd, her face swollen and bruised, had a broken shoulder,  
a shattered hand and a finger that will probably have to be 
amputated. The 29-year-old woman, her boyfriend and young son 
survived after being pulled from their bathroom and tossed four or 
five houses down the street. 
</P>
<P>
	``I actually remember being in the funnel of the tornado,'' Ms.  
Todd said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the injured died overnight, bringing the number of dead  
from Monday's tornadoes in Oklahoma to 41. Five people died in 
Kansas. About 750 people in Oklahoma and 150 in Kansas were 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The phone at the Oklahoma Medical Examiner's Office continued to  
ring with calls from people worried about relatives unaccounted for 
since the storms. Fifty-four people were on the missing person's 
list Thursday morning, but the number dropped as loved ones were 
located safe and sound during the day, spokesman Ray Blakeney said. 
Searchers have combed devastated neighborhoods with dogs and 
infrared devices. 
</P>
<P>
	James Scarberry, 30, driving a pickup truck lent by a co-worker,  
felt lucky to have found his wallet and ATM card under the bed in 
what was left of his bedroom. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess you don't realize everything you're missing until you  
have to look for it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Masteller stood on top of her house, now 2 feet tall, in a  
T-shirt, jeans and shoes that were obviously too big for her. She 
wore an old pair of flowered-rimmed glasses that her son pulled 
from the rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all I've got,'' she said, tugging at the shirt. ``I  
don't have credit cards. I don't have a checking book. Not even my 
wedding ring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The school system in the suburb of Moore, which lost an  
elementary school and a high school, said classes will resume on 
Monday. The 2,200 displaced students will finish the last two weeks 
of school at a nearby college, another elementary school and an old 
administration building. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms damaged or destroyed the homes of at least 1,500  
students and those of nearly 100 teachers and administrators, 
district spokeswoman Susan Pierce said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel strongly that in a time of crisis, one thing the  
school can offer is routine, stability and structure in the school 
day,'' she said. ``It's important for those students who have 
suffered a great loss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore toured the tornado damage in  
Haysville, Kan., and hugged people who lost their homes. He said 
the Labor Department will spend $5.7 million to help clean up the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims of the storm were remembered Thursday during a ceremony  
at the Oklahoma Capitol to observe the National Day of Prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been through many devastating things,'' Lt. Gov. Mary  
Fallin said. ``This is a time Oklahoma can be revived. It's a time 
when Oklahoma can be renewed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
