<DOCNO> APW19990506.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:42:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UN Gets Sizable Role in Kosovo Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The new peacekeeping plan for Kosovo approved  
by the United States, Russia and six other nations is designed to 
win over Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic while ensuring the 
tormented ethnic Albanian refugees can return to their homes in 
safety. 
</P>
<P>
	It assigns a prominent role to the United Nations, which could  
have an impact on the troops' mission if Russia, China or other 
Security Council members that opposed NATO's air campaign are able 
to limit the weapons the troops carry or the force they can apply 
to protect returned refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said after a  
briefing by State Department and Pentagon officials Thursday that 
the force ``could well not include Americans,'' there seems to be 
little doubt there will be a sizable U.S. contingent, as there is 
helping to keep the peace next door in Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28,000-member force initially planned for Kosovo is now  
considered too small to monitor the postwar resentment that could 
boil over into violence even after most of the Serb troops and 
paramilitary units depart the province. 
</P>
<P>
	The force could expand to 60,000, with a proportionally larger  
U.S. share than the 4,000 considered at the outset. 
</P>
<P>
	That guarantees the Clinton administration will not budge from  
its insistence that the American troops be under the control of 
American commanders. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor is the United States apt to replicate U.N.-run operations in  
Bosnia-Herzegovina that failed to deter civilian atrocities before 
a combination of NATO attacks on the Serbs and a Croatian offensive 
produced the Dayton accords in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	That ``dual-key'' arrangement in which the United Nations shared  
power with NATO slowed and in some cases blocked the troops from 
intervening to stop mayhem against civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger,  
described the security force approved Thursday by the Group of 
Eight foreign ministers as a ``robust presence that would not only 
be able to defend itself but maintain civil order.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The communique issued at the meeting in Bonn, Germany, referred  
merely to ``effective international civilian and security 
presences,'' without any direct reference to NATO itself. 
</P>
<P>
	Troops from Russia, Ukraine and other countries friendly to  
Yugoslavia are likely to be included, and possibly from such NATO 
nations as Greece and Portugal, which have not actively engaged in 
the 6-week-old NATO attacks on the Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States gave ground, as Clinton signaled he was  
willing to do when he declared before going to Germany that he was 
open to negotiate the composition of the force. So did Russia, 
which had opposed armed peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials depicted the agreement reached by the United  
States, Russia, Germany, Britain, France, Canada, Italy and Japan 
as one in which Moscow mostly moved closer to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian line is otherwise.  
</P>
<P>
	Sergey Lavrov, Russia's ambassador to the United Nations, said  
the agreement reflected Russia's long-held call for an 
international presence for Kosovo authorized by the Security 
Council. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am glad that this is now accepted by our Western partners,''  
he told reporters in New York. ``I am sorry that it took them one 
and a half months of bombing to come to the same solution which we 
were offering. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not to say that we are already there. We would still  
have to see how the details of those arrangements could be 
negotiated, and this would require good will on both sides as was 
repeatedly stressed by Russian leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the outset, the Clinton administration spoke in terms of a  
NATO force, then called it a NATO-led force, and then the term 
evolved to a force with NATO at its core. The communique omitted 
even that construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic, meanwhile, has moved from outright opposition to any  
peacekeeping force in Kosovo. His negotiators refused even to 
discuss the concept at talks in Rambouillet, France, in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Under relentless NATO hammering, the Yugoslav president has  
backed down and said he would consider a peackeeeping contingent 
that was unarmed or carried only light weapons. He also insisted on 
keeping 11,000 Serb troops in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has flatly rejected both proposals,  
and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Thursday security 
for ethnic Albanians ``must mean a strong military force with NATO 
at its core.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But with the United States and Russia beginning to close ranks  
on peacekeeping operations, the stage is set for a new diplomatic 
overture to Belgrade. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is due here 
on Friday to meet with Albright and keep the diplomatic wheels 
turning. 
</P>
<P>
	Still to be heard from is Milosevic, who in a preliminary  
reaction Thursday said through state-run media that a political 
settlement was possible after NATO halted its bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Barry Schweid reports on diplomacy for The  
Associated Press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smoltz Best in Majors Since 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- It was a little more than three years ago that  
John Smoltz decided he needed a change. 
</P>
<P>
	So he came up with an offspeed pitch to go along with his 90  
mph-plus fastball and his nasty breaking pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, he's been dominating. Smoltz has won 61 games -- more  
than any other pitcher in the major leagues -- since 1996, the year 
he won the NL Cy Young Award. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Braves right-hander, who turns 32 next week, won his  
ninth straight decision Wednesday in a 12-3 victory over the St. 
Louis Cardinals. He allowed three runs -- two earned -- and five hits 
in seven innings. He also had two of Atlanta's hits and raised his 
batting average to .375. 
</P>
<P>
	``That might have been his worst game of the year. If it was,  
I'll take that the rest of the year,'' manager Bobby Cox said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that I have a changeup, I have a way of slowing the  
hitters down,'' said Smoltz, who is 5-0 and leads the NL with a 
1.69 ERA. ``Everything used to be hard, hard, hard. Now they can't 
look one way. It's been a weapon since I started throwing it, and 
will continue to be a weapon for me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, coming off elbow surgery, Smoltz went 17-3. He is  
17-1 since the 1998 All-Star break, losing only to Houston, 4-3 on 
Aug. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like he's in the hitters' head,'' Atlanta third baseman  
Chipper Jones said. ``Whatever they are looking for, he's throwing 
something else and making them look bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz sometimes seeks out Tom Glavine, who won Cy Young Awards  
in 1991 and 1998, and Greg Maddux, who won the award for four 
straight times from 1992-95. Both have relied heavily on changeups. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pick Glavine's and Maddux's brain about how to throw it,  
when to throw it and how to fix it when I'm throwing it badly,'' 
Smoltz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz has a 151-105 career record. Prior to 1996, he was 90-82;  
since then, he's 61-23. 
</P>
<P>
	``I try not to think about my numbers. I honestly haven't looked  
at my stats this year,'' Smoltz said. ``I just don't want to get 
carried away with what's happening. Right now I feel like I'm in a 
pretty good groove and can't wait for my next start.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
