<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Banking Overhaul Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate on Thursday passed sweeping  
legislation that would lift Depression-era barriers and let banks, 
securities firms and insurance companies get more deeply into each 
other's businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The mostly party-line vote was 54-44 on the bill, which faces a  
likely presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration supports such legislation in  
principle. But in a showdown with Senate Banking Committee Chairman 
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, it has threatened a presidential veto of the 
bill unless there are major changes. They include the removal of 
provisions that Democrats view as an attack on the 1977 Community 
Reinvestment Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think in the end, the president's going to have to decide,  
is he for a financial modernization bill,'' Gramm told reporters 
during the evening vote, which followed 2 1/2 days of debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm said he believed it was possible to work out a compromise  
on the issues of contention. 
</P>
<P>
	Proponents of the financial overhaul legislation, led by Wall  
Street and the insurance industry, maintain it is needed to keep 
the U.S. financial industry competitive in global markets and that 
it would save consumers billions by providing one-stop financial 
shopping. The financial industries have spent millions in recent 
years lobbying for the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The banking industry already has won permission from federal  
regulators in recent years to skirt some of barriers separating 
financial industries that were erected by the 1933 Glass-Steagall 
Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The chances of a presidential veto also were increased Thursday  
when the Senate rebuffed an effort by Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., 
and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., to steer the 
legislation toward the view of Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and 
the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	An amendment proposed by Shelby and Daschle brought to the  
Senate floor a long-simmering debate between the administration and 
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, supported by most 
Republicans, over the best bank corporate structure to allow in 
revamping the financial services laws. It was killed on a 53-46 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin and the administration want to let banks get into new  
kinds of financial activities through subsidiaries of the banks 
themselves, not just through affiliated companies within the same 
parent holding company. That arrangement would increase the power 
of the Treasury's Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, 
regulator of nationally chartered banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan and most Republican lawmakers, on the other hand, want  
to let banks diversify through a holding company. That would expand 
the independent Federal Reserve's role as a regulator. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar financial overhaul bill recently cleared the House  
Banking Committee and is being reviewed by the House Commerce 
Committee, which has given it a lukewarm reception. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, aiming to protect consumers' privacy, the Senate  
overwhelmingly adopted a measure that would make it a federal crime 
for anyone to misrepresent himself to obtain someone's private 
financial data. The vote was 95-2. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure responded to Americans' growing concern over privacy  
in an era of consolidations creating huge financial institutions 
selling everything from checking accounts to mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The action on Gramm's proposal followed a request to Congress by  
President Clinton earlier this week to bolster consumers' financial 
privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans have become increasingly concerned about the issue''  
of privacy, said Sen. Paul Sarbanes of Maryland, the banking 
panel's senior Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer protection measure doesn't go nearly as far as many  
privacy advocates wish. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmund Mierzwinski, consumer program director for the U.S.  
Public Interest Research Group, called it ``a scam and a sham'' and 
a ``substitute for true privacy reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are extremely disappointed in the Senate for calling that  
privacy,'' said Mierzwinski. Among other things, he said, the 
lawmakers should have addressed the issue of affiliated financial 
companies sharing their customers' data with each other. For 
example, in some large financial concerns, insurance operations 
might share customer information with the company's brokerage unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Although almost all senators backed the privacy provision, the  
broader bill was the subject of extensive debate Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., called it ``exactly the wrong bill at  
exactly the wrong time. ... This is moving this country in the 
wrong direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Removing the Depression-era barriers separating banks, brokerage  
firms and insurers would increase the likelihood of future taxpayer 
bailouts of big institutions that fail, Dorgan warned. 
</P>
<P>
	``This orgy of big bank mergers in our country moves now at an  
accelerated pace, unabated.'' he said. He cited recent 
consolidations including those in which banking giant Citicorp 
merged with brokerage-insurer Travelers Group in a deal valued at 
$36.9 billion, NationsBank Corp. and BankAmerica Corp. combined in 
a $41.5 billion marriage, and Banc One Corp. and First Chicago NBD 
Corp. united in a $18.7 billion deal. 
</P>
<P>
	In a setback for the administration Wednesday, the Senate  
defeated, 52-45, an amendment that would have removed the 
provisions related to the community lending law that are opposed by 
the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill exempts small rural banks from the community-lending  
law and makes it harder for the government to use satisfactory 
community-lending ratings as a requirement for banks being allowed 
to expand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
