<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pornography Prosecutions Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stepping up prosecutions of  
pornography-related offenses could reduce crime, say lawmakers and 
anti-pornography activists. 
</P>
<P>
	``Research has shown that pornography contributes to sexual  
assault, including rape and molestation of children,'' Rep. Joe 
Pitts, R-Pa., said Wednesday at a news conference called to observe 
May as Victims of Pornography Month. 
</P>
<P>
	A study of child molesters revealed that 87 percent of those who  
molested girls and 77 percent of those who molested boys admitted 
using hard-core pornography regularly, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The laws are already in place,'' said Rep. John Hostettler,  
R-Ind. ``We need the Justice Department to enforce the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gene McConnell, who lives in Cincinnati, said he started looking  
at pornography at age 12. Although he wasn't proud of it, he didn't 
think he was hurting anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	But he gradually became obsessed with it, he told reporters. And  
he thinks that played a role in his impulsive decision to jump into 
a woman's car and try to rape her years later. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell, now vice president of victim assistance for the  
National Coalition for the Protection of Children &AMP; Families, said 
he broke away from pornography for a while at age 16 after becoming 
overwhelmed with shame for having molested a 14-year-old girl. 
</P>
<P>
	But he returned to it years later after he began having trouble  
in his marriage. Soon afterwards, he began frequenting strip clubs 
and massage parlors and paying prostitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 17 years ago, he forced his way into the woman's car  
and grabbed her by the throat. But then he realized he was about to 
damage another person's life. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fear in her eyes was like being hit with a baseball bat,''  
McConnell said. ``I said, `I'm sorry, I've made a serious mistake,' 
got out of the car and walked away.'' The woman wrote down his 
license plate number and turned him in to police, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've heard thousands of stories from men ... who have similar  
stories to my own,'' he said. ``They may not have taken it to the 
extent that I did, but pornography played a significant role in 
their dysfunctional relationships.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
