<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Removes Trustee From Trust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- A judge has removed from a wealthy trust one of  
the five trustees who was accused of mismanagement and abuse of 
power while overseeing a school for Hawaiian children. 
</P>
<P>
	The ouster of trustee Lokelani Lindsey on Thursday could mark  
the first step toward the complete dismantling of the 
once-untouchable board for the Bishop Estate trust. 
</P>
<P>
	Another state court hearing was scheduled for today concerning  
the fates of all the trustees. The Internal Revenue Service has 
threatened to cancel the estate's nonprofit status if the trustees 
do not resign. 
</P>
<P>
	The trust, created by the 1884 will of Princess Bernice Pauahi  
Bishop to educate ``the children of Hawaii,'' has assets valued at 
up to $10 billion and is the state's largest private landowner. 
</P>
<P>
	The trustees are paid commissions based on the estate's  
investment performance. They now earn more than $1 million each. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Circuit Court Judge Bambi Weil granted a request by  
two other trustees to remove Lindsey. She had no immediate comment 
and her attorney said he would appeal the ouster. 
</P>
<P>
	``The standards to remove a trustee are very high and certainly,  
in our view, the other side never came close to meeting that 
standard,'' attorney David Gierlach said. ``This case is not going 
to go away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindsey was appointed in 1993 to oversee the Kamehameha Schools,  
the estate's sole beneficiary. But she relinquished that authority 
in December 1997 after coming under fire for releasing her own 
report criticizing the test scores of Kamehameha's 3,100 students 
of Hawaiian ancestry. 
</P>
<P>
	That same month, trustees Oswald Stender and Gerard Jervis  
accused Lindsey of being unfit to sit on the board of trustees. 
They claimed she misused trust resources, abused her power and 
mismanaged the schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
