<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dell Opening Nashville Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Dell Computer Corp. plans to construct a  
plant and an office building near Nashville International Airport 
which could bring 3,000 new jobs to the area within the next five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell will open a temporary plant in nearby Lebanon in August and  
start making Dimension computers while the permanent plant is under 
construction, vice chairman Kevin Rollins said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell will have a technical support office in Nashville by  
mid-September and employ 1,000 workers before the end of the year, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to comment on speculation the job tally eventually  
could reach 10,000, except to say ``there's plenty of room to 
grow'' on the 700-acre site. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at our trajectory and the growth rates of our  
business, you can see we are going to need a lot of people and a 
lot of help,'' Rollins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell was created 15 years ago by Michael Dell in a University of  
Texas-Austin dorm room. It is now the world's No. 3 computer 
manufacturer, reporting profits last year of $1.5 billion and sales 
of $18.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell employs 24,000 people in 33 countries, including 17,000 at  
its headquarters in Round Rock, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell's Nashville campus, its first U.S. operation outside Texas,  
will house a 300,000-square-foot plant and a 250,000-square-foot 
office building. Most of the jobs will be for factory, customer 
service and technical work, with salaries ranging from $24,400 for 
entry-level workers to $45,000 for middle managers. 

</P>
</TEXT>
