<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 96.50 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fell today as investors, reacting  
to more signs of a robust economy, grew increasingly concerned 
about interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 96.50 at 10,858.91. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 20.85 at 1,326.46, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 44.24 at 2,490.21. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are increasingly worried that the strong economy will  
reawaken inflation and prompt the Federal Reserve to push rates 
higher. They were especially anxious today to see whether April 
employment figures, to be released Friday, will signal increased 
inflationary pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Remarks by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan didn't help  
the markets much. Although he praised the performance of the U.S. 
economy in recent years, he warned that gains in productivity 
cannot keep inflation at bay forever. 
</P>
<P>
	He warned that the nation's longest peacetime expansion will be  
threatened at some point down the road by the tight labor markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is falling because the few people that are playing  
right now are looking at the risks of higher interest rates,'' said 
Charles White, portfolio manager at Avatar Associates in New York. 
``On the margin, there's a little bit of profit-taking going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks were particularly hard hit by the  
nervousness over interest rates. The discount broker Schwab Corp. 
was down 6 1/8 at 101 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	A jump in bond market yields only added to the uncertainty. The  
Treasury's 30-year bond carried a yield of 5.77 percent, up sharply 
from late Wednesday's 5.70 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the strong economy, many big retailers reported  
their sales soared to better-than-expected levels in April. But 
their stocks were mostly lower, with Wal-Mart falling 2 15/16 to 
42 1/8 and Dayton Hudson slipping 2 5/16 to 62 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a margin of nearly 4  
to 3 on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 591.1 
million shares, down from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 7.53 at 633.01, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 4.15 at 789.64. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
