<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seagram Loses $199M in 3rd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Seagram Co., the media and liquor company, lost  
$199 million in its third quarter as more disappointments at the 
box office wiped out profits in other divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	The company blamed the loss on several poorly performing movies,  
incluing ``EdTV'' and ``Virus.'' Another poor set of movie releases 
in the quarter before that also resulted in lower revenues from 
home video rentals, which kick in several months after theater 
releases. 
</P>
<P>
	The $199 million net loss, which translated to 50 cents per  
share, compared to net profits of $461 million, or $1.32 per share, 
in the same period a year ago. The 1998 results were boosted by a 
one-time $433 million gain on the sale of Time Warner stock and a 
one-time $360 million gain from selling TV properties. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was not as wide as the 54 cents per share estimated by  
Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. Seagram shares 
rose 81 1/4 cents or 1.4 percent to $59.75 on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's operating loss, which does not reflect one-time  
gains or charges, came to $163 million, compared with operating 
income of $47 million a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Not counting the effect of those one-time gains and other  
non-operating factors, the company's cash flow -- a commonly used 
measure for media companies -- declined 20 percent to $135 million 
in the three months ending in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite several hit movies such as ``Shakespeare in Love,'' the  
overall bad box office showing was the latest sign of trouble at 
Seagram's Universal Pictures, which shook up its top management 
late last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagram president and CEO Edgar Bronfman, Jr. said the company  
expects its film operations to post another loss in the next 
quarter, ``and it will be several quarters before our film business 
returns to profitability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other parts of Seagram's operations did well. Cash flow at its  
music business jumped 25 percent as Universal Music Group artists 
garnered 27 Grammy awards. UMG became the world's largest music 
company after acquiring PolyGram last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagram's liquor business, which now makes up about a third of  
the company's revenues, also posted a 25 percent gain in earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Net revenues for the quarter jumped to $3.22 billion from $1.99  
billion. The increase was largely due to the addition of PolyGram. 
If PolyGram had been included in the results a year ago, the 
company would have had revenues of $2.99 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Seagram earned  
$739 million, or $2 per share, a rise of 19 percent compared to 
$622 million, or $1.76 per share in the same period a year ago. 
Revenues also rose 19 percent to $8.79 billion from $7.37 billion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
