<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Privacy Included in Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Aiming to protect consumers' privacy, the  
Senate on Thursday overwhelmingly adopted a measure that would make 
it a federal crime for anyone to misrepresent himself to obtain 
someone's private financial data. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 95-2 for the amendment to sweeping legislation the  
Senate is crafting that would let banks, securities firms and 
insurance companies get more deeply into each other's businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure responded to Americans' growing concern over privacy  
in an era of consolidations creating huge financial institutions 
selling everything from checking accounts to mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The action on the proposal of Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, chairman  
of the Senate Banking Committee, followed a request to Congress by 
President Clinton earlier this week to bolster consumers' financial 
privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans have become increasingly concerned about the issue''  
of privacy, said Sen. Paul Sarbanes of Maryland, the banking 
panel's senior Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm also rebuffed an effort by Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.,  
and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., to steer the 
financial overhaul legislation toward the view of Treasury 
Secretary Robert Rubin and the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	An amendment proposed by Shelby and Daschle brought to the  
Senate floor a long-simmering debate between the administration and 
Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, supported by most Republicans, over 
the best bank corporate structure to allow in revamping the 
financial services laws. It was killed on a 53-46 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate action increased the chances of a presidential veto.  
</P>
<P>
	The consumer protection measure doesn't go nearly as far as many  
privacy advocates wish. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmund Mierzwinski, consumer program director for the U.S.  
Public Interest Research Group, called it ``a scam and a sham'' and 
a ``substitute for true privacy reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are extremely disappointed in the Senate for calling that  
privacy,'' said Mierzwinski. Among other things, he said, the 
lawmakers should have addressed the issue of affiliated financial 
companies sharing their customers' data with each other. For 
example, in some large financial concerns, insurance operations 
might share customer information with the company's brokerage unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Although almost all senators backed the privacy provision, the  
broader bill was the subject of extensive debate Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., called it ``exactly the wrong bill at  
exactly the wrong time. ... This is moving this country in the 
wrong direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Removing the Depression-era barriers separating banks, brokerage  
firms and insurers would increase the likelihood of future taxpayer 
bailouts of big institutions that fail, Dorgan warned. 
</P>
<P>
	``This orgy of big bank mergers in our country moves now at an  
accelerated pace, unabated.'' he said. He cited recent 
consolidations including those in which banking giant Citicorp 
merged with brokerage-insurer Travelers Group in a deal valued at 
$36.9 billion, NationsBank Corp. and BankAmerica Corp. combined in 
a $41.5 billion marriage, and Banc One Corp. and First Chicago NBD 
Corp. united in a $18.7 billion deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Proponents of the financial overhaul legislation maintain it is  
needed to keep the U.S. financial industry competitive in global 
markets and that it would save consumers millions by providing 
one-stop financial shopping. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration supports such legislation in  
principle. But in a showdown with Gramm, it has threatened to veto 
the Senate bill unless there are major changes, notably the removal 
of provisions that Democrats view as an attack on the 1977 
Community Reinvestment Act. 
</P>
<P>
	In a setback for the administration Wednesday, the Senate  
defeated, 52-45, an amendment that would have removed the 
provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm wants to exempt small rural banks from the  
community-lending law and make it harder for the government to use 
satisfactory community-lending ratings as a requirement for banks 
being allowed to expand. 
</P>
<P>
	The privacy amendment takes aim at the practice of pretext  
calling, in which people call employees at banks and other 
businesses and use Social Security numbers to get information about 
bank accounts and other financial data. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Clinton urged Congress to bolster consumer's  
rights when banks and other financial companies seek to share or 
sell information about them. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's proposals include requiring banks and other financial  
institutions to tell consumers when they plan to share or sell 
their personal financial information, and giving consumers the 
power to stop such a transfer. He also wants to restrict any 
sharing of customers' medical information by affiliated companies 
within a financial conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Sens. Connie Mack of Florida and Don Nickles of  
Oklahoma voted against the financial privacy amendment. Freshman 
Sen. Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., is refraining from voting on the 
financial services legislation to avoid a conflict of interest: he 
owns a large stake in the Bank of Montreal, which previously bought 
his family's Illinois bank. He voted present. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
