<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Players Return Home Day Late </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Normally it's no big deal if you oversleep and  
miss your plane. But this week such an incident caused a ruffling 
of diplomatic feathers in the United States and Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	When more than 300 Cubans, including an all-star baseball team,  
took off from Baltimore-Washington International Airport Tuesday 
morning, six of their compatriots missed the flight, allegedly 
because they overslept. 
</P>
<P>
	The six are now back in Cuba, having assured U.S. immigration  
agents on Wednesday that they were eager to go back and were not 
would-be defectors. They arrived 24 hours late and missed the 
celebration in Havana of the Cuban team's 12-6 triumph over the 
Baltimore Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	What troubled the Cuban side was that the immigration officials  
interviewed the Cubans without first communicating with Cuban 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Luis Fernandez, spokesman for the Cuban diplomatic mission here,  
said he first learned of the interviews when a reporter called to 
ask about them hours after the Jamaica Air jet departed. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez, who was at BWI for the departure of the flight, said  
it would be a ``provocation'' for the interviews to have taken 
place without prior communication with Cuban officials. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Cuba would find it ``offensive'' if the six were asked  
whether they were leaving voluntarily. It was not clear, he added, 
whether Cuba would lodge a protest with the State Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Menendez, D-N.J., said in a telephone interview it was  
entirely appropriate that Cuban officials were not notified in 
advance. He noted that Cuba is on a list of countries alleged by 
the State Department to be sponsors of terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	Menendez said the six were interviewed on the jetway before they  
boarded. He said the Immigration and Naturalization Service should 
have found a site more neutral than one where Cuban security agents 
who escorted the group to the airport were nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	All six answered ``no'' to the following questions: Were they  
leaving involuntarily, were they fearful of returning to Cuba and 
was their return forced by coercion, Menendez said. He added that 
he was skeptical about the Cuban claim that the six overslept. 
</P>
<P>
	State and Justice Department officials accept the Cuban  
explanation. 
</P>
<P>
	They are also in agreement with Cuba on another issue: Both  
sides will work to facilitate communications between Rigoberto 
Herrera, the Cuban pitching coach who defected Tuesday morning, and 
his family back in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Herrera, 54, turned up at a Baltimore police station Tuesday  
morning and asked for political asylum. Officials said they expect 
the request to be granted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 11:15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monk Charged With Coffin Vandalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMER, Mass. (AP) -- A monk has been charged with vandalism for  
scratching a cross on the coffin of a 17-year-old boy who died in 
his arms after being struck by a hit-and-run driver. 
</P>
<P>
	The abbot of the small monastic community, which draws its  
traditions from the Eastern Orthodox Church, called it a 
misunderstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Christopher Martel's family said they were appalled  
at what they considered to be the desecration of the boy's casket 
just before it was lowered into his grave. The Martels are Roman 
Catholic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't right,'' said Joshua Martel, 19, a brother. ``I  
don't know in his religion if it's bad or good, but I don't think 
it was right at all to carve on the casket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Scott Goodwin, 41, who goes by the name Father Lazarus,  
pleaded innocent Tuesday to vandalism and wanton destruction of 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't do it to deface or offend at all,'' said William  
Saulnier, Goodwin's abbot. Saulnier said Goodwin also scratched 
``ICXC'' and ``NIKA'' -- Greek letters for ``Jesus Christ 
conquers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin's lawyer, Gregory Hession, said that Goodwin had known  
Christopher Martel and was walking back to his monastery in 
Brimfield when he heard the car strike the boy nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	``The boy literally died in his arms,'' Hession said.  
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin waited until the family members were escorted to their  
vehicles following the graveside service and then used a stone and 
dirt to mark the casket, said Elaine Sansoucy, director of the 
funeral home. 
</P>
<P>
	``It all happened so fast,'' Sansoucy said. ``I yelled, `Stop!'  
and it was over.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
