<DOCNO> APW19990506.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 03:35:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Surge / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Growing expectations that Japan may intensify  
efforts to repair its economy propelled the main Tokyo stock index 
3.59 percent higher today. The dollar rose against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.48 yen in late afternoon, up 0.90 yen from  
late last Friday in Tokyo but below its late New York level 
Wednesday of 120.65 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 599.08 points,  
or 3.59 percent, to 17,300.61 points -- its highest close since 
17,363.74 on Oct. 24, 1997. On Friday, the index lost 240.71 
points, or 1.42 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's rally came on the same day the Tokyo Stock Exchange  
began fully-computerized trading. The 120-year history of floor 
trading ended on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Japan were closed Monday through Wednesday  
for the nation's ``Golden Week'' holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said in Washington on Monday that he  
was determined to ensure a successful revitalization of the 
Japanese economy, which remains mired in its worst recession since 
World War II. Obuchi also held talks with U.S. President Bill 
Clinton at the White House on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are expecting more spending,'' said Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi,  
a strategist at Daiwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshiro Mori, secretary-general of the ruling Liberal Democratic  
Party, has reportedly hinted at the need to increase public 
spending to boost growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must consider holding a session of parliament this autumn  
to handle substantial economic stimulus measures,'' Kyodo News 
service quoted Mori as saying on Monday. Mori is currently on a 
trip to Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said buying from public funds also helped to lead the  
Tokyo market higher in the afternoon session. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 788  
million shares, up from Friday's turnover of 535 million shares. 
Advancing issues outnumbered retreaters 1,069 to 189, with 66 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 44.00 points, or 3.29 percent, to 1,381.12 
points. The TOPIX fell 10.52 points, or 0.78 percent, Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the dollar moved lower slightly from its level on  
Wednesday in New York on lingering expectation that any new 
economic stimulus steps from Japan could help boost its currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said, however, the dollar's losses were pared on  
short-covering after a spokesman for the prime minister expressed 
skepticism about reports on the new public spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Akitaka Saiki, spokesman for Prime Minister Obuchi told  
reporters that he was not sure if the news reports quoting Mori 
were accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 119.83 yen and 120.73 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 130.26 yen, up from  
126.86 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.330 percent from 1.420 percent late Friday, pushing 
its price up to 103.81 yen from 103.35 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
