<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Oklahomans Don't Have Cellars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- You know the image -- the tornado comes and  
Midwesterners head for the root cellar, closing the door over their 
heads and safely riding out the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	In real life, most of the people in the path of the killer  
twisters that swept through ``Tornado Alley'' this week didn't even 
have a basement to hide in. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's deadly tornadoes hit Oklahoma City the hardest, killing  
at least 38. Others died in Kansas, Texas and Tennessee, making 
this the nation's deadliest tornado outbreak since 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	For many parts of Tornado Alley, which stretches from north  
Texas to the Dakotas, safe cellars are from days gone by. 
</P>
<P>
	``In 23 years of building, I've only done one,'' said Tom  
Vorderlandwehr, an Oklahoma City-area home builder. ``It's not 
something that's typical to the area any more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many say the reasons are simple: soil conditions and cost.  
</P>
<P>
	In Oklahoma City much of the soil is red clay, which expands  
when wet and contracts when it dries. Because of the clay, a 
builder constructing a basement must remove twice as much dirt as 
normal and surround the home's concrete walls with more stable 
material. A finished basement can add $30,000 to $40,000 to a 
home's cost, builder Mark Dale said. 
</P>
<P>
	In northern Texas, the soil is a black ``gumbo'' with a wildly  
fluctuating moisture content. Most homes are built above ground, 
either on pier-and-beam foundations or concrete slabs. Storm 
cellars, few and far between, were found in older, rural areas. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kansas, the stable soil means most homes have basements.  
Wichita home builder Quentin Moeder said he never builds a home 
without one. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis George said that even in Oklahoma City's red clay, he can  
dig a cellar for as little as $20 a square foot, though it won't be 
pretty. ``Actually, a basement's about as cheap as putting a garage 
on,'' said George, who runs a backhoe service and builds homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Despain, a home builder and director of the Oklahoma City  
Board of Realtors, said that complacency, not cost, is the issue. 
Oklahoma City has been lulled into a false sense of security, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see, we haven't had very many of these massive storms that  
just swipe everything away,'' Despain said. ``People think they can 
just get in a closet and be safe, and we found out last night that 
you can't. When we have a storm like last night, you've just got to 
be underground to be safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His office manager was left in critical condition after she was  
swept from the bathtub where she was hiding under a mattress and 
was thrown two blocks. Several of the dead from Monday's storms 
were found huddled in bathtubs or under heavy furniture -- the 
places experts say you should go if you don't have a basement. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale said he's installing a lot of storm rooms above ground  
inside new homes, using concrete walls with a steel-reinforced 
ceiling. Texas Tech University in Lubbock has a research center 
looking to make buildings more storm resistant and provides plans 
for reinforcing a bathroom to make it a stronger shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	It takes an extraordinary event like Monday's tornado --  
classified F5, the most powerful -- to change people's habits, 
Despain said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm kind of guessing that if today we advertised basements  
that we'd be busy for the next year building them,'' he said. ``I 
think I'm going to build me one after last night.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
