<HEADLINE> Northwest Flight Attendants Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- After going nearly three years without a new  
contract, the union representing flight attendants at Northwest 
Airlines is mailing strike authorization ballots to members. 
</P>
<P>
	Lack of movement on pension issues in the latest round of talks  
forced the union to seek rank-and-file authorization to order a 
strike against the nation's fourth-largest airline, said Teamsters 
Local 2000 President Billie Davenport. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's just no movement on their part on the pension issue,  
which is our members' number one issue,'' Davenport said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballots will be mailed next week to the union's 11,000 members.  
The flight attendants will vote during a 30-day period. 
</P>
<P>
	No strike could take place at Northwest unless the National  
Mediation Board declares an impasse in the contract negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight attendants would then be barred from striking for 30 days  
and the sides could continue to negotiate during the cooling-off 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest round of talks ended Monday. They are scheduled to  
resume in early June. 
</P>
<P>
	If talks aren't productive, Davenport believes mediator Maggie  
Jacobsen will ask the National Mediation Board to release the sides 
from negotiation. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest spokesman Jon Austin had no comment on the flight  
attendants' move to distribute strike ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest flight attendants with 30 years experience receive  
$1,000 a month in retirement benefits, far below other major 
airlines deals, Davenport said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
