<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Honda Plans Eastern Alabama Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- American Honda Motor Co. Inc. has picked  
eastern Alabama for the site of its third U.S. auto production 
plant and said today it will hire up to 1,500 people to build 
either minivans, sport utility vehicles or both. 
</P>
<P>
	American Honda executive vice president Tom Elliott said the  
plant was vital because sales of light trucks, such as minivans and 
sport utility vehicles, are expected to exceed half of all U.S. 
auto sales by next year. Honda's Odyssey minivan and SUVs are 
strong sellers, Elliott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Government and private groups have committed $102.7 million in  
incentives to purchase the land and get the site ready for 
construction as well as putting together training programs for 
employees. In addition, Honda will receive $55.6 million in tax 
breaks, according to the governor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The $400 million, 1.7 million-square-foot plant is being built  
at the Talladega County community of Lincoln, about 35 miles east 
of Birmingham. Illinois, Georgia and Virginia were reported to also 
have been in the running. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction is to begin in mid-2000 and production is scheduled  
to begin in the spring of 2002. Full capacity is expected to be 
reached in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to vehicle production, the Alabama plant will make  
V6 engines. Honda already makes cars at two plants in Ohio, where 
the company also has an engine plant. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second international automaker to pick Alabama for  
production. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, Alabama offered $253 million in tax breaks and other  
incentives to lure what is now DaimlerChrysler AG to Vance, a 
community about 30 miles west of Birmingham. The first 
Mercedes-Benz plant in the United States now has 1,700 employees 
and makes the M-Class sport utility vehicle. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
