<DOCNO> APW19990506.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 23:55:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Puerto Rico Seeks More U.S. Input </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Puerto Rico's governor and other political  
leaders gave different interpretations of an inconclusive statehood 
referendum last December and said Congress shares the blame for the 
confusion over the island's future. 
</P>
<P>
	In a sometimes heated Senate Energy Committee hearing Thursday,  
several senators demanded that Puerto Ricans take more initiative 
in defining their future options. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing before a packed audience considered the Dec. 13  
referendum on Puerto Rico's future, when 46.6 percent supported 
statehood, 2.8 percent were for either independence or free 
association and a majority 50.3 percent cast their votes for ``none 
of the above.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current commonwealth arrangement, the 3.8 million  
residents of Puerto Rico are U.S. citizens, but they pay no federal 
taxes and cannot vote for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of an enhanced commonwealth status, under which the  
island would receive more political and economic independence, 
claimed that most of the ``none of the above'' voters backed their 
position, which was not on the ballot. ``The people of Puerto Rico 
were unambiguous in their rejection of statehood,'' said Anibal 
Acevedo Vila, president of the Popular Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	He was questioned sharply by Sen. Mary Landrieu, D-La., who said  
a status that would allow Puerto Rico to keep such benefits as $10 
billion a year in federal funding while not accepting new 
responsibilities is ``a false choice because there are no free 
lunches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Pedro Rossello, who supports statehood, said one clear  
conclusion was that the referendum was a rejection of the status 
quo. He said it was up to Congress to draw up a road map that would 
finally give Puerto Ricans a chance to choose their future course. 
</P>
<P>
	Rossello said only Oklahoma was a U.S. territory longer than  
Puerto Rico, which came under U.S. control after the 1898 
Spanish-American War. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruben Berrios Martinez, president of the Puerto Rican  
Independence Party, said Puerto Ricans had rejected statehood in 
referendums in 1993 and 1998 and Congress ``should take 'no' for a 
final answer'' and ``formally declare its willingness to decolonize 
Puerto Rico.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House last year by a one-vote margin passed a bill  
authorizing a Puerto Rican statehood referendum, but the Senate 
never acted, and the December vote was nonbinding. 
</P>
<P>
	There's little momentum in Congress for action this year. Some  
lawmakers are wary of promoting statehood for a Spanish-speaking 
island that is poorer than any of the 50 states, and -- to the 
disadvantage of Republicans -- would probably send Democrats to 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Craig Thomas, R-Wyo., told Rossello that it was up to the  
Puerto Ricans, not Congress, to define their future goals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
