<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Businesses Reel From Tornadoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The deadly tornadoes and storms that hit parts of the Midwest  
and South have had little impact on most national business 
operations, despite disrupting the lives of many employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Several companies with sites in Oklahoma City, the hardest-hit  
region, said it had been business as usual for the most part, with 
employees in other parts of the country able to fill in for local 
interruptions. 
</P>
<P>
	The tornadoes and storms, which began to descend upon the area  
on Monday and continued through the week, left dozens of people 
dead and thousands of homes and businesses destroyed in Oklahoma, 
Kansas, Texas and Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors, America Online and Southwest Airlines are among  
the companies with large operations in Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwest Airlines employs 1,200 people at its Oklahoma City  
reservation center and was forced to shut down that unit all day 
Tuesday so employees could take care of their homes and families. 
</P>
<P>
	``But our eight other reservation centers around the country  
were able to handle the calls,'' said Kristie Kerr, a spokeswoman 
for the Dallas-based airline. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerr said about 26 employees had homes destroyed by the  
tornadoes, and a number of others missed work due to the weather, 
which also forced the cancelation or delay of numerous flights in 
the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwest was collecting food and supplies to send to displaced  
employees and relief organizations. It also was setting up a 
special fund through the company credit union to help raise money, 
Kerr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other major companies with ties to the area also were  
donating much-needed supplies and money to victims and relief 
efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just trying to answer whatever calls come in,'' said  
Shane Boyd, a spokesman for Fleming Cos., a food distribution 
company based in Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has been contacting grocery vendors to help with the  
relief effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about truckloads of products, ultimately dozens  
of truckloads from vendors,'' Boyd said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 10 percent of the 1,200 people who wok at Fleming's  
Oklahoma City headquarters were personally affected by the 
tornadoes, he said. ``We had 20 that lost everything,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, General Motors Corp. said its Oklahoma City assembly  
plant, which manufactures the Chevrolet Malibu and Oldsmobile 
Cutlass, was spared from damage and production would not be 
affected. 
</P>
<P>
	About 110 of its 3,500 employees lost everything, and another 40  
suffered some property losses, according to Frank Lee, president of 
United Auto Workers Local 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The UAW and plant management are providing assistance to the  
victims, and have even taken out full-page newspaper ads to 
advertise a special hotline for affected workers. Both are helping 
find temporary housing for displaced families and have organized a 
``gate drive'' to donate clothing and supplies. On Wednesday, they 
announced a $300,000 donation to the American Red Cross, Salvation 
Army and Feed the Children. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online, which employees 1,200 people at a call center in  
Oklahoma City, said operations weren't affected by the storms. But 
20 employees had homes damaged or destroyed, said Andrew Weinstein, 
a spokesman for the Dulles, Va., company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're working with those employees to help them rebuild,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Premier Parks Inc. of Oklahoma City, which operates 34 theme  
parks around the world, including Six Flags, said neither its 
operations nor employees were affected by the storms. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lucked out. No one was impacted,'' said Jane Braden, a  
spokeswoman. 

</P>
</TEXT>
