<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Down; Wheat Up / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean futures retreated Thursday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade, while wheat edged higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans faced continued pressure from forecasts for  
more favorable planting weather over the next week and on 
increasing deliveries of crops stored from last year's harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were finding some support, however, on talk that corn  
plantings actually may be higher than previously estimated. That 
would mean fewer acres planted to soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by expectations for a large winter  
wheat crop that would increase already ample inventories, but 
finished slightly higher in a late round of position-covering. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1/4 cent to $2.62 1/4 a bushel; July  
corn fell 2 cents to $2.19 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 3/4 cent to 
$1.19 1/2 a bushel; July soybeans fell 1 1/4 cents to $4.83 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle were mixed, while feeder cattle were lower on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Pork futures advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell 0.50 cent to 61.40 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell 0.32 cent to 72.15 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose 1.02 cents to 58.92 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose 1.95 
cents to 59.25 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
