<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 20:15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lobbyists Succeed With Banking Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As a March snowstorm paralyzed the capital,  
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm gathered 40 lobbyists 
for the banking, insurance and securities industries to deliver a 
blunt message. 
</P>
<P>
	If they wanted to eliminate Depression-era barriers prohibiting  
banks, securities firms and insurance companies from delving into 
each other's business, they were ``going to have to do some work,'' 
declared Gramm, R-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months later, on Thursday, the bill passed the Senate, where  
similar legislation had died just six months earlier. The measure 
is the product of a furious lobbying effort that paired a powerful 
committee chairman with cash-flush industries in the battle to 
reverse doubts among lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the legislation was doomed both by concerns it would  
create financial superstores unfriendly to consumers and squabbles 
over whether to repeal requirements that financial institutions 
demonstrate they have made loans to minorities and low-income 
people in their neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing was left to chance this time.  
</P>
<P>
	The American Bankers Association flew in 200 bankers from around  
the country this week to meet with senators. The Securities 
Industry Association's Web site flashed ``Urgent!'' and asked 
visitors to send a form letter to their senators. 
</P>
<P>
	And Merrill Lynch, the brokerage firm, ran weekly newspaper ads  
directed at lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	But what set this lobbying effort apart from the many each year  
in Washington was the extensive role Gramm played in organizing it. 
Since the March gathering, he has continued to meet regularly with 
the lobbyists to discuss their strategy and get progress reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm's office said he got the idea from watching Sen. Robert  
Byrd, D-W.Va., mobilize interest groups in the last Congress to 
successfully amend the surface transportation bill to ensure 
gasoline taxes were spent on highways. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaving nothing to chance, the Texas Republican has done plenty  
of lobbying of his own, buttonholing more than half of his 99 
colleagues to make his own pitch. ``I find that in talking to 
people face-to-face, you tend to get their attention,'' Gramm said. 
</P>
<P>
	Observed Sen. Spence Abraham, R-Mich: ``He's been briefing  
everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm, a longtime supporter of the financial industry, received  
$1.8 million in campaign contributions between 1993 and 1998 from 
banks, savings and loans, insurers and securities firms. That's 
more than any other member of the Senate, according to the Center 
for Responsive Politics. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry has much invested in Congress, doling out $23.3  
million to congressional candidates in the 1998 election cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm's bill would make it easier for banks, securities firms  
and insurance companies to enter each other's business. 
</P>
<P>
	A bank, for example, could write insurance and sell stocks in  
addition to offering savings and checking accounts. A firm that 
sells stocks could also sell insurance and set up its own bank. 
Consumers would shop at, in Gramm's words, ``a supermarket for 
financial services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the bill are not nearly as well-heeled. Three  
consumer groups opposing the legislation -- Consumers Union, the 
Consumer Federation of America, and the U.S. Public Interest 
Research Group -- spent $540,000 to lobby during the last six months 
of 1998. Three industry groups lobbying for the bill -- the American 
Bankers Association, the Securities Industry Association and the 
American Council of Life Insurance -- spent 12 times that, or $6.7 
million, during the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the opponents are making their position known. Some are  
lobbying against a provision in the legislation that exempts small 
banks from the Community Reinvestment Act, which requires financial 
institutions to document how they invest money in all communities 
that they receive deposits from. 
</P>
<P>
	Community development organizations have sent letters telling  
real-life success stories, like that of the New York City 
businesswoman who received a loan to start her company and the 
Mississippi resident who got a home mortgage, all because banks had 
to provide money under the CRA. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one of the things local groups can talk to their  
senators about, these kinds of details about what's happening in 
their communities,'' said Debby Goldberg, a neighborhood 
reinvestment specialist with the Center for Community Change. The 
nonprofit organization works with community groups in low-income 
and minority neighborhoods. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
