<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Beckett's 'Molloy' Has US Premiere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Molloy'' is, finally, an accessible, really  
funny Samuel Beckett theater piece. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of a nearly wordless man feeling the inside of the  
invisible box that holds him, or some other Beckett staging that 
mystifies much of the audience, ``Molloy'' tells a story. Much of 
it is hilarious. 
</P>
<P>
	Compiled from Beckett's 1951 novel, ``Molloy,'' which is the  
first in a trilogy, the play opened Thursday in its American 
premiere at the Irish Arts Center. Irish actor Conor Lovett 
performed Molloy with a gentle speaking voice and skillful timing. 
</P>
<P>
	The theme of ``Molloy'' is stated in the third book in the  
trilogy, ``The Unnamable'': ``You must go on. I can't go on. I'll 
go on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Molloy, an old Irishman, is obviously in terrible physical  
shape, which he describes with sardonic wit. He's even funnier 
relating anecdotes about mishaps that befall him. It is easy to 
recognize yourself or someone you know in some of Molloy's 
experiences. 
</P>
<P>
	First, he talks about visiting his blind, ancient mother; he  
knocks on her skull when he wants her to give him money. 
</P>
<P>
	On the way to see her one day, he rested, leaning forward on his  
bicycle handlebars, which gets him arrested for doing something 
against public decency. He's told that his short, stiff leg is no 
excuse -- there aren't two sets of laws, one for the crippled. 
Having no papers, domicile or occupation and not being sure of his 
name or his mother's address doesn't help his case at the police 
station. 
</P>
<P>
	Released the next afternoon, Molloy gets on his bicycle and  
almost immediately runs over a dog on a leash. A crowd is ready to 
beat him up but the owner, who talks nonstop, says she was taking 
the dog to the veterinarian to be put down. He helps her bury the 
dog and meets her parrot, which, from its language, previously 
belonged to a French sailor and an American sailor. 
</P>
<P>
	As Beckett was wont to write, Molloy also describes his private  
parts and bodily functions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lovett and director Judy Hegarty compiled the one-act play,  
which is presented by the Gare St. Lazare Players. After an 
intermission, the Irish Arts Center shows a film, ``Waiting for 
Beckett.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Molloy'' has been on tour since its debut in London in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baltimore Set To Demolish Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Baltimore has settled on a plan to demolish  
Memorial Stadium next year to make way for a 446-unit senior 
housing development and a recreation center. 
</P>
<P>
	City Housing Commissioner Daniel P. Henson III announced the  
decision on Wednesday, ending some three years of debate about the 
fate of the abandoned, 46-year-old stadium and its 30 acres of 
prime real estate. 
</P>
<P>
	Completed in 1953, the northeast Baltimore stadium has been  
vacant since Dec. 14, 1997, when the Baltimore Ravens played their 
last football game there. The team moved across town to a $223 
million stadium south of the baseball park at Camden Yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Memorial Stadium was once the heart of Baltimore's sports  
universe. John Unitas threw his final touchdown pass for the 
Baltimore Colts there. It's where the Orioles clinched their second 
World Series championship, and Frank Robinson ripped a home run 
completely out of the ballpark -- the only player to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember the first time I went to watch a football game at  
Memorial Stadium, when I was 12 or 13 years old,'' Henson told The 
(Baltimore) Sun. ``But all of us recognize that this is a building 
that is going to fall down on us at some point, and we need to let 
it go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plans for the senior citizens' housing project, which Mayor  
Kurt L. Schmoke talked about during his weekly news conference 
Thursday, represent a victory for community groups that lobbied for 
the recreation center and housing. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents opposed two alternative developments -- a high-tech  
center and a retail complex -- fearing they would bring traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	The nonprofit Govans Ecumenical Development Corp. (GEDCO) will  
have until Nov. 8 to obtain financing for the $43 million project 
and conduct a study to convince the city that there is enough 
demand among senior citizens for housing, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	No city money will be used for the project.  
</P>
<P>
	If the developer clears these hurdles, the city will sell some  
of the land to the developer and demolish the stadium in early 
2000. The state has committed $10 million to help tear down the 
structure. 
</P>
<P>
	State Comptroller William Donald Schaefer said Thursday the  
decision should have been put on hold. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not fair for the current administration to saddle the  
state or the next mayor with decisions as important as these,'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
