<DOCNO> APW19990506.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Gets Steele Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- Julie Hiatt Steele's trial on charges of  
obstructing the independent counsel's investigation of the 
president moved swiftly to the jury Thursday after her lawyers 
declined to call any witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The three days of prosecution witnesses were dominated by the  
testimony of Kathleen Willey, a former White House employee whose 
allegation of an unwanted sexual advance by President Clinton was 
broadcast nationally last year. Ms. Steele is charged with making 
false statements to Kenneth Starr's investigators that did not 
corroborate Mrs. Willey's story. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton denied Mrs. Willey's account under oath when it was  
raised in a deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment 
lawsuit. A spokesman said the White House would have no comment on 
the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyers presented the case as one woman's word  
against another's. They accused Mrs. Willey of past lies and 
assailed her failure to remember clearly what she contends was her 
first conversation with Ms. Steele about the alleged incident, just 
hours after it happened in November 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele told investigators that Mrs. Willey first told her  
about the encounter with Clinton more than three years afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are only two people who know what happened between  
Kathleen Willey and Julie Hiatt Steele,'' defense attorney Nancy 
Luque said in closing arguments. ``You heard from Kathleen Willey. 
She doesn't remember.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the trial opened, Ms. Steele's defense team told jurors she  
would testify on her own behalf, but that plan was scrapped. 
</P>
<P>
	After the prosecution rested Thursday, defense lawyers asked  
U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton to dismiss all four charges 
against her -- three counts of obstruction of justice and one of 
making false statements in an FBI interview. They argued that her 
statements, true or not, weren't material to either Starr's 
investigation or the Jones sexual harassment lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	When Hilton declined, Luque announced she would rest her case.  
Jury deliberations began at 2 p.m. EDT. At one point jurors sent a 
question to the judge; he did not disclose publicly what it asked. 
Jurors quit for the day after 3 1/2 hours of deliberation. 
</P>
<P>
	Closing arguments began with prosecutor Stephen Binhak reminding  
jurors that Ms. Steele told investigators she first heard about the 
1993 Clinton-Willey encounter when Mrs. Willey called in March 1997 
and asked her to lie to a Newsweek reporter to back up her story. 
</P>
<P>
	Binhak said records show that call from Mrs. Willey's car phone  
lasted ``one measly minute.'' It would have been impossible for 
Mrs. Willey to relate the story of the alleged sexual advance and 
convince Ms. Steele to lie in that amount of time, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My grandmother didn't go to college, but she had a word for  
that: baloney,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Binhak also emphasized that three one-time friends of Ms. Steele  
testified that she said she had learned of Mrs. Willey's story 
before 1997 -- and that as investigators closed in Ms. Steele tried 
to persuade each of these people that she had not told them the 
story. Two of the witnesses said they were told about the incident 
before 1997. The third, a local TV producer, said Ms. Steele told 
him in 1997 she had learned about it shortly after it happened in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Luque said that Ms. Steele simply had a ``disagreement'' in  
recollection with the three witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Mrs. Willey who ``didn't tell the truth,'' she argued.  
</P>
<P>
	``She didn't tell the truth to the independent counsel. She  
didn't tell the truth to the FBI,'' Luque said. ``So ... why is 
Julie Hiatt Steele here?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luque said it ``defies logic, defies common sense'' that Ms.  
Steele would lie since she stood to make more money by supporting 
Mrs. Willey's headline-grabbing account. Ms. Steele sold 
photographs of Mrs. Willey and Clinton to three media companies for 
a total of $15,500. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was sitting on a gold mine ... simply for corroborating  
Mrs. Willey,'' Luque said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor David Barger opened the trial by saying Ms. Steele  
had betrayed a friend and violated the rule of law. 
</P>
<P>
	In closing, Luque told the jury that the opposite was the case,  
that Mrs. Willey ``betrayed her friends'' and that ``Ken Starr 
betrayed the rule of law'' by bringing the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Barger countered that Ms. Steele had been given the opportunity  
to tell the truth three different times and ``she could have come 
clean'' to avoid prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutors ``want to be fair,'' he told the jury.  
</P>
<P>
	In Richmond, Va., a three-judge appeals court panel ordered  
Hilton to reconsider his decision to keep some documents in the 
Steele case secret -- including, apparently, the results of a lie 
detector test for Mrs. Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilton denied a request by news organizations, including The  
Associated Press, to unseal documents submitted in secret by 
Starr's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyer for Susan McDougal, in whose recent criminal trial  
Ms. Steele testified, said that Mrs. Willey flunked a polygraph 
examination. Steele's lawyers have said only that lie detector 
results are an issue for one of Starr's witnesses in the Steele 
case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
