<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Would Pressure FCC on Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill that would speed up the Federal  
Communications Commission's review of telecommunications and media 
mergers was approved today by a Senate panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Judiciary Committee's antitrust subcommittee on a  
voice vote sent the measure to the full committee for 
consideration. The bill would set deadlines for the FCC to decide 
merger applications. 
</P>
<P>
	For mergers valued at more than $15 million, the FCC would have  
180 days after an application is filed to issue a decision. The 
application is deemed approved without conditions if the FCC 
doesn't act by the end of that period. 
</P>
<P>
	A majority of the FCC's five commissioners, however, can extend  
that deadline by 60 days. But they can seek an extension only once 
per merger. 
</P>
<P>
	For smaller mergers, the FCC would have 90 days to act, or the  
application is approved. The FCC, with majority approval, could get 
another 30 days to issue a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	To become law, the measure still would have to be approved by  
the Senate and House, and signed by the president. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 467  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
