<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Nears Bankruptcy Bill Passage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House, seeking to stem rising personal  
bankruptcies, on Wednesday moved toward passing legislation pushed 
by credit card companies that would make it tougher for people to 
erase their debts. 
</P>
<P>
	The bipartisan bill has solid Republican support but has split  
the Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has objected to the bill without specifically  
threatening a veto. The administration especially has criticized 
the measure's creation of a ``means test,'' based on debtors' 
income, to determine whether they must gradually repay their debts 
or erase them entirely while under Bankruptcy Court protection from 
creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and Rep.  
John Conyers of Michigan, the panel's senior Democrat, tried to 
soften the means test provision, which uses the Internal Revenue 
Service's living expense standards to help determine how much 
debtors can repay. But their efforts were rebuffed in a 184-238 
vote against their amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting the massive lobbying push of the credit card companies,  
Hyde quipped during debate on the House floor, ``Let me pay my 
respects to the creditor lobby: They are awesome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conyers said the bill ``is bad for women, children, working  
Americans ... it is good for the credit card industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Big bank-owned credit card networks, notably Visa and  
MasterCard, and retail-business groups say their losses from 
forgiven debts in bankruptcy have forced them to raise interest 
rates for consumers who handle credit responsibly. 
</P>
<P>
	But consumer groups, unions, civil rights groups and bankruptcy  
attorneys maintain the legislation favors corporate profits over 
the needs of families struggling with debt who need a fresh start. 
They insist that the credit card companies share the blame by 
flooding consumers with mailed solicitations to entice them into 
easy credit. 
</P>
<P>
	By voice vote, the lawmakers adopted an amendment requiring  
credit card companies to clearly disclose their fees for late 
payments and how long it would take customers to pay off balances 
by making only minimum monthly payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies also would have to clearly reveal the expiration  
dates of introductory ``teaser rates'' and the higher interest 
rates replacing them. And the same disclosures would have to be 
made in offers for credit card accounts made over the Internet, 
which have attracted an estimated 7.8 million people in the last 
five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents also maintain that the bill, by barring certain credit  
card debts from being erased in bankruptcy, would force single 
mothers and children owed support by bankrupt fathers to compete 
with credit card companies in collecting debts. 
</P>
<P>
	But the measure's sponsors, led by Reps. George Gekas, R-Pa.,  
and Jim Moran, D-Va., say it gives highest priority among debts to 
child support and alimony payments, putting them ahead of credit 
card debt and other obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, bankruptcy overhaul legislation cleared the  
Banking Committee last month and went to the full chamber, but the 
key issue of providing information to credit card users remained 
unresolved. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers are responding to a rising tide of personal  
bankruptcies, which reached a record 1.4 million last year despite 
the strong economy, up more than 300 percent since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase is being driven by ``bankruptcies of convenience,''  
said Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va., a sponsor of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second straight year the House enacted bankruptcy  
overhaul legislation. Last year, the administration threatened to 
veto a House-passed bill and the Senate adjourned without voting on 
the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislative action has come amid an ongoing lobbying blitz  
by credit card companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Visa USA Inc. increased its lobbying bill to $3.6  
million from $900,000 in 1997, according to recent disclosure 
reports. MasterCard International's lobbying expenses rose to $1.8 
million from $430,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Chapter 13 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, people must repay  
their debts according to a court-ordered plan. Credit card 
companies complain that too many people take shelter under the more 
lenient Chapter 7, which erases debts, when they could afford to 
restructure debts under Chapter 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
