<HEADLINE> Oriole Bird Mascot Injured by Fan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- One of the Baltimore Orioles' mascots is out of  
action after a run-in with a fan, a team spokesman said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	John Crownapple, one of three people who dress up as The Bird,  
was injured when he was pushed off an outfield wall Tuesday night 
during the game against the Chicago White Sox, team spokesman John 
Maroon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore police said he suffered a broken ankle and had bone  
chips loosened in the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Louis Vitaglyano, 43, of Philadelphia was arrested and charged  
with second-degree assault and reckless endangerment, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses told officers that Vitaglyano shoved The Bird off the  
roof of the groundskeeper's shed at Oriole Park in the ninth inning 
as he was leading cheers in front of the stands. Crownapple fell 
onto the field, about 10 feet below. Maroon said Crownapple did not 
provoke the attack. He said the mascot's pranks against opposing 
players and mascots are nonviolent. 
</P>
<P>
	Crownapple is recovering at home. Maroon said the team is  
waiting to find out when he will be able to work again, but he 
cannot be replaced because of his specialized training and the 
difficulty of his routines. 
</P>
<P>
	Maroon said the other two people trained to portray the Orioles'  
mascot were filling in for Crownapple at games. But the team has 
canceled other public appearances by The Bird. 
</P>
</TEXT>
