<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Timing Gets Brothers New Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Two brothers convicted of  
second-degree murder in a 1995 shooting will get a new trial 
because the judge held court on a Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Criminal Court Judge Doug Meyer ignored state law prohibiting  
courtroom proceedings on Sunday, the state Court of Criminal 
Appeals ruled unanimously, dismissing the brothers' convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers, Debiasi and Dewayne King, remained in custody  
after the appeals court April 30 ruling. An attorney for one of the 
brothers said he had no immediate plans to seek release. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1996 trial, the sequestered jury indicated they would  
like to continue through the weekend instead of taking a break, the 
appeals court wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer said he was aware of the Sunday court prohibition but  
noted ``society had become much more tolerant of nonessential 
functions being performed on that day and decided to proceed,'' the 
court wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban must be obeyed unless the General Assembly or the state  
Supreme Court change the law, the appeals court wrote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
