<DOCNO> APW19990506.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 06:32:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Ministers Meet Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- On the sidelines of President Clinton's  
visit, foreign ministers from western powers and Russia met today 
seeking agreement on the outline of a Kosovo peace plan that could 
be endorsed by the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting Russia, which opposes NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia,  
into such a common front could increase diplomatic pressure on 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to settle on NATO's terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow, a traditional Serb ally, appears to be moving toward  
supporting a key alliance demand: a NATO-led international force to 
secure the return of Kosovo refugees. Milosevic has so far refused 
to accept such an armed international force. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he was optimistic there will be an accord at the  
Group of Eight meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're getting closer,'' he said in an interview with  
European television correspondents in Frankfurt. ``I wouldn't be 
surprised if it happens today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic has shown no sign of giving in, but some of his  
maneuvers prompted speculation of a Yugoslav diplomatic offensive. 
</P>
<P>
	With Belgrade's permission, Kosovo's most prominent ethnic  
Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova, flew to Rome on Wednesday. Last 
weekend, Milosevic allowed three captured U.S. soldiers to be 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's meeting of G-8 foreign ministers at a government guest  
house outside Bonn is the first since NATO's assault began March 
24. 
</P>
<P>
	Represented are the United States, Britain, France, Germany,  
Italy, Japan and Canada -- the world's leading industrial countries 
-- and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met separately before the  
main session with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and his 
German counterpart, Joschka Fischer. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the talks, Western leaders praised mediation efforts by  
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, who has met twice with Milosevic 
since airstrikes began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not least because of Chernomyrdin's mission, the key political  
positions have come closer together,'' German Chancellor Gerhard 
Schroeder said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Russia ``has shown an  
increased interest'' in helping solve the Kosovo crisis over the 
past two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Ivanov said before leaving Moscow that no quick  
solution was in sight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not optimistic about a breakthrough,'' the ITAR-Tass news  
agency quoted him as saying. ``But if there is the slightest 
progress, this will be important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An aim of the talks is a U.N. mandate for any military force to  
protect ethnic Albanian refugees returning to Kosovo and to 
establish an interim administration for the Yugoslav province, Cook 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some European governments, including Germany's, are also under  
pressure to pursue diplomacy to head off growing antiwar sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The military means we are using are not an end in themselves,  
they are the means for a single purpose: ending the killing in 
Kosovo,'' Schroeder said in a speech to parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, on a two-day trip to Germany to meet U.S. military  
personnel involved in the airstrikes on Yugoslavia, stressed that 
the bombing will continue until Milosevic gives in. 
</P>
<P>
	But he softened his rhetoric this week after meeting  
Chernomyrdin, offering both a pause in NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia 
and negotiations on a U.N.-backed peace force for Kosovo if 
Milosevic starts pulling out his forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
