<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Track Reopens With NASCAR Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- With flags at half staff, Lowe's Motor  
Speedway returned to the business of racing, this time without any 
spectators in the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	More than two dozen Winston Cup teams showed up for a test  
session Wednesday, four days after three spectators were killed and 
eight injured when struck by debris from a crash in an Indy Racing 
League event at the track. 
</P>
<P>
	The track had remained silent following Saturday night's  
accident, and speedway officials said they discussed calling off 
the two-day Winston Cup test booked by General Motors for its 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``We considered a variety of factors and decided to go ahead  
with the test, primarily because it is a non-spectator event,'' 
track spokesman Jerry Gappens said. ``We felt it was in everybody's 
best interests to move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With no fans sitting in the seats during the private test  
session, the Winston Cup drivers went out on the track early in the 
afternoon and began turning laps at about 180 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL drivers were going about 35 mph faster than that  
Saturday night when a three-car crash sent a tire and suspension 
parts flying into the stands above the 1.5-mile, high-banked 
trioval. 
</P>
<P>
	The fatal wreck occurred near the exit of the fourth turn, and  
20 minutes into Wednesday's practice, Michael Waltrip crashed in 
almost the same spot. His Chevrolet spun violently through the 
third turn and slammed off the fourth-turn retaining wall, about 
200 yards from the site of the deadly crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip wasn't injured, but it served as an eerie reminder of  
recent events. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our hearts go out to the folks who lost their lives and their  
families and the people who were injured,'' three-time Winston Cup 
champion Jeff Gordon said as he prepared to go out for his first 
test run. ``But we know that Charlotte Motor Speedway, the IRL and 
really everybody in motorsports is going to come together and do 
whatever they can to improve the situation to make sure that 
doesn't happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night's accident was the second in nine months  
involving multiple fan fatalities in U.S. racing. Both crashes 
occurred during Indy-car races when wheels and suspension parts 
snapped off cars and flew into stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel pretty fortunate in Winston Cup,'' Gordon said. ``With  
NASCAR rules, the way our cars are built, things like that are a 
little less likely to happen. But still we want to prevent anything 
like that. We want to keep the fans safe, we want to keep the 
drivers safe and make it a fun event for everybody to enjoy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only one of the eight injured people still hospitalized,  
Haley McGee, 9, of Conover, N.C., remained in critical condition at 
Carolinas Medical Center in Charlotte with brain and lung injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	For the second day in a row, speedway president H.A. ``Humpy''  
Wheeler attended a funeral for one of the victims, this time going 
to a service for Randy Pyatte, 21, of Connelly Springs, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Back at the track, engineers and architects moved closer to  
finalizing plans to modify the catch fence that surrounds the 
speedway. The fence now rises 15 feet above the track and is topped 
by a 35-inch-long canopy positioned at a 45-degree angle. Gappens 
said the speedway is looking at adding to both the height of the 
fence and the length of the canopy. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
