<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bohn Leads ABC Bowling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Parker Bohn III, looking to improve on  
last year's second-place finish, stayed undefeated in the 96th 
annual American Bowling Congress Masters tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Bohn, who made history at last year's finals by rolling a  
televised perfect 300 game, defeated Charlie Tapp and Chris Barnes 
in the first two rounds of the double-elimination format. The 
19-time Professional Bowlers Association champion is looking for 
the first major victory of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Also undefeated was last week's tournament winner, Eric Forkel.  
The Tucson, Ariz., resident defeated Mike Wolfe and John Gant to 
remain in contention. 
</P>
<P>
	Also left in the winner's bracket were 1997 ABC Masters champion  
Jason Queen of Decatur, Ill., and Doug Kent, Canandaigua, N.Y., the 
1991 champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying leader Barnes was 2-1 and alive in the losers'  
bracket. Also still in the loser's bracket was Hall of Famer Pete 
Weber, who owns 24 PBA titles, but has yet to win this event. 
</P>
<P>
	The field of 64 has been trimmed to 32 finalists.  
Double-elimination match play continues Friday afternoon and 
concludes at night, with the top four finalists advancing to 
Saturday's championship round. Top prize is $40,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
