<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Slip Early / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar edged higher by late morning Friday  
despite some selling pressure following comments from U.S. Federal 
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. Japanese stocks slipped. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.56 yen at midday trading, up 0.08 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level 
Wednesday of 120.50 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average fell 122.45 points, or 0.71 percent, to  
17,178.16 points at the end of the morning session. On Thursday, 
the index rose 599.08 points, or 3.59 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On the foreign exchange market, the dollar initially inched down  
on Greenspan's comments Thursday that the U.S. jobless rate 
couldn't continue without leading to inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	That started a selloff in the U.S. bond market as investors  
demanded higher rates of return as protection against inflation. 
This in turn pushed down the dollar by raising concern that it 
could signal a trend away from U.S. assets, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar later drifted higher, although there was no major  
market-moving news ahead of the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 129.98 yen, down  
slightly from 130.00 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, investors took profits after Thursday's big  
jump in which the market registered its highest close since Oct. 
24, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshihiko Kuroichi, a general manager at Meiko Securities said  
the Tokyo market ``went too high Thursday, this morning we are 
seeing some market correction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 0.96 points, or 0.07 percent, to 1,380.16 
points. The TOPIX rose 44.00 points, or 3.29 percent, Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed  
down 8.59 at 10,946.82 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.335  
percent from 1.330 percent late Thursday, pushing its price down to 
104.13 yen from 104.18 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
