<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Plan Drafted To End Kosovo Conflict  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Russia and the major Western powers set  
aside their differences over NATO airstrikes today and drafted a 
joint plan to end the Kosovo conflict. The plan includes the 
deployment of an international force to keep the peace after the 
withdrawal of Yugoslav forces. Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic responded by reiterating his demand that Western powers 
stop airstrikes as a first step toward reaching any settlement. 
Milosevic did not reject the plan outright or refer to the call for 
foreign troops. 

</P>
<P>
	Bombing Continues in Balkans  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Round-the-clock NATO bombing  
continued in Yugoslavia today. According to local reports, a NATO 
missile slammed into a residential area in Serbia's second largest 
city and allied jets struck a chemical plant. NATO also struck 
across Kosovo, where Serb forces continue to battle the ethnic 
Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army. The attacks came as foreign 
ministers from Russia and the major Western powers, meeting in 
Germany, agreed on a draft plan for ending the Kosovo conflict, 
including the deployment of an international force to keep the 
peace after the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces. 

</P>
<P>
	Bank Overhaul Bill Passes Senate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate tonight passed legislation that  
would lift Depression-era barriers and let banks, securities firms 
and insurance companies get more deeply into each other's 
businesses. The mostly party-line vote was 54-44 on the bill, which 
faces a likely presidential veto. Proponents of the financial 
overhaul legislation, led by Wall Street and the insurance 
industry, maintain it is needed to keep the U.S. financial industry 
competitive in global markets and that it would save consumers 
billions by providing one-stop financial shopping. 

</P>
<P>
	House OKs US Military Funding Boost  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House tonight approved $13.1 billion for  
the fight with Yugoslavia and to buttress U.S. forces around the 
globe. The measure would more than double the $6.05 billion 
President Clinton requested last month to back the NATO air war 
through September and care for hundreds of thousands of refugees 
who have fled Kosovo. The additions include $1.1 billion to buy 
missiles and bombs, $1.3 billion for spare parts, $1.8 billion to 
improve troops' pay and pensions, and $1.1 billion to modernize 
military bases, mostly in Europe. 

</P>
<P>
	Major Jail Break Staged in Mexico  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Two hundred state police swarmed through the  
hills of southern Chiapas state today in search of dozens of 
prisoners who staged a mass escape. The mass escape began Tuesday 
after rioting broke out at the 245-inmate prison. Escapees 
overpowered guards, stole firearms and used two female prison 
employees as hostages. They were later released. Local reports say 
five of the 77 escapees have been recaptured. The prison reopened 
in 1998 after being partially destroyed by leftist rebels. The 
rebels freed 180 inmates from the facility in that attack. 

</P>
<P>
	Beer Ad in Gay Mag Draws Response  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A Budweiser advertisement showing two men  
holding hands in a free magazine for gays and lesbians has drawn so 
much response that Anheuser-Busch set up special hotlines to handle 
calls. The ad for Bud Light in the April 22 issue of EXP magazine 
says ``Be Yourself and Make It a Bud Light,'' and carries a tagline 
saying ``Proud Sponsor of the St. Louis PrideFest '99.'' PrideFest 
is a gay and lesbian festival held in June. 

</P>
<P>
	Viacom Files To Float Chain Shares  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Five years after buying Blockbuster, Viacom has  
applied for permission to sell shares in the video rental company 
in order to focus on its main businesses of making movies and TV 
shows. Viacom filed an application with the Securities and Exchange 
Commission today to make an initial public offering in Blockbuster 
Inc., the nation's leading home video chain with 6,500 stores 
nationwide. Viacom runs the MTV, VH1 and Nickelodeon networks. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Open Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks opened mixed Friday as the Nikkei shed  
19.08 points to 17,281.53 in early trading. On Wall Street today, 
the Dow industrials finished at 10,946.82, down 8.59. The 
technology-laden Nasdaq was down 62.16 at 2,472.28. 

</P>
<P>
	Former Cowboy Found Dead in Car  
</P>
<P>
	PLANO, Texas (AP) -- Mark Tuinei, a former Dallas Cowboys  
offensive lineman who helped them win three Super Bowl titles, was 
found dead in his car this morning. He was 39. Police said a friend 
who had been told to go to Tuinei's house to check on him found 
Tuinei unconscious in a vehicle. Efforts to revive him failed. The 
cause of death was not immediately known. Police said foul play, 
alcohol or drugs were not believed to be involved. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  

</P>
</TEXT>
