<DOCNO> APW19990506.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> INS `Hubbing' Plan Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Immigration and Naturalization Service has  
proposed grouping illegal immigrants by nationality and shipping 
them to detention ``hubs'' in Texas and Chicago to await 
deportation hearings. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the proposal is racist and would demoralize  
immigrants, leaving them hundreds of miles from their families and 
support services they will need if they choose to fight 
deportation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost like the INS has forgotten they're people and not  
packages,'' said Rep. Luis Gutierrez, D-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The INS says the plan would be a cost-effective and efficient  
way to process detainees. Currently, illegal immigrants awaiting 
deportation are generally jailed in whatever part of the country 
they are arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan would encompass the 18 states in the agency's central  
region, relocating illegal Mexican, Central American and Caribbean 
immigrants to separate facilities in Texas. All other immigrants -- 
those from Europe, Asia and Africa -- would be shipped to Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The INS says the plan is open to revision, although the agency  
would like to implement it early this summer. Detractors -- 
including the Congressional Hispanic Caucus -- believe the plan 
should be scrapped. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutierrez said he's concerned about immigrants' due process  
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do they ship your lawyer with you? Your witnesses? Your  
documents? All of your support network so you can have a fair 
hearing?'' he asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan, an illegal immigrant from Honduras who is picked  
up in a workplace raid in Indiana would be sent to Dallas to await 
deportation or a hearing before an immigration judge. Today, such a 
case would be handled at the nearest INS facility, with the 
immigrant most likely detained at a county jail that contracts with 
the INS. 
</P>
<P>
	The INS says many detainees -- there are about 4,300 in the  
central region -- are convicted criminals who already have their 
deportation orders. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want these people near where we can quickly move them to  
their home country,'' said Brian Perryman, the director of the 
INS's district office in Chicago. ``A very small percentage of them 
are going to prevail even on appeal. Most of them are going out.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
