<DOCNO> APW19990506.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 09:15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Okla., Kansas Assess Tornado Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- In her debris-littered front yard,  
7-year-old Megan Varva leaped across chunks of concrete and wood 
like a gazelle on an obstacle course. 
</P>
<P>
	``My outfit is new,'' she said proudly, tugging at her  
pink-and-white striped shorts set. ``My mom said I'm going to be 
getting about a new outfit a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Megan's new wardrobe isn't a luxury. Her old clothes, like much  
of her neighborhood, lay twisted in the dirt after Monday's deadly 
tornadoes in Oklahoma and Kansas. The toll in the two states rose 
to 46 today with the deaths of three people overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to go in there,'' the first-grader said of what  
little was left of her house. ``It isn't nice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many in the twister-scarred southern Plains would agree. Their  
homes are now nothing more than a jagged nest of splintered wood, 
mangled furniture, shattered glass -- and broken dreams. 
</P>
<P>
	The big orange ``U'' spray painted along a wall of 9-year-old  
Sara and 5-year-old Rebecca Johnson's home in Haysville, Kan., said 
it all: Uninhabitable. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 3 inches of rain have poured in through the roof. The  
house must be inspected for structural damage before Dave Johnson 
and his daughters can even think of returning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just picking up the pieces,'' Johnson said Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Clifford Cunningham, 24, seemed to see a silver lining today as  
he surveyed the damage to the home where he lived with his mother 
and sister. ``This house was old anyway. At least I don't have to 
mow the yard now,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	All around Oklahoma City, cars -- some with smashed windows --  
lined up at police and National Guard checkpoints as families came 
to dig through the debris before an 8 p.m. curfew. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheryl and John Molsbee drove slowly past mounds of debris that  
obliterated neighborhood landmarks before finally pulling up to 
their brick-and-frame home. It no longer had a roof. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's worse than I thought,'' said John Molsbee.  
</P>
<P>
	Three injured people died overnight in hospitals, raising the  
death count to 41 in the deadliest tornado to hit Oklahoma since 
1947, said Ray Blakeney of the state Medical Examiner's Office. At 
least 748 people were injured. Blakeney said his office had 55 
missing person reports today, down from the 100 that were 
unaccounted-for Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the dozens of missing persons reports, John Long, chief  
of the public education office for the Oklahoma City Fire 
Department, said he didn't expect the fatality count to grow by 
that much. Rescuers have made at least three searches of each 
damaged home. 
</P>
<P>
	The tornadoes Monday also killed five in Kansas and injured  
nearly 150 people there. 
</P>
<P>
	More twisters swarmed across parts of Texas and Arkansas on  
Tuesday, killing one person. And late Wednesday, strong winds were 
blamed for several deaths in Tennessee as storms destroyed homes in 
dozens of counties and temporarily shut down Nashville 
International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	The damage estimate has been placed at more than $500 million in  
Oklahoma and more than $140 million in Kansas, where 1,129 
buildings were destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	A disaster housing program through the Federal Emergency  
Management Agency will provide rental assistance for up to 18 
months, said Ben Frizzell of the Oklahoma Office of Civil Emergency 
Management. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those trying to get their lives together was Calvin  
Waters, a sheet metal worker in Haysville whose home was heavily 
damaged. He spent a second day trying to clear the debris, patch 
holes in the roof and mop up. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters called himself fortunate. He was shaken by the deaths of  
a woman and her month-old baby near his home -- two people he didn't 
know. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always think a child should get a chance to grow up,'' he  
said. ``If you have to take two people, don't take a baby child. 
Take me, I'm 44 years old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has authorized emergency disaster declarations  
for both Oklahoma and Kansas, paving the way for federal emergency 
funds for home and business owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Anderson will likely need both forms of aid. Before a  
tornado destroyed his used motorcycle shop in Midwest City -- just 
outside Oklahoma City -- it stopped first in Moore, sucking up his 
home and leaving it a shattered pile of glass and metal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it hasn't sunk in yet,'' he said. ``Yesterday,  
I woke up and said it has to be a dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For hundreds of regional business owners, the nightmare has  
begun. 
</P>
<P>
	They must negotiate with insurance companies, hope for a fair  
and quick settlement, and eventually -- if they can manage it -- get 
back to business. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Silsby, an owner of a destroyed surplus store in Midwest  
City, tried to put a positive spin on things as he surveyed the 
wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday was the shock of, `I've lost everything,''' he said.  
``Now it doesn't matter. We can replace it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
