<DOCNO> APW19990506.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 07:05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Assembly Democrats Back Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- All California Assembly Democrats but  
one are endorsing Vice President Al Gore's White House bid, 
snubbing his chief rival for the nomination, Bill Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	The 46 Assembly members cited the attention Gore has lavished on  
California and Clinton administration policies. Since taking office 
in 1993, Gore has made nearly 60 visits to California. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, no other candidate has your experience nor your  
record of achievements,'' Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa 
wrote in a letter to Gore released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter listed the booming economy, falling crime and stiffer  
air and water quality standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The only Democratic Assembly member who did not back Gore was  
Dick Floyd. His office did not immediately respond to a request for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Wally Knox was not on the list of Assembly backers faxed out by  
the Gore campaign, but he said by telephone that he, too, likes 
Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's endorsements, which came 10 months before the  
primary, mirrored a similar gesture made in January by 25 
California Republican lawmakers on behalf of Texas Gov. George W. 
Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``With seven years of vice presidency, certainly the vice  
president is going to have major institutional advantages,'' 
Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser said. ``It would be surprising if it 
didn't, but it doesn't really change the way we go about our 
campaign.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
