<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Africa Investments Execs Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- One of South Africa's largest  
publicly traded companies managed by blacks, New Africa Investments 
Ltd., has been rocked by the resignation of its two co-founders. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman Nthato Motlana and Jonathan Sandler, the executive  
director, said late Wednesday they would leave May 11. 
</P>
<P>
	The departures, following turmoil over attempts to grant share  
options to the executives, were a setback to South Africa's efforts 
to give blacks more economic control. 
</P>
<P>
	The exit of Motlana and Sandler -- high profile proponents of  
encouraging black entrepreneurship -- followed increasing 
dissatisfaction among New Africa's shareholders with the company's 
management style and its efforts to boost the group's flagging 
stock price. 
</P>
<P>
	Matters came to a head two weeks ago when Motlana, Sandler and  
fellow executive directors Dikgang Moseneke and Zwelakhe Sisulu 
tried to give themselves share options worth 130 million rand 
($21.3 million) in subsidiary African Merchant Bank Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Minority shareholders rebelled at what they saw as an  
unjustified equity grab, and a proposed resolution granting the 
shares was jettisoned just before to a general meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	New Africa said late Wednesday that it ``made changes to its  
executive committee to better focus the company's resources on its 
current and future business interests, while improving its 
relationships with its shareholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from the resignations of Motlana, a one-time physician to  
President Nelson Mandela, and Sandler, New Africa said Moseneke and 
Sisulu, the remaining executive directors, have agreed to 
renegotiate their salary packages. 
</P>
<P>
	The move appeared to be an attempt to correct the impression  
that black enrichment was overshadowing efforts to build black 
empowerment. 
</P>
<P>
	In a further attempt to distance itself from accusations of  
greed, Motlana's and Sandler's indirect equity interests in New 
Africa will be taken over by separate trusts to be established with 
funding from subsidiary Hollard Insurance Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair founded New Africa in 1993 and listed it on the  
Johannesburg Stock Exchange a year later. It currently commands a 
market capitalization of almost 10.5 billion rand ($1.72 billion) 
and has substantial interests in insurance and retail and merchant 
banking. 
</P>
<P>
	In The Sowetan newspaper Thursday, Motlana blamed ``the white  
media'' for his downfall. 
</P>
<P>
	New Africa ``is a black-owned company has been a success story,  
and this is the reason why some white establishments do not like 
it,'' he was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
