<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Hears About IOC Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The senior Olympic official in the United  
States made her first monthly report to Congress today on reform 
efforts triggered by the Salt Lake City scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Anita DeFrantz, an International Olympic Committee vice  
president from Los Angeles, briefed members of the staff of Sen. 
John McCain, who had requested the regular reports following a 
contentious Commerce Committee hearing last month. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz explained the organization of IOC 2000, an 80-member  
task force that will recommend changes in the Olympic committee's 
membership and rules, and on plans for the IOC's next general 
assembly in June, according to Commerce Committee spokeswoman Pia 
Pialorsi. 
</P>
<P>
	``Senator McCain still has grave concerns about the reform  
process,'' Pialorsi said. ``But we do not want to prejudge the 
IOC's actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said the committee staff ``greatly appreciated'' the  
information DeFrantz supplied. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain has requested similar updates from IOC president Juan  
Antonio Samaranch and U.S. Olympic Committee president Bill Hybl. 
It was not known if they had submitted their first reports to the 
senator as well. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain has threatened to press legislation affecting the IOC's  
rich American sponsorships unless the panel takes strong action to 
change from the clubby culture that led to the Salt Lake scandal, 
the worst in Olympic history. He had grilled DeFrantz and another 
American IOC member, James Easton, at a Capitol Hill hearing last 
month, and said he did not feel the IOC took the need to reform 
seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	The senator was quoted in Thursday's Washington Post as saying  
recent IOC moves were ``not encouraging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC this week closed the case against the highest ranking  
official implicated in the scandal, executive board member Kim 
Un-yong of South Korea, and ordered further investigation of 
allegations against another top-level member, Phil Coles of 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Samaranch filled the IOC 2000 panel with 80 people  
-- four times the number originally planned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure how an organization can function effectively with  
that large a number of people,'' McCain told the Post. ``It's not a 
reason to have a lot of confidence.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
