<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Severe storms pounded across the Southeast today, while clear  
and dry conditions prevailed over the far West. 
</P>
<P>
	A line of deadly storms struck western Tennessee early today,  
destroying homes, grounding flights and damaging buildings in 
several counties. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and thunderstorms were expected through the day from the  
upper Ohio Valley down through the Tennessee Valley and central 
Gulf Coast states. Some of the storms could pack 70 mph winds, 
large hail and possibly tornadoes. 
</P>
<P>
	Steady rain and scattered storms were also forecast for the  
Great Lakes, western Pennsylvania and mid-Atlantic states. 
</P>
<P>
	Look for variably cloudy skies in New England, with a chance of  
showers in the southern part of the region by evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Skies should be mostly cloudy from the Dakotas and Minnesota  
down to Arkansas, with clouds decreasing from the west towards 
evening. Scattered showers were possible. 
</P>
<P>
	A system moving into the Pacific Northwest should spread clouds  
and rain into Washington, Oregon and northern California. Up to six 
inches of mountain snow could accumulate in Washington. The rest of 
the West should be fair and dry. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Wednesday was 106 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The low was 14 at 
Stanley, Idaho. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 50s and 60s in the  
Northwest and upper Plains; the 60s and 70s in New England, the 
Rockies and the Great Lakes; the 70s and 80s in the Southeast, 
southern Plains and far West; and the 90s in Florida and the 
deserts of the Southwest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
