<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 21:35:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) -- Jews in the U.S. military have faced  
bigotry and anti-Semitic remarks, but a rabbi who is a longtime 
naval chaplain concludes in a new book that such intolerance in the 
ranks is the exception. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Albert Isaac Slomovitz says he is not trying to hide  
anything in ``The Fighting Rabbis.'' The book recounts examples of 
prejudice, such as a rabbi withdrawing as the main speaker for a 
World War II cemetery dedication when other chaplains threatened to 
tell Christian troops to stay away. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Slomovitz said in an interview: ``What I found was that  
quite often the military was ahead of society in terms of 
recognizing people on merit as opposed to race, religion, or creed, 
or something else. I suggest that the military, as an institution, 
was a counterbalance to societal hatred.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The image of an anti-Semitic military is one of two major  
stereotypes Slomovitz challenges in his book. The other is that 
Jews shunned military service. 
</P>
<P>
	He cites records showing about 250,000 Jewish-Americans served  
in World War I and 550,000 in World War II. Many who fought in 
World War I emigrated from Russia where the Czarist army made 
military service unpopular by conscripting 12-year-olds. In the 
U.S. military, a disproportionate number of Jewish members were not 
conscripted, but enlisted. 
</P>
<P>
	``They go back across the Atlantic, end up in France,'' he said.  
``I just found that amazingly fascinating, showing really their 
allegiance to this land of opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Slomovitz, 48, chief chaplain at Pensacola Naval Air Station,  
said few people, including Jews, are aware of Jewish Americans' 
military heritage. The book, published this year by the New York 
University Press, began as his dissertation for a Ph.D. in ethnic 
history from Loyola University in Chicago, a Roman Catholic 
institution. 
</P>
<P>
	Slomovitz grew up in North Miami Beach and earned a bachelor's  
degree from Columbia University. He took night classes for his 
master's and doctorate at Loyola while stationed at Great Lakes 
Naval Training Center through 1995. He plans to retire this summer 
in Atlanta and wants to write another book focusing on 
Jewish-Christian relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Books about the experiences of Jewish chaplains have been  
published before, but Slomovitz is the first to write a 
comprehensive history. 
</P>
<P>
	He traces Jewish-American military history to 1655, when Jews  
demanded the right to join the New Amsterdam militia, to recent 
years, when Christian as well as Jewish clergy stationed in Saudi 
Arabia were called ``morale officers,'' not chaplains, to avoid 
offending their Muslim hosts. 
</P>
<P>
	Jews served in the American Revolution but had no chaplains  
until the Civil War when Congress changed a law that permitted only 
Christians to serve in that capacity. The South had no chaplains, 
but civilian clergy, Christian and Jewish, ministered to 
Confederate troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four rabbis served in the Army and one in the Navy during  
World War I. They included Chaplain Elkan Voorsanger, who was 
called ``The Fighting Rabbi.'' He enlisted as a medic and remained 
in the trenches as a chaplain when Congress authorized additional 
positions for military clergy. 
</P>
<P>
	In World War II, 311 rabbis served, and six lost their lives.  
</P>
<P>
	Rabbi Alexander Goode and three other chaplains -- two Protestant  
and one Catholic -- died when they gave their life jackets to other 
soldiers after a German submarine torpedoed a troop ship. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewish chaplains and soldiers also helped save thousands of  
Holocaust survivors. They moved them to safe areas and in one 
instance forced farmers at gunpoint to slaughter cattle so victims 
could be fed. 
</P>
<P>
	The rabbis, however, could not have accomplished their work  
without the cooperation of their Christian colleagues, Slomovitz 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That epitomizes what the chaplaincy, and what the book, is  
about: That people of varying faith orientations could get along, 
help each other, not only without losing their faith but maybe 
enhancing it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said chaplains of all faiths fight for everyone's religious  
needs and help troops with personal problems regardless of creed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ironic in a way,'' Slomovitz said, ``that in the midst of  
an institution whose purpose is to fight war, you have people who 
really are making peace with each other and cooperating.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Cop Torture Victim on Stand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Haitian immigrant Abner Louima told a jury  
Thursday that police officers who arrested him in 1997 took turns 
beating him before one sexually brutalized him with a stick in a 
police station bathroom. 
</P>
<P>
	The enraged officer rammed the stick up Louima's rectum and then  
jammed it in Louima's mouth, he said in a halting voice at the 
federal trial of five white officers charged with violating his 
civil rights. The incident prompted demonstrations against police 
brutality and inflamed racial tensions in the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking the stand on the third day of the trial, Louima at one  
point was asked to rise and identify the officer. He slowly scanned 
the courtroom before pointing at Officer Justin Volpe. Louima's 
finger shook visibly; Volpe sat expressionless. 
</P>
<P>
	After the attack, Louima testified, Volpe warned Louima that if  
he ``ever talked to anyone about what they did to me, he'd kill me 
and my family and he was not joking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe is one of four officers charged with beating Louima after  
mistakenly thinking he had sucker-punched Volpe as police tried to 
disperse a rowdy crowd outside a Brooklyn nightclub on Aug. 9, 
1997; a fifth officer is charged with covering up the assault. 
Prosecutors revealed this week that Louima's cousin was the man who 
punched Volpe. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe also is accused of sodomizing Louima in a fit of rage.  
Louima was hospitalized with severe internal injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Louima, 32, the government's star witness, slipped  
into the courtroom unobtrusively, wearing an oversized, dark blue 
suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning by Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad,  
Louima said his night began quietly. He described leaving his 
security guard job early, stopping at his parents' house and then 
joining his brother, cousin and friends for an outing to a popular 
nightspot, Club Rendezvous. 
</P>
<P>
	As the club closed and a large crowd spilled onto the street at  
about 4 a.m., Louima said, he noticed an injured man surrounded by 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was one guy who had some blood on his face and was  
complaining that he got hit by a cop,'' Louima testified. 
Bystanders grew angry, he continued, and ``I was very angry, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Louima said he commented that police are ``not supposed to hit  
the person because they have rights.'' After that, he heard someone 
behind him say, ``Shut up,'' then felt himself being knocked to the 
ground and handcuffed. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima described being taken away in a patrol car to a nearby  
intersection where four white police officers -- identified earlier 
by prosecutors as Volpe, Thomas Bruder, Thomas Wiese and Charles 
Schwarz -- began pummeling him. One, he said, taunted him: ``Stupid 
nigger. I'm going to give you a lesson on how to respect a cop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following a second beating by two of the officers, Louima said,  
he was taken into the stationhouse, where one officer -- identified 
by Schwarz by prosecutors -- removed Louima's belt, the witness 
said. With his pants down at his knees and his hands still cuffed, 
the officer led him into the bathroom with Volpe following behind, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima said he noticed Volpe grab something near a trash can  
before being tossed face down near a toilet. Volpe kicked him in 
the groin, and then the mouth when he started to yell, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima also testified that he lied to reporters when he said  
that an officer had said ``It's Giuliani time,'' a reference to the 
law-and-order policies of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. He said two men 
who visited him at the hospital had told him to make the statement 
to attract attention. 
</P>
<P>
	In opening statements earlier in the week, Volpe's attorney,  
Marvyn Kornberg, said Louima had 150 million reasons to lie about 
the entire incident -- one for every dollar in his civil claim 
against the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 14:35:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Wars Buzz Hits Warp Speed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Now that a few people have actually seen the  
new ``Star Wars'' movie in special screenings, the hype has yielded 
to the buzz. And the buzz is ... well, don't expect a masterpiece, 
just a really good movie with cool special effects. 
</P>
<P>
	In other words, a certain summer blockbuster.  
</P>
<P>
	``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace'' was screened  
Tuesday night in eight North American cities for movie theater 
executives, their families, and -- apparently -- a bundle of ``Star 
Wars'' fans who somehow finagled some of the prized tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost immediately, early reviews hit cyberspace, followed by  
the reactions to the reviews, then the reactions to the reactions, 
along with all manner of claims, counterclaims, insults and 
soul-searching over the film, which opens nationwide May 19. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys, it's a movie!'' responded Tom Sherak, distribution head  
of 20th Century Fox, which is releasing the film for George Lucas. 
``It isn't the Bible! It's fun, it's enjoyable, it's escapism. But 
it's a movie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Uh huh.  
</P>
<P>
	In what was titled, ``What I believe to be the FIRST review  
anywhere on the Internet,'' Ronald Epstein wrote on his Home 
Theater Forum Web site (www.hometheaterforum.com) that while he was 
impressed, the movie may not satisfy hard-core ``Star Wars'' fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like 'Star Wars,' it smells like 'Star Wars' and it  
feels like 'Star Wars.' However, is it a 'Star Wars' that we are 
going to walk away satisfied with? Well ... perhaps, but not for 
everyone,'' Epstein wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	While the early amateur critics loved the action sequences and  
most of the effects, including what they found to be an incredible 
underwater sequence, some reviewers thought the 2-hour-plus movie 
dragged a bit in places, that it was a little too kid-oriented and 
that one of the computer-generated characters, Jar Jar Binks, was 
annoying. 
</P>
<P>
	Such views, however, were quickly countered by those who, like  
Jerry Rhoades on Home Theater Forum, found the movie to be 
``PHENOMENAL!!!!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't watch it to analyze and match other people's reviews and  
thoughts to the film, just sit back, relax and enjoy the ride,'' he 
said. ``I did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On a leading ``Star Wars'' Web site, www.theforce.net, a writer  
using the nickname BetterJedi wrote, ``Wow! What a film. I'm going 
to have to see it about 10 or 15 times to take it all in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But another writer, going by Job21, wasn't as impressed. ``It  
was a dream come true at first but quickly turned into a 
nightmare,'' Job21 said. 
</P>
<P>
	That was countered by a fuselage of reaction from fans, many of  
whom raised doubts about whether Job even saw the movie, pointing 
out his review noticeably lacked the kinds of details that would 
suggest he was there. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the theater operators themselves, they gave their usual  
tempered thumbs-up -- they praised the movie just enough to avoid 
losing any customers but not so much that Lucas could extract 
higher fees for showing the film. 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line, financially, is the early buzz -- or for that  
matter the reactions from the professional critics who see 
``Phantom'' Friday night -- won't mean a thing initially, said Paul 
Dergarabedian, of box office tracker Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``This movie is critic-proof,'' he said. ``I think it doesn't  
matter what anybody says, good, bad or indifferent. The film is 
going to play big in those first two weeks without question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After that ... the Force only knows.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
