<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:25:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A newly discovered audiotape  
suggests that someone tried to cover up key facts in the 1992 
bombing of the Israeli Embassy in Buenos Aires, the Israeli 
diplomat who was ambassador at the time of the blast said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The tape purportedly contains an order from a police officer  
redirecting a patrol car away from the embassy area just before the 
explosion, which killed 29 people. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with Israeli radio, Yitzhak Shefi alleged that  
the tape proved some Argentinian police officers tried to ``cover 
the facts'' and keep suspicion away from themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Interior Minister Carlos Corach said he has asked police to  
determine the authenticity of the tape, which was handed over by an 
officer to a congressional committee investigating the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	No suspects have been detained following the 1992 bombing.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- President Ernesto Zedillo has announced a  
$978 million anti-poverty program aimed at the 91 poorest regions 
in Mexico, to be implemented over the next three months. 
</P>
<P>
	The money is to be spent in providing health services, food and  
education to millions of Mexicans living in extreme poverty, news 
media reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico's economy has withstood international economic crises and  
continues to grow at rate exceeding that of more developed nations. 
But 40 percent of the country remains in poverty, never recovering 
from the economic crisis that broke out shortly after Zedillo took 
office in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1994-95 crisis, in which the peso lost half its value and  
interest rates soared, left millions jobless and unable to pay back 
loans 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- Showing that nothing is sacred  
in El Salvador's crime wave, Roman Catholic officials said Thursday 
that their churches have been hit by a wave of burglaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Churches and parishes, mostly in rural parts of the country,  
have been affected, with altars stripped of religious images, said 
Monsignor Roberto Torruella, rector of La Merced Church in the 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the items stolen have been priceless objects dating  
backing back to colonial times. 
</P>
<P>
	Crime has surged in the Central American country since a 1992  
peace agreement ended its 12-year civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
