<DOCNO> APW19990506.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 21:07:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tagliabue Urges Support for Patriots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue urged area  
business leaders to purchase high-end seats and suites in order to 
help the New England Patriots build a new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody knows it's going to be difficult,'' Tagliabue told  
about 500 people today at the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce 
annual meeting and dinner. ``There will be suites that need to be 
purchased. There will be premium seats that need to be purchased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue said a partnership between the NFL, state government  
and private investors is needed to make the stadium work. He cited 
stadium ventures in Buffalo, Detroit and Seattle as successful 
examples. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from encouraging teamwork, Tagliabue mentioned no specific  
locations or deadlines for a new Patriots stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Meetings last month between Tagliabue, Gov. Paul Cellucci and  
legislative and business leaders preceded the collapse of a $380 
million stadium proposal in Hartford, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL has supported keeping the team in the Boston area, which  
has the nation's sixth largest television market; Hartford has the 
27th. 
</P>
<P>
	Massachusetts lawmakers have proposed paying $70 million for  
infrastructure supporting a new stadium in Foxboro, the team's 
current home. But Patriots owner Robert Kraft would have to pay for 
the stadium, though it would be partly financed through favorable 
loans from the NFL. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0122 </DOCNO>
