<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 10:45:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Buys MediaOne for $54 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Now that AT&AMP;T Corp. has won a takeover fight to  
become the nation's largest cable TV company, a debate has begun 
over whether consumers also win. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T plans to offer its 16 million cable TV customers a broad  
array of telephone, Internet and TV services. It announced a deeper 
alliance today with computer software leader Microsoft Corp. to 
increase its orders for devices used to enable delivery of Internet 
and interactive TV via cable. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers will only need one cable into their homes, and will  
receive just one, lower-priced bill, AT&AMP;T says. 
</P>
<P>
	The ambitious strategy, however, is being criticized by consumer  
groups, lawmakers and competitors. AT&AMP;T, already the largest 
long-distance phone company, will stifle competition with its 
dominance of cable TV and high-speed, ``broadband'' Internet 
access, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	At the heart of the debate is AT&AMP;T's plan to spend $54 billion  
to acquire MediaOne Group Inc., the nation's fourth-largest cable 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	After weeks of high-stakes jousting, AT&AMP;T struck a truce late  
Tuesday with Comcast Corp., the No. 3 cable company, which had also 
sought to buy Denver-based MediaOne. Under terms of the pact, AT&AMP;T 
and Philadelphia-based Comcast will divvy up the cable TV customers 
of MediaOne. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Cooper, research director for the Consumer Federation of  
America, said the costs of the deal for consumers outweigh any 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``The costs are humongous in terms of the anti-competitive  
effects on cable and broadband services and the benefits of local 
phone competition are minuscule,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's competitors aren't mincing words either.  
</P>
<P>
	Keep America Connected, a coalition backed by regional phone  
monopolies, took out a three-quarter page advertisement Wednesday 
in The New York Times calling AT&AMP;T's acquisition of MediaOne a 
``dangerous and aggressive plan to dominate the way Americans 
communicate to an extent no force, institution, company or person 
has ever been allowed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, for its part, claims it can save consumers 20 percent to  
25 percent off their cable and telephone bills. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based company plans to offer MediaOne customers  
combined cable, phone and Internet service early next year. The 
expanded service will include local, intrastate and long-distance 
phone calls, cable, and Internet access for a flat, monthly fee. 
Extra services, like call waiting and caller I.D., may also be 
included. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T said it may only charge customers between $4 to $6 for an  
extra line for a fax or computer, compared with the $17 charged by 
some phone companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more you buy from AT&AMP;T, the less it's going to cost you,''  
said C. Michael Armstrong, chairman and chief executive of AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	But Armstrong will have to convince lawmakers that's a good  
thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the House Commerce  
Committee's telecommunications subcommittee, which oversees 
telephone and television policies, is also concerned the planned 
merger would stifle cable TV competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin hasn't decide whether he will oppose the deal, but ``he's  
leaning against it at this point,'' said spokesman Ken Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin intends to ask the Federal Communications Commission and  
either the Justice Department or the Federal Trade Commission ``to 
take a hard look at this,' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Worries also have been voiced about the growing role of  
Microsoft, which is investing $5 billion in AT&AMP;T as it widens its 
Internet and telecommunications presence. AT&AMP;T stressed today that 
it still will deal with other software providers. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, AT&AMP;T's investors are betting that the company's  
chairman, who has proved a savvy negotiator in his deals with 
Comcast and MediaOne, will again prevail. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's shares were rising further this morning after climbing  
more than 10 percent Wednesday. In early trading today, AT&AMP;T was up 
$2.81 1/4 at $59.75 a share on the New York Stock Exchange, where 
MediaOne's shares were up $2.50 at $79.37 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast's common shares, which rose about 14 percent, on  
Wednesday, added 62 1/2 cents this morning to $37.25 a share on the 
Nasdaq Stock Market following a previously announced stock split 
that took effect today. Microsoft was up $1.50 at $80.62 1/2 in early 
Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Under AT&AMP;T's pact with Comcast, the two companies plan to  
exchange 2.7 million customers, giving each company a stronger 
presence in markets they have targeted for growth. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T will get 700,000 subscribers in seven markets, including  
Atlanta, Sacramento, Chicago and Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast will get 2 million subscribers in seven markets,  
including Michigan, New Jersey, Pennyslvania and Washington. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 09:05:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines To Fight Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Philippine Airlines will fight an  
attempt by the U.S. Export-Import Bank to seize Boeing jets used by 
the ailing flag carrier on its long-distance flights, a company 
lawyer said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine Airlines lawyer Estelito Mendoza said the carrier  
will oppose the Ex-Im Bank's petition with a U.S. Bankruptcy Court 
to allow the seizure of the four Boeing 747-400 jumbo jets it 
helped the airline acquire. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL, Asia's oldest airline, has been unable to repay more than  
$2.2 billion in debt, owed largely to U.S. and European creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter Wednesday to Manila's Securities and Exchange  
Commission, the Ex-Im Bank said it began the recovery move after 
deciding PAL's financial rehabilitation process ``lacks fundamental 
attributes of transparency, fairness and predictability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a response Thursday to the Ex-Im Bank, SEC chairman Perfecto  
Yasay said the move violates the bank's earlier commitment to 
follow the SEC's jurisdiction in the airline's rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Yasay told reporters the Ex-Im Bank approved PAL's  
rehabilitation plan in March, thereby submitting itself to the 
SEC's jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Ex-Im Bank has complaints about PAL's rehabilitation  
process, it should bring a case to a court in the Philippines, not 
the United States, Yasay said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should not act like a bully,'' Yasay said.  
</P>
<P>
	The four Boeing aircraft are used daily for PAL's long-haul  
flights, mainly to U.S. destinations, and their seizure would 
jeopardize the company's international flight operations, 
Philippine officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the Ex-Im Bank sought a U.S. court's help in  
recovering the aircraft after PAL failed to make payments on its 
debt. U.S. authorities subsequently seized two of the planes in Los 
Angeles and Hong Kong but returned them after airline officials 
appealed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ex-Im Bank and other major PAL creditors were displeased  
last week when businessman Lucio Tan, the airline's majority 
stockholder, reassumed active management control. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan, which holds a 70 percent stake, has had strained  
relationships with PAL's unions, and the creditors say they want 
the airline to be run by professional managers. 
</P>
<P>
	Yasay, however, said the Ex-Im Bank could not object to Tan's  
return to PAL's management helm because he has a right under 
Philippine laws to assume control of a company he owns. 
</P>
<P>
	Yasay said the Philippine government may temporarily take over  
PAL's management if Tan is unable to raise $200 million in new 
funds for PAL required under the rehabilitation plan by a June 4 
deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 12:35:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Estafan To Sing at Arena's Opening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Gloria Estefan will be the sole performer at the  
American Airlines Arena grand opening on New Year's Eve, and she 
promises to give a show ``the likes of which you've never seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a blowout,'' Ms. Estefan said Wednesday.  
``We're bringing unique things that haven't been seen before in a 
concert.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Gloria Estefan Millennium Concert Spectacular on Dec. 31  
will be the opening event for the arena. Tickets range from $150 to 
$500 and will go on sale May 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Estefan's other projects include finishing a  
Spanish-language album, writing a screenplay, and producing a film 
with her husband. She also will make her acting debut later this 
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
