<HEADLINE> Recruiting of Census Workers Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Goodwill Industries will help the Census  
Bureau recruit temporary workers to count the nation next year. 
</P>
<P>
	A partnership with the national nonprofit organization was  
announced Wednesday by Census Director Kenneth Prewitt and Fred 
Grandy, president of Goodwill. 
</P>
<P>
	Among its programs, Goodwill conducts job training for people  
needing work and will now recruit these workers for Census jobs. It 
trained some 320,000 people last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This program will tap an underutilized pool of eager  
employees,'' Grandy said. ``Our graduates are skilled, reliable and 
ambitious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prewitt said he was ``thrilled this community-based agency will  
help us find some of the 850,000-plus workers we will need to 
conduct the census.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwill Industries helps people with disabilities and other  
needs by providing job training and placement assistance through a 
network of 185 local centers in the United States and Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
