<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:34:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Olympic Official Responds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- An Australian Olympic official, accused of  
helping Atlanta beat Melbourne in bidding for the 1996 Games, gave 
no extraordinary assistance to Atlanta organizers, a spokesman said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics in Australia want Phil Coles, a member of the  
International Olympic Committee and the Sydney Organizing Committee 
for the Olympic Games (SOCOG), to resign because of links to 
scandals that organizers say are damaging sponsorship and 
threatening ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta bid documents released last week included a letter from  
Atlanta board member Horace Sibley to Coles thanking him for ``your 
time and your advice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When reports of the letter hit Australia, criticism of Coles  
increased. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Walker, a member of Melbourne's bid, said that the ``heat''  
Coles is feeling is justice for his ``dalliance with Atlanta.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a pity that so many of us spent so much time  
pursuing the games for 1996 for Melbourne and we find that one of 
our number chose to help the other side,'' Walker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta officials say several IOC members received similar  
thanks after meeting with the bid team in 1988, two years before 
Atlanta was announced as the site of the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's safe to say all the IOC members provided good  
advice and counsel to all the candidate cities who were bidding for 
the 1996 Games,'' said Lee Echols, spokesman for the athletics 
foundation. ``Did he (Coles) give extraordinary help? Absolutely 
not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles says there's a conspiracy against him, possibly by members  
of Melbourne's failed bid. 
</P>
<P>
	In nine boxes of Atlanta Olympic documents released last week,  
The Associated Press found five similar letters Sibley wrote on the 
same day to other IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	All the letters contained similar thanks, and one other --  
written to Venezuelan IOC member Flor Isava-Fonseca -- mentions 
advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``You gave us some good advice and we will follow it,'' the  
letter to Ms. Isava-Fonseca said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sibley and former Atlanta Olympics chief Billy Payne did not  
immediately return calls seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the private group holding thousands of boxes of  
records detailing Atlanta's Olympic has gone to court rather than 
bend to pressure from Georgia's governor and attorney general to 
make the documents public. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation filed suit asking for a  
ruling that the documents do not fall under the state's Open 
Records Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Journal-Constitution has been fighting to open the  
4,000 boxes of records. The newspaper says the public has a right 
to know if they contain evidence that Atlanta officials engaged in 
bribery akin to the scandal that has tainted Salt Lake City's bid 
for the 2002 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	In Atlanta, the athletics foundation sued Wednesday after  
Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker demanded the bid documents 
be made public. 
</P>
<P>
	``GAAF's steadfast refusal to make the documents available to  
the public ... lends credence to the belief that GAAF has something 
to hide,'' Baker wrote to Joseph Bankoff, the foundation's 
attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to Baker, Bankoff wrote, ``There is no shadow over  
the Games other than one manufactured'' by the 
Journal-Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletics foundation, created by Payne in 1987 to bid for  
the Olympics, says the documents are the property of a group of 
private citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	But Baker says the records must be opened because Atlanta's  
Olympic efforts involved a partnership between government and 
private interests. 
</P>
<P>
	No evidence of wrongdoing was found in the nine boxes out of  
4,000 the foundation has voluntarily opened. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta officials have admitted to routinely exceeding the  
International Olympic Committee's $200 spending limit on gifts, but 
insist they did nothing wrong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
