<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft, AT&AMP;T Form Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Deepening an alliance of titans of  
communications and technology, Microsoft Corp. said today it will 
invest $5 billion in AT&AMP;T Corp. and AT&AMP;T said it will increase its 
use of Microsoft's software. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact is designed to offer customers interactive TV, with  
phone service, e-mail and other Internet features -- all through one 
cable TV with one bill. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, which is becoming the nation's largest cable company, and  
Microsoft, the largest software company, will test the new service 
in three cities next year to find out what works and what consumers 
want. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to go to three cities and make it real and learn  
from it,'' said C. Michael Armstrong, chairman and chief executive 
of AT&AMP;T, who did not name the trial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement today follows AT&AMP;T's truce late Tuesday with  
Comcast Corp., which stopped a bidding war and paved the way for 
AT&AMP;T to acquire MediaOne Group Inc., the nation's fourth-largest 
cable company. 
</P>
<P>
	With the addition of MediaOne's cable subscribers, AT&AMP;T will  
control the cable connections to 25 million homes. AT&AMP;T has an 
existing agreement with Microsoft to buy software to power the 
set-top boxes that will control the new packages of services. 
</P>
<P>
	Under today's agreement, AT&AMP;T could double its purchases of  
Microsoft software to 10 million copies, giving Microsoft up to 40 
percent of AT&AMP;T's cable business. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies plan to deploy Microsoft's TV software, based  
on Windows CE, in one large city, and one suburban community. AT&AMP;T 
also plans a test in a third city that would use Microsoft's 
software for set-top boxes with another company's software for 
larger computers known as servers, which deliver services such as 
interactive entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	As speculation about such a deal has grown in recent days,  
worries have been voiced about the clout such an alliance could 
wield over basic communications services for consumers. But AT&AMP;T 
stressed that it is not ruling out similar agreements with other 
technology businesses, saying its arrangement with Microsoft is a 
``nonexclusive agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've said 150 times, when you're in the networking  
business, the only way to make money is to carry the most 
traffic,'' Armstrong said. He added that AT&AMP;T doesn't want to get 
into the business of providing Internet directories, chat rooms, 
and home pages, saying ``We are open and welcome to commercial 
relationships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street cheered the deal. In early afternoon trading today,  
AT&AMP;T was up more than 9 percent on the New York Stock Exchange, 
rising $5.18 3/4 to $62.12 1/2 a share. Microsoft was up 43 3/4 cents at 
$79.56 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said it would buy $5 billion in AT&AMP;T securities that  
will be convertible into 66.7 million shares of AT&AMP;T stock. It also 
purchased the right to acquire an additional 40 million shares in 
three years. If it exercises all its options and winds up with 
106.7 million shares, it would own about 3.4 percent of AT&AMP;T. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 22:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Litton Offering To Buy Shipbuilders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Another defense industry mega-merger is on  
the table -- and Newport News Shipbuilding and Avondale Industries 
Inc. are in the thick of it yet again. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton Industries Inc. on Thursday offered to buy the two  
companies in a package deal valued at $1.76 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The unsolicited bid came less than a month after the Pentagon  
rejected General Dynamics' effort to acquire Newport News 
</P>
<P>
	Litton said the combination ``would create a worldwide leader in  
the shipbuilding industry and a full-service contractor with the 
ability to compete across the spectrum of the U.S. Navy's 
shipbuilding needs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company would have revenues of about $7.4 billion  
and more than 58,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodland Hills, Calif.-based Litton offered a tax-free,  
stock-for-stock deal for Newport News Shipbuilding. Each share of 
the Newport News, Va-based company would be converted to .55 Litton 
shares, valuing the deal at $1.26 billion based on Thursday's 
closing stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avondale offer is for $38 per share, or $504 million, in  
cash. The combined offer also includes another $600 million in 
debt. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans-based Avondale and Newport News Shipbuilding already  
were preparing to merge when General Dynamics made its offer for 
the Virginia yard in February. 
</P>
<P>
	But on April 14, Defense Secretary William Cohen scuttled the  
General Dynamics proposal, saying any cost savings to taxpayers 
would not justify the loss of competition for designing and 
building Navy ships. 
</P>
<P>
	The Litton proposal is expected to require a Pentagon review as  
well. Michael R. Brown, chairman and CEO of Litton, said the 
company has had preliminary discussions with the Department of 
Defense about the offer, and claimed the acquisitions would enhance 
competition within the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	William P. Fricks, chairman and chief executive officer of  
Newport News Shipbuilding, said the company's board of directors 
agreed to ``preliminary discussions'' with Litton ``to fully 
evaluate the terms of the offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to emphasize, however, that our board has not made any  
determination as to the adequacy of Litton's present proposal, and 
there can be no assurance that any transaction proposed by Litton 
will be acceptable to our board,'' Fricks said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Albert L. Bossier Jr., chairman and CEO of Avondale, said the  
company had Litton's offer under review and would comment further 
when the review is complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Retired Rear Adm. Eugene Carroll, deputy director of the  
Washington-based Center for Defense Information, a Pentagon 
watchdog group, said the Litton proposal is another indication of 
consolidation pressures in the defense industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``The drive in the whole military complex is for consolidation  
and so-called economies of scale, where they cut costs and overhead 
-- in theory, to the advantage of the Department of Defense,'' 
Carroll said. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton controls a number of aerospace, defense and electronics  
businesses, including Ingalls Shipbuilding in Pascagoula, Miss., a 
builder of Navy destroyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News Shipbuilding, where the Steelworkers union has been  
on strike since April 5 over wages and other benefits, is the only 
builder of Navy aircraft carriers and shares submarine work with 
General Dynamics' Electric Boat division in Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale designs, builds and overhauls Navy surface ships as  
well as commercial vessels. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 06:32:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Signs East Timor Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Now that a historic accord has given the  
people of East Timor a vote on their future, the next hurdle is to 
stop escalating violence so voters can decide whether to remain 
part of Indonesia or seek independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement signed Wednesday by the foreign ministers of  
Portugal and Indonesia and witnessed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi 
Annan states clearly that ending violence and intimidation ``is a 
prerequisite'' for holding a free and fair ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia invaded East Timor in 1975 and annexed the former  
Portuguese colony in 1976. It has refused to allow U.N. 
peacekeeping troops to oversee the Aug. 8 ballot -- and the 
agreement states that Jakarta is responsible for ensuring that 
voting is held ``in an atmosphere free of intimidation, violence or 
interference from any side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stressing that ending violence is ``crucial,'' Annan noted that  
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie had given his word that he would 
do his utmost to maintain law and order. 
</P>
<P>
	In a memo, Annan says the first step is to bring armed civilian  
groups under control. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-independence rebel groups and pro-Indonesian militiamen  
blame each other for the surge in fighting following Indonesia's 
surprise announcement in January that it would offer the 800,000 
East Timorese independence if they rejected wide-ranging autonomy. 
Both sides signed a peace pledge on April 21, along with top 
Indonesian military leaders, but the violence has continued. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan said all armed groups must disarm before the vote and  
Indonesian military forces must also be redeployed. 
</P>
<P>
	There must also be an immediate ban on rallies by armed groups  
as well as freedom for both sides to hold peaceful political 
activities and have access to the media, his memo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Independence activists have demanded a major reduction of  
Indonesian troops in East Timor and disarmament of the militias. 
Pro-Indonesian militia leaders oppose the U.N.-supervised ballot 
and have warned that they will fight for their cause. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement says the parties should ``take the necessary steps  
to achieve disarmament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, while insisting his  
government was determined to demilitarize East Timor, said his 
country could not promise to disarm the militias immediately 
because of difficulties in getting pro-independence rebels down 
from the mountains. He also stressed that disarmament requires 
cooperation of both groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement states that Indonesian police will be ``solely  
responsible'' for maintaining law and order, and that Annan will 
make some unarmed U.N. civilian police available to serve as 
advisers and to supervise ballot boxes as they travel to and from 
polling stations. 
</P>
<P>
	A 600-strong U.N. mission will oversee voting and a U.N. advance  
team has already arrived in East Timor, U.N. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama handed over a $10 million  
check from the Portuguese government to help finance the U.N. 
mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 06:32:31 </DATE_TIME>
