<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.D. Canola Crop Expected To Rise / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FARGO, N.D. (AP) -- Bill Mickelson grew his first acre of canola  
more than 20 years ago as an experiment. This spring, his canola 
crop will rival that of his spring wheat fields. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rolla farmer is among a growing number expected to push  
North Dakota's combined canola crop above 1.2 million acres this 
spring -- the first canola crop of more than 1 million acres in the 
state. Canola is a grain, often used to make cooking oil. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been our most profitable crop for the last five years,''  
said Mickelson, who farms with his brother. ``And even with prices 
down a little right now, we'll make more on it than anything 
else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canola has quickly become the fastest growing crop in North  
Dakota. In 1991, farmers planted just 30,000 acres. In 1997, the 
crop had grown to 456,000 acres, and it nearly doubled last year to 
800,000 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	It has become so popular, in fact, that the previously  
loose-knit Northern Canola Growers Association recently hired a 
full-time director to oversee marketing and production efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It got to the point where it became too demanding for the  
board of directors to handle it all in the little free time they 
had,'' said Barry Coleman, who began his duties as executive 
director March 1. ``So they hired me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The association has about 150 producers as members. They pay a  
$40 annual membership fee and checkoff fees of 3 cents per 
hundredweight of canola. 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman said there has been a surge in new membership requests  
this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think farmers looked around and saw that this is one of the  
few crops where producers are making any money,'' he said. ``It's 
kept a lot of folks in business these past years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canola's success as a rotational crop for wheat, along with  
stable prices for raw canola and growing consumer demand for 
healthier oils, has helped increase canola production, Coleman and 
Mickelson say. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only are individual farmers like Mickelson planting more of  
it, but farmers who have never grown the crop are now including it 
in their rotations. Canola currently is grown in every county of 
North Dakota, which continues to be the largest producer of the 
crop in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	IDAHO FALLS, Idaho (AP) -- If there is one thing that keeps  
potato growers in the field, it is the prospect of winning big, 
says Bruce Huffaker, publisher of the North American Potato Market 
News. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite poor prices, he said, there are no signs eastern Idaho  
farmers are cutting back on acreage this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	They tend to look at potatoes as a cure-all, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	After a rainy week that slowed things down, growers are  
returning to the fields. And after three years of depressed prices, 
many are looking at 1999 as their last shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``Another bad year will finish a lot of guys off,'' said Mark  
Mickelsen, who farms 7,000 acres and owns Rigby Produce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:48:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, NATO Agree on Kosovo Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Russia and the major Western powers set  
aside their differences over NATO airstrikes Thursday and drafted a 
joint plan to end the Kosovo conflict, including the deployment of 
an international force to keep the peace after the withdrawal of 
Yugoslav forces. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and other Western officials welcomed Russia's  
backing for ``effective international civil and security 
presences'' in Kosovo, where a NATO campaign has failed to halt the 
expulsions of one-third of the ethnic Albanians in the southern 
Serb province since March. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo's most prominent ethnic Albanian leader told a news  
conference in Rome a day after he and his family were allowed to 
leave Yugoslavia that he favored an international peacekeeping 
force -- including NATO -- in his homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need above all to create security in Kosovo so people can  
return,'' said Ibrahim Rugova, who was a negotiator for the ethnic 
Albanian delegation at the failed peace talks in Rambouillet, 
France, that preceded the 6-week-old NATO air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton described the draft agreed to in Germany as ``a  
significant step forward ... increasing the likelihood that there 
will ultimately be a resolution of this that will actually work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He made his remarks after meeting a grateful crowd of Kosovo  
refugees housed at a German facility and greeting three U.S. 
soldiers freed last week by Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO hopes getting Moscow on board in a common front will  
increase the diplomatic pressure on Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic to drop his resistance to an international military 
presence in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	To bring in Russia, the Western powers agreed on a statement  
that makes no reference to any NATO role in Kosovo peacekeeping and 
stresses the importance of U.N. backing for the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	However, NATO ministers insisted they had not dropped demands  
for an international force that is strongly armed, equipped with a 
mandate to use force and spearheaded by alliance troops. 
</P>
<P>
	``This must mean a strong military force with NATO at its  
core,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said after the 
meeting of foreign ministers from Russia and the G-7 group of 
leading industrialized nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without robust military presence, nothing will be achieved,''  
added German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, who chaired the 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministers issued seven ``general principles'' for a  
political solution to the crisis that they said will be proposed as 
the basis for a U.N. resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from the international force, they include a verifiable  
end to violence in Kosovo; withdrawal of military, police and 
paramilitary forces; establishment of an interim administration in 
the province; the ``safe and free'' return of refugees; economic 
aid to the region; and a political settlement granting 
``substantial self-government for Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said ``it would be  
premature to speak of a breakthrough, but progress has been made,'' 
the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Fischer acknowledged NATO and Moscow, which has religious and  
cultural ties with the Serbs, remain at odds over Russian calls for 
suspending the bombing and over the strength and composition of the 
international force. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic's refusal to accept an armed international force in  
Kosovo has been the main sticking point of previous peace attempts. 
Western ministers said Russia's backing and the possibility of a 
U.N. resolution would crank up pressure to accept. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a unity of purpose, including the Russians, so there  
is increasing pressure being applied,'' Canadian Foreign Minister 
Lloyd Axworthy said after the 2 1/2-hour meeting in a government guest 
house overlooking the Rhine River outside Bonn. 
</P>
<P>
	Axworthy said senior diplomats from the G-8 nations will meet  
within days to draw up the text of a U.N. resolution to back the 
proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said no peace deal would  
work without a forceful international presence led by NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	``The refugees are not going to return to Kosovo unless there is  
a credible protection,'' Cook said. ``If it is going to be 
credible, if it is going to work, it must have real teeth and those 
teeth will need to be provided by the NATO countries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said the force will include troops from the United  
States and probably Russia. NATO officials said Britain and France 
would also participate, rejecting suggestions that allied nations 
taking part in the bombing campaign be excluded. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO, meanwhile, said that despite the intensified diplomatic  
efforts there would be no letup in the air raids on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied targets Thursday included fuel depots, bridges and  
military airfields. 
</P>
<P>
	The allies said they are well on their way to dismantling Serb  
forces in Kosovo ``bit by bit'' but at the same time acknowledged a 
failure to stop Milosevic's ethnic cleansing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have all but entirely pinned them down,'' Maj. Gen. Walter  
Jertz said at a NATO briefing. ``Their ability to operate 
effectively, let alone carry out acts of brutality, is further 
reduced with each day that passes.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 23:25:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schools Struggle With Colo Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANTIOCH, Ill. (AP) -- Andrew Eisen is a bookish 15-year-old who  
likes to write stories and poems, an honors student who says he's 
never been in trouble at school. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the sophomore at Antioch Community High School says he can't  
set foot on campus because administrators fear he may be capable of 
killing a classmate. 
</P>
<P>
	In the days after two students unleashed a deadly attack at a  
Colorado school, Eisen's story is becoming increasingly familiar. 
Across the country, students carrying weapons, overheard making 
threats or found scribbling something deemed threatening on a piece 
of paper are being kicked out of school. Bomb threats have kept 
thousands more at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a tough situation because administrators charged with  
keeping schools safe are not taking any chances,'' said Doug 
Bruenlin of the Family Institute at Northwestern University. ``But 
they are doing a fair amount of damage to kids who had no intention 
of doing any harm to anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The day after the Columbine High School shooting, an Antioch  
teacher urged students to report any problems they were having with 
other students. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Eisen's attorney, Jed Stone, another student told  
the teacher that he had overheard Eisen say he didn't like him and 
that he had gone shooting with his father. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone said that report triggered a chain of events that included  
a call to police and a search of Eisen's locker, where officials 
found papers and poems he'd written. On one sheet of paper, beneath 
the words ``The Absurdity of Violence,'' he had written that a 
student ``walked into a cafeteria and opened fire with a .22 
carbine rifle, witnesses said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When I found out (the other teen) was scared of me, I thought  
it was funny,'' Eisen said. So, the next time he saw the other 
student, he said he told him, ``I hate you.''' 
</P>
<P>
	On April 22, Eisen was summoned to see the principal. He was  
taken to the police station, where he said he was fingerprinted and 
charged with disorderly conduct. He then spent a week in juvenile 
hall. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials and the police department would not discuss the  
case. The Lake County state's attorney's office did not return 
phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	But Nancy Krent, an attorney representing the school district,  
defended how the case has been handled. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the facts of this case any school district that acted  
the way this school district did would have acted properly,'' Krent 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisen said he fears he may be expelled for the remainder of this  
school year and all of the next school year. Sheila Eisen worries 
about what his arrest will do to her son's goal of going to a top 
college or to his recent acceptance to a prestigious exchange 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has the potential to ruin his life,'' she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cavs Lead League in Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- If someone had accidentally stumbled into the  
Cavaliers' news conference today, they might have thought it was a 
symposium on orthopedics or a college Anatomy 101 lecture. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting next to the microphones and water glasses on the front  
table were two skeleton models,one of a large human right foot, the 
other of a right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	The props were all you needed to know about the Cavs' 1999  
season, 50 games in which Cleveland's players and fans got a crash 
course on metacarpals, meniscus and medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Crazy,'' said guard Derek Anderson, who missed 10 games with  
an injured right knee, and the season finale in Toronto with the 
flu. ``It's amazing what we had to go through. It's just hard to 
believe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs redefined the overused ``day-to-day'' sports cliche  
this season en route to a 22-28 finish. Cleveland's players were 
sometimes hour-to-hour and minute-to-minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Injuries ravaged the young team, turning a year which started  
with promise and playoff hopes into one of survival. When the 
season ended Wednesday night with a 96-87 loss to the Raptors -- 
Cleveland's 10th loss in 11 games -- the Cavs had seven healthy 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess you could say we had seven survivors,'' said Mitchell  
Butler, who was waived early in the year and brought back as the 
injured list filled up. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs players who didn't survive until the finish included  
center Zydrunas Ilgauskas (broken left foot), forward Shawn Kemp 
(sprained left mid-foot), guard Brevin Knight (broken left hand) 
and forward Corie Blount (torn knee cartilage). 
</P>
<P>
	After Anderson got sick earlier this week and Wesley Person went  
down with a turned ankle, coach Mike Fratello had to use assistant 
coaches Marc Iavaroni, Sidney Lowe and former Cavs guard and 
current broadcaster Austin Carr just to get through a pregame 
shootaround. 
</P>
<P>
	It was that kind of season.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was a tough, tough year for our organization, our players,  
and our fans,'' said Fratello. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs hoped to build on the momentum created last season when  
they qualified for the playoffs with three rookie starters. 
However, the NBA lockout took care of that. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, in their fifth game, the Cavs lost Ilgauskas, the 7-foot-3  
center they signed during the offseason to a seven-year contract, 
for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got the double whammy,'' said Anderson. ``We had two weeks  
to get ready for the season and then just when we got going, `Z' 
went down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Ilgauskas out, the Cavs were forced to start forward Vitaly  
Potapenko -- since traded to Boston for Andrew DeClercq -- at center, 
leaving Kemp with little help inside and prone to constant 
double-teams in the post. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were never able to evaluate our team as a team,'' said  
general manager Wayne Embry. ``We had the abbreviated training camp 
and then Z's injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ilgauskas' injury was the season's most devastating, and the one  
the Cavs will watch closest this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John Bergfeld, the team doctor, spent nearly 25 minutes  
reviewing the team's medical dossier during Thursday's news 
conference. Bergfeld said he expected Ilgauskas to make a full 
recovery and he should be ready for training camp this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We anticipate it should heal itself up well,'' said Bergfeld.  
</P>
<P>
	In a season of gloom and doom there were some positives.  
</P>
<P>
	Kemp, who became the butt of jokes and a poster boy for the NBA  
lockout when he arrived at training camp weighing more than 300 
pounds, slimmed down and carried the team by himself for much of 
the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing with his back to the basket more than at any time in his  
10-year career, Kemp led Cleveland in scoring (a career-high 20.5 
points per game) and rebounds (9.2 per game). He was also an 
inspirational leader, and would frequently pull aside teammates on 
the floor to point out what they should be doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``He showed a maturity this year that I hadn't seen in him  
before,'' Fratello said. ``He was amazing night in and night out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kemp is convinced that a healthy Cavs squad with a few new  
pieces can compete for the NBA title. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got five starters who can hang with any starting five in  
the league,'' he said. ``We need to improve our bench and score 
more consistently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs aren't planning any major changes for the offseason,  
but CEO Jim Boland said the team was concerned about attendance 
figures that dropped 17 percent. A new uniform could be in the 
works, too, Boland said. 
</P>
<P>
	In acquiring DeClercq from Boston, the Cavs also got a  
first-round draft pick from the Celtics. Cleveland can use the pick 
-- it can not be one of the top three -- this year or in 2000 or 
2001. With that pick and the one they already own, the Cavaliers 
could have two top 10 selections. 
</P>
<P>
	After seeing what the Cavs just went through, Jim Paxson, the  
club's vice president of basketball operations, joked about what 
they might do in the draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe one of our picks ought to be part of the Cleveland  
Clinic,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
