<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Foreign Ministers Meet Over Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- On the sidelines of President Clinton's  
visit, foreign ministers from western powers and Russia met today 
seeking agreement on the outline of a Kosovo peace plan that could 
be endorsed by the United Nations. Getting Russia, which opposes 
NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia, into such a common front could 
increase diplomatic pressure on Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic to settle on NATO's terms. Moscow, a traditional Serb 
ally, appears to be moving toward supporting a key alliance demand: 
a NATO-led international force to secure the return of Kosovo 
refugees. 

</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanian Refugees Stranded  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- Thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees  
trying to cross into Macedonia were stranded at a town inside 
Kosovo today after being turned back overnight by Macedonian 
authorities. A handful who were allowed to enter said a packed 
trainload of refugees was waiting near the border today, its 
occupants ordered to remain on board. The U.N. refugee agency said 
Serb police had beaten back some Kosovo Albanians at the border the 
previous day. 

</P>
<P>
	Bus Accident Kills 22 in E. China  
</P>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- A bus loaded with students veered off a  
road and plunged into a reservoir, killing 22 people and injuring 
15 in eastern China, state media reported Thursday. The bus was 
carrying 43 middle-school students, two teachers and four other 
people when it crashed yesterday into the Changting Reservoir near 
the city of Hangzhou, the Xinhua News Agency said. Ten people were 
still missing today, Xinhua said. It did not say how many students 
were among the dead. Police were investigating the cause of the 
crash, and the driver was detained for questioning, the report 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Inspect North Korean Site  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A U.S. team will begin inspecting a  
possible nuclear weapons site in North Korea on May 18, South 
Korean officials said today. About 15 American officials and 
nuclear experts will spend several days inspecting the site at 
Kumchang-ri, northwest of the North's capital of Pyongyang, they 
said. At least two inspections are planned to clear U.S. suspicions 
that the communist country may be reactivating a nuclear weapons 
program frozen under a 1994 agreement with Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Powerful Storms Strike Tennessee  
</P>
<P>
	LINDEN, Tenn. (AP) -- A line of powerful storms blew through  
western Tennessee early today, destroying homes, closing schools 
and damaging buildings in 30 counties. At least four people were 
killed. Two of the victims, a man and woman, died in a Linden home 
that was destroyed last night by straight-line winds, said Capt. 
Gary Rogers of the Perry County rescue service. A 14-year-old girl 
who was missing Wednesday night was found early today and taken to 
a hospital where she died on arrival, according to officials. The 
fourth victim was killed when his car hit a tree that had been 
blown across the highway in Madison County, about 80 miles 
northeast of Memphis. 

</P>
<P>
	Source: Amy Fisher Granted Parole  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A parole board has voted 2-1 to release Amy  
Fisher after nearly seven years in prison for shooting her lover's 
wife in the face, The Associated Press has learned. She is expected 
to be freed next week, according to a state official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. A Division of Parole spokesman would say 
only that Ms. Fisher would be notified of the panel's decision 
today. Ms. Fisher was 16 when she shot Mary Jo Buttafuoco in the 
head at her home on New York's Long Island in 1992. 

</P>
<P>
	Missing WWII Soviet Soldiers Found  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Scout groups have found and buried the remains of  
3,400 soldiers and civilians from a major World War II battlefield 
during the past 10 years, a news agency reported today. The youth 
groups organize regular expeditions to the Kursk battlefield to 
locate the remains of soldiers killed in the 1943 battle that took 
place 300 miles south of Moscow, the ITAR-Tass news agency 
reported. Efforts are made to identify the remains from dog tags 
and other evidence before the bodies are buried in formal 
ceremonies. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Surge  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The main Tokyo stock index 3.59 was percent higher  
today. The Nikkei gained 599.08 points to close at 17,300.61. 

</P>
<P>
	Dodgers 8, Expos 2  
</P>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Jamie Arnold allowed only one hit in 6 2-3  
scoreless innings in his first major league start, and Gary 
Sheffield homered twice last night as the Los Angeles Dodgers 
defeated the Montreal Expos 8-2. Arnold, pitching in place of 
injured Carlos Perez, held the Expos hitless until Orlando Cabrera 
singled leading off the sixth. Sheffield hit a three-run homer off 
Javier Vazquez in the third for a 3-0 lead. He hit his seventh home 
run, a solo shot, in the ninth off Guierrmo Mota. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
</P>
