<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Widow of Celtics Star Testifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- After days of tests prompted by Reggie Lewis'  
collapse during a playoff game, team doctors broke the news to the 
Boston Celtics captain and his wife: The basketball star had a 
life-threatening heart condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was devastating,'' Lewis' widow recalled as she testified  
Thursday during the malpractice trial stemming from the player's 
death in 1993. ``Reggie had experienced excellent health up to that 
point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Harris-Lewis detailed the subsequent search for a second  
opinion that led her to Dr. Gilbert Mudge, a highly respected 
Boston cardiologist. Mudge eventually discounted the potentially 
career-ending diagnosis of heart arrhythmia and told Lewis he had a 
less serious neurological condition that causes fainting spells. 
</P>
<P>
	Three months later, Lewis collapsed and died while practicing  
jump shots at Brandeis University. He was 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis sued Mudge and two doctors who consulted on the  
case, Mark Creager and Peter Friedman, claiming they misdiagnosed 
and mistreated Lewis' condition. A third consultant settled with 
Harris-Lewis for an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge has said he was unable to diagnose Lewis properly because  
he lied about cocaine use. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, under questioning by her lawyer, Robert Harley,  
Harris-Lewis denied her late husband ever used illegal drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was totally against it,'' she said, adding that having  
grown up in rough neighborhoods -- she in Bridgeport, Conn., and 
Lewis in Baltimore -- both had seen lives destroyed by drugs. ``It 
wasn't part of our lifestyle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After collasping during a playoff game against Charlotte in  
1993, Lewis was diagnosed with arrhythmia and told he might need to 
wear a pacemaker. 
</P>
<P>
	The unexpectedly dire news, along with Harris-Lewis' displeasure  
at the way the doctors seemed to be keeping the couple in the dark 
while releasing information to the media, led her to seek advice 
from a friend at Brigham and Women's Hospital. He recommended 
Mudge. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis recalled how after getting the referral, Lewis  
stripped off the heart monitors attached to his chest and left New 
England Baptist in the middle of the night for a meeting with 
Mudge. 
</P>
<P>
	The cardiologist initially agreed with the arrhythmia diagnosis,  
Harris-Lewis said. But after ordering further tests, he revised his 
opinion and told Lewis he suffered from neurocardiogenic syncope -- 
and could, in all likelihood, return to professional basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were obviously happy,'' Harris-Lewis recalled. Her lawyer  
then asked if she believed the advice and trusted Mudge. She 
answered yes to both questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis, who met Lewis when both were students at  
Northeastern University, is suing to recover money he would have 
made had he lived, estimates of which have ranged from $40 million 
to more than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the doctors have suggested the Lewises had incentive  
to lie about drug use, including the Celtics' contract and 
insurance policy that would have been nullified by such activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis, who lives in the Boston area with her 6-year-old  
son and 5-year-old daughter, is scheduled to resume her testimony 
Friday morning in Suffolk Superior Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
