<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bombing Continues in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A NATO missile slammed into a  
residential area in Serbia's second largest city and allied jets 
struck a chemical plant in round-the-clock bombings on Yugoslav 
targets Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Four people were injured Thursday afternoon when a bomb fell  
between a school and a residential building in battered Novi Sad, 
local Studio B TV reported. The bomb smashed windows in surrounding 
buildings and left behind a huge crater. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO struck Novi Sad again hours later, before dawn Friday.  
Powerful detonations were also heard in the southern city of Nis, 
the private Beta news agency reported, without giving details on 
the possible targets at eitehr site. Yugoslav media also reported a 
raid early Friday near Sremska Mitrovica, 45 miles west of 
Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	During the day, NATO struck across Kosovo, where Serb forces  
continue to battle the ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army. Four 
civilians were wounded when the allies targeted Lipljan, about 10 
miles south of the provincial capital, Pristina, state-run media 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in Serbia, NATO missiles struck a chemical factory  
near the Danube River port of Prahovo in eastern Serbia on the 
border with Romania, the state-run Tanjug news agency said. One 
person was reported injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Another raid just before midnight Thursday destroyed a railway  
bridge northeast of Belgrade near the Romanian border, Beta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Predawn strikes Thursday morning hit two fuel depots in a major  
industrial center near Nis. A bridge near Novi Pazar in 
southwestern Serbia and a military airfield nearby in central 
Serbia were also destroyed late Wednesday, Montenegrin radio 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In the capital, where power supplies were still patchy following  
Sunday's bombings of two power plants, air raid warnings sounded 
several times but there no reports of any strikes on the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's attacks came as foreign ministers from Russia and the  
major Western powers, meeting in Germany, agreed on a draft plan 
for ending the Kosovo conflict, including the deployment of an 
international force to keep the peace after the withdrawal of 
Yugoslav forces. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO launched airstrikes against Yugoslavia on March 24 in an  
attempt to stop atrocities against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. 
Since then, more than one-third of Kosovo's 2 million population 
have fled the province, mostly into Macedonia and Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	As the foreign ministers gathered in Bonn, Yugoslavian President  
Slobodan Milosevic met with Greek envoy Carolos Papaouillas, 
presumably to discuss the outline of the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, state-run media quoted Milosevic as saying NATO must stop  
its air campaign before any peace efforts can go ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic said a ``just solution on all open issues can be  
reached through the political process of direct talks, which is 
predicated upon an end of the aggression and return of peace and 
return of Yugoslav citizens to their homes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian President Milan Milutinovic, who also attended the  
meeting, was quoted saying NATO ``aggression must stop 
immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic has refused NATO demands that an armed NATO-led force  
be allowed into Kosovo to protect returning refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview published Thursday by the Austrian daily Kurier,  
Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic said his country would 
agree to a U.N.-led force. 
</P>
<P>
	``We accept an international presence, a U.N. mission,'' he told  
the paper. ``The mandate, structure and number of troops should be 
agreed upon between Yugoslavia and U.N. Secretary General Kofi 
Annan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jovanovic refused to comment on whether or not the force would  
be armed. He insisted a U.N. force could not include NATO members 
participating in the bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
