<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:08:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuggets Improve, but Disappoint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- With only one winning season in the '90s, maybe a  
change in scenery will help the Denver Nuggets change their 
misfortune. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nuggets rounded out a dismal decade with a 14-36 record in  
their final season in McNichols Arena, which will be torn down in 
favor of the $160 million Pepsi Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Denver improved its victory total in a lockout-shortened  
season, the Nuggets struggled to jell under first-year head coach 
Mike D'Antoni. They beat just three playoff-bound teams, never won 
more than two in a row and finished with seven straight losses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite frankly, I think we need a break,'' guard Chauncey  
Billups said. ``It was a long 90 days ... a long 90 days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The toll of playing four and sometimes five games a week was  
particularly difficult on the young Nuggets as they tried to find 
chemistry with several new players such as Billups, Nick Van Exel 
and Antonio McDyess. 
</P>
<P>
	Also hampering their progress was the loss of first-round draft  
pick Raef LaFrentz, who averaged 13.8 points and 7.6 rebounds in 12 
games before suffering season-ending knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Raef was healthy, we beat the Lakers and Utah at home,''  
forward Danny Fortson said. ``You need to have an extra big guy out 
there. Once he went down, it was hard to recover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LaFrentz's absence forced the Nuggets to play the 6-foot-7  
Fortson in the middle, where he often gave up five inches to 
opposing centers. He responded gamely, however, finishing fourth in 
the NBA in rebounding with 11.6 boards per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver's other main highlight was the successful return of  
McDyess, who spent a mediocre season in Phoenix before the Nuggets 
lured him back with a six-year, $67.5 million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	McDyess, originally acquired by Denver in a draft-day trade in  
1995, averaged a career-best 21 points and 10.7 rebounds, but was 
clearly drained after fighting constant double teams while playing 
nearly 39 minutes a night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wears on your body and makes your legs tired,'' McDyess  
said. ``At the end, I didn't have any legs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finding someone to complement McDyess is one of several key  
issues for Denver in the offseason. Owner Bill Laurie, who bought 
the Nuggets last month, also must decide whether to bring back Van 
Exel and D'Antoni. 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie has remained noncommittal about D'Antoni, a coaching star  
in Italy before his move to the NBA. The players believe D'Antoni 
deserves at least one more season to prove himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a rookie coach taking over a team that had won 11  
games,'' Billups said. ``You've got to give the man a chance. 
Everybody in this locker room knows how good he is. We're all 
behind him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Van Exel, the petulant point guard is a free agent this  
summer but says his top priority is re-signing with the Nuggets. 
General manager Dan Issel has defended Van Exel against critics who 
say he is moody and has a shoot-first, pass-later mentality. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan's pretty much told me that he would love to re-sign me, so  
he's given me all the confidence in the world,'' Van Exel said. ``I 
think I can really trust him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Exel, who stands to make more money by staying in Denver,  
also said he also feels obligated to McDyess after lobbying his 
friend to turn down more money in Phoenix and sign with the 
Nuggets. 
</P>
<P>
	``After begging him to come here and telling him we would make  
the playoffs, it really didn't happen this year,'' Van Exel said. 
``To beg him to come here and then to just abandon him, I don't 
think that'd be being a friend.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
