<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barnesandnoble.com Plans IPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Barnesandnoble.com is going ahead with plans for  
an initial public offering of stock despite signs that Wall 
Street's frenzy for Internet-related businesses may be waning. 
</P>
<P>
	The online retailer -- jointly owned by bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble  
and German media conglomerate Bertelsmann -- said Thursday that it 
hopes to raise about $300 million in the IPO, selling 25 million 
shares, or about 18 percent of the company, for about $12 each. A 
date for the offering hasn't been set. 
</P>
<P>
	The money will help the New York-based company in the fierce  
battle for market share against Amazon.com and the swarms of 
smaller outfits vying for a piece of the burgeoning online 
retailing business. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks, especially IPOs, have been the darling of Wall  
Street for the past year, with investors embracing just about any 
company with online operations or even online plans. Many IPOs have 
doubled in the first days of trading and kept on going. 
</P>
<P>
	But this may not be the right time to take an Internet company  
public. For example, the online real estate firm Comps.com sold 
shares earlier this week for $15 each, but had fallen to $13.50 by 
Thursday afternoon on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Internet ``stalwarts'' such as Amazon.com and eBay  
have slumped recently as investors shifted away from high-flying 
technology issues in favor of long-neglected industrial companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, the euphoria for Internet stocks is a little  
overdone,'' said Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at 
George K. Baum &AMP; Co., in Kansas City, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, it is safe to say that barnesandnoble.com has a better  
name than an unknown xyz.com company,'' he said. ``But this market 
is still oversaturated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some analysts say that barnesandnoble.com's IPO may do  
well merely because it is a well-known name and investors have long 
liked the online-bookselling concept. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the last week, we've seen some lower quality IPOs,'' said  
Linda R. Killian, who evaluates IPOs for Renaissance Capital Corp. 
``These companies aren't unique in any way. Barnesandnoble.com is 
not like those.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like many online companies, barnesandnoble.com is a  
fast-growing, but money-losing business. 
</P>
<P>
	In reporting its IPO plans to the Securities and Exchange  
Commission, the company said it lost $20.2 million in the first 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales, however, rose to $32.3 million, an increase of 25 percent  
from the fourth quarter of 1998 and up 259 percent from year-ago 
levels. 
</P>
<P>
	The online bookseller also said it now has 1.7 million  
customers, with more than 450,000 shopping for the first time 
during the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	But barnesandnoble.com still lags behind Amazon.com, which is  
quickly building itself into an online shopping hub with a broad 
array of books, music, video, gifts and auctions. Amazon's customer 
tally was 8 million customer at the end of the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnesandnoble.com stock will trade under the symbol ``BNBN'' on  
the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second time in a year that plans have been announced  
to sell shares of barnesandnoble.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Last August, Barnes &AMP; Noble announced its intention to take its  
online operation public, but decided to postpone the offering after 
Bertelsmann purchased a 50 percent stake in the company. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
