<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Cider House' Staged Off-Broadway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In ``The Cider House Rules,'' orphan Homer Wells  
wonders if he can be the hero of his own life. It's a personal and 
moral dilemma audiences should find intriguing -- and more than a 
little moving. 
</P>
<P>
	The wide-eyed, innocent lad has plenty of opportunity to test  
his mettle in this ambitious stage adaptation of John Irving's 
sprawling novel that has made its way to New York after productions 
by the Seattle Repertory Company and the Mark Taper Forum in Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	New Yorkers are seeing only part one of the show at  
off-Broadway's Atlantic Theater Company. Production of part two 
depends on the first half's reception. Judging from this terrific 
initial effort, the Atlantic should proceed immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Subtitled ``Here at St. Cloud's,'' the three-hour-plus  
production is story theater at its crowd-pleasing best. In fact, it 
takes the form a step further, artfully blending narrative and 
dialogue lifted directly from the book within adapter Peter 
Parnell's careful condensation of the voluminous plot. 
</P>
<P>
	The effort, directed by Tom Hulce and Jane Jones, is seamless,  
with 19 performers slipping in and out of multiple roles as quickly 
as they can change costumes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cider House'' is a big novel with big themes, told in an  
expansive, leisurely style that would do Charles Dickens proud. In 
fact, young Homer reveres David Copperfield, another orphan who 
makes his way in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Irving populates his novel with a parade of memorable characters  
who span more than half a century, from the 1880s into the days 
following World War II. Central to his tale is the relationship 
between Homer and Dr. Wilbur Larch, a man who does what he calls 
the Lord's work and the devil's work at St. Cloud's, an orphanage 
in rural Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Larch delivers unwanted babies -- and also aborts them, depending  
on the wishes of the mother. ``Here at St. Cloud's, I try to 
consider, with each rule I make or break, that my first priority is 
an orphan's future,'' Larch says. 
</P>
<P>
	Homer is the one true orphan at St. Cloud's, adopted and then  
returned by three different families. Larch, his two adoring nurses 
and an equally unadoptable female orphan named Melony become his 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the three leads from the Los Angeles production have come  
with the show to New York -- and deservedly so. Josh Hamilton could 
not be better as the bewildered, sweet-tempered Homer, a young man 
whose convictions are tested daily by what he learns of Larch's 
doings at St. Cloud's. 
</P>
<P>
	Irving's novel doesn't take the easy way out in dealing with the  
question of abortion. The author clearly -- and clinically -- 
presents both sides of the argument, something Parnell also does in 
his stage version. 
</P>
<P>
	Jillian Armenante is nothing less than astonishing as the  
snarling, tomboyish Melony, who instructs Homer in the mysteries of 
sex. Armenante, a solidly built woman, barrels through the role 
with audacious authority. It is a brazen, career-defining 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	A ruddy Colm Meaney, a fine new addition, displays a determined  
yet kind manner that gives Larch moral weight, the authority to 
make life-and-death decisions at St. Cloud's. 
</P>
<P>
	What's curious about this ``Cider House Rules'' is that it  
leaves the audience hanging. The ``rules'' of the title are never 
introduced. They await explanation in the second half, which 
apparently Parnell, Hulce and Jones are revising extensively. Let's 
hope they work quickly. There is an audience eager to know what 
happens to Homer and his dealings with ``The Cider House Rules.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
