<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Gets Marine Pilot Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Prosecutors accused a Marine pilot  
Thursday of knowing full well that a tape he helped get rid of was 
going to be destroyed to impede an investigation into an air 
accident that killed 20 people in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who in this situation had the most to gain to make sure there  
wasn't any information about this flight?'' said prosecutor Maj. 
Daniel Daugherty in his closing statement at Capt. Richard Ashby's 
trial. ``He handed over that tape knowing it was going to be 
destroyed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby's lawyer, Frank Spinner, said Ashby had no criminal intent  
but had ``exercised poor judgment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the judge, Col. Alvin Keller, spent an hour instructing  
jurors, who will begin deliberating Friday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury must decide whether Ashby, 32, of Mission Viejo,  
Calif., is guilty of obstruction of justice and conspiracy. If 
convicted, he could be sent to prison for up to 10 years or 
dismissed from the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby was acquitted of manslaughter charges by a separate jury  
in March. If acquitted of these charges, he would start F-18 
fighter jet training. 
</P>
<P>
	After the jet hit the cable and landed, Ashby put the tape in  
his flight suit pocket. He retrieved it a few days later, wanting 
to see what was on it, he testified, but couldn't find a video 
player and handed it over to the navigator, Capt. Joseph 
Schweitzer, 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer, who was convicted of the charges Ashby faces and was  
kicked out of the Marines, said he threw the tape into a bonfire. 
Schweitzer said he feared that the tape, which included images of 
his face, would be played in the Italian media with scenes of the 
carnage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
