<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 10:33:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disney-Katzenberg Feud Very Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- After months of often tense negotiations,  
Jeffrey Katzenberg was comfortably back in the Disney family. His 
1988 contract to run the movie studio guaranteed him not just 
riches but the opportunity to continue working with a longtime 
friend, Michael Eisner. 
</P>
<P>
	In a handwritten note to the Walt Disney Co. chairman,  
Katzenberg thanked him for his ``extraordinary patience and care 
and understanding,'' and signed off, ``I'm deeply appreciative and 
do love you for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The love affair didn't last.  
</P>
<P>
	In makeshift courtrooms before a retired judge, divorce  
proceedings are under way, the messy aftermath of the 
disintegration of a Hollywood power marriage. It's the kind of feud 
the movie business rarely sees, one that breaks a sacred industry 
taboo: Never air grievances publicly. 
</P>
<P>
	Emotions have flared in what should have been a dry contract  
dispute. Katzenberg is suing Disney, alleging he's owed at least 
$250 million in an incentive bonus due to him after he left his job 
as head of the movie division in 1994, having overseen its 
triumphant return to animated-film supremacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney counters that Katzenberg forfeited that bonus because he  
resigned two years before the end of his six-year contract. 
Katzenberg went on to help Steven Spielberg and David Geffen form 
DreamWorks SKG, where he oversees animation. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides reached a partial settlement, which was sealed by the  
court but was said by the Hollywood Reporter to be a $77 million 
Disney check to Katzenberg. The case went to phase two April 26 -- 
arbitration by a retired Superior Court judge -- to decide how big 
Katzenberg's bonus should be. 
</P>
<P>
	It is there, in a lawyers' office on Avenue of Stars, that the  
drama and incongruity of the case is emerging -- from nasty memos on 
Disney stationery featuring a smiling Mickey Mouse, to bitter 
exchanges about ``personal animosity'' and ``the little midget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In opening statements, Katzenberg's attorney Bert Fields said  
this case of a mouse house divided boiled down to one thing: ``The 
personal animosity of one man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That would be Eisner, who became Disney's chairman in 1984 after  
resigning as president of Paramount Pictures when he wasn't 
promoted to chairman. One his first moves that year was to hire 
Katzenberg, his former Paramount movie chief, as chairman of 
Disney's film division. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Eisner and Katzenberg, Disney underwent a dramatic  
transition from a moribund film and theme park company to the 
entertainment behemoth of today. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1988, Katzenberg renegotiated his contract, getting a  
boatload of goodies, including $5 million for a Malibu beach house, 
a $750,000 annual salary, generous bonuses and, most importantly, 
what he says was the 2 percent incentive bonus on future income, 
payable when he left the company. 
</P>
<P>
	This, Katzenberg believes, would be a lump-sum estimate of a  
percentage of all the future rental income and theatrical 
re-release ticket sales of some of the biggest animation films of 
all time, including ``The Lion King'' and ``Aladdin,'' as well as a 
piece of every T-shirt, doll, game, mug and what-not sold in Disney 
Stores around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time the deal was completed, Disney was on the brink of  
great success in animation. Though slow to recognize the potential 
of animation, Katzenberg embraced it and got credit for its rebirth 
at Disney. 
</P>
<P>
	The warm feelings of the times were reflected in Katzenberg's  
1988 happy note to Eisner, recalling the negotiations as ``very 
difficult on all of us'' but thanking Eisner for his support. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been together a very long time,'' Katzenberg wrote. ``In  
fact, in terms of Hollywood timekeeping, about three lifetimes so 
far. I not only hope but I'm counting on us staying together 
forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forever lasted five years. By 1993, their relationship soured.  
</P>
<P>
	Eisner felt that Katzenberg was taking too much credit for  
animation and not enough responsibility for the lackluster 
live-action films. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, after company President Frank Wells died in a helicopter  
crash in 1994, Katzenberg approached Eisner about assuming Wells' 
position. Eisner says in his 1998 autobiography, ``Work in 
Progress,'' that the request came just 36 hours after Wells' death, 
leaving him ``stunned'' at Katzenberg's insensitivity. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisner has said he and key members of the Disney board didn't  
see Katzenberg as presidential material. Eisner considered him a 
fine movie executive but didn't think he had the maturity or 
big-picture focus for the more important job. Eisner complained 
that Katzenberg focused on his own agenda and wasn't concerned 
enough about the company as a whole. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg, in turn, was shocked that he wasn't being considered  
for the post, since he had dutifully served Disney for a decade. In 
parting ways with Disney, Katzenberg says, he made only two 
requests of Eisner: that he get his fat incentive bonus and that 
the separation be amicable. 
</P>
<P>
	Forget it.  
</P>
<P>
	Disney nixed the incentive bonus, because, Disney says,  
Katzenberg was never entitled to it in the first place. But 
Katzenberg testified that at a meeting at his house Eisner 
condescendingly told him, ``If I behaved myself, in a couple of 
weeks he would revisit'' the issue. Eisner was angry the divorce 
proceeding was being played out in the press, and he blamed 
Katzenberg for the leaks. 
</P>
<P>
	In unusually blunt language, Eisner testified: ``If he's going  
to play this media game, this deceptive game, this disingenuous 
game ... I was simply not going to pay his money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This media game, as Eisner saw it, was part of what he called  
Katzenberg's ``dark side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eisner vented much of his anger to Tony Schwartz, the  
collaborator on his autobiography. Schwartz's notes included this 
quotation from Eisner about Katzenberg: ``I think I hate the little 
midget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The remark about the 5-foot-4-inch executive never made it into  
the book. But Eisner was confronted with the notes by Katzenberg's 
lawyer, Bert Fields. Eisner said he probably was joking or 
temporarily angry. Then Eisner issued what many saw as a thinly 
veiled threat to Fields and Katzenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	The line of questioning was ``ill-advised,'' an icy Eisner told  
the lawyer. He further said, the questioning was ``not in your 
client's best interest or mine, but particularly your client's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trial continues next week.  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 11:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Lower, Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the other major  
currencies in European trading Thursday. Gold rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0806, up from $1.0664 on Wednesday,  
while the British pound was quoted at $1.6408, up from $1.6298. 
Later in New York, the euro was quoted at $1.0796, and the pound 
was quoted at $1.6404. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell to 120.82 Japanese yen, down from 121.32 on  
Wednesday. In New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 120.81 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe compared with late Wednesday:  
1.4853 Swiss francs, down from 1.5045; and 1.4494 Canadian dollars, 
down from 1.4558 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8099 German marks,  
down from 1.8340; 6.0703 French francs, down from 6.1511; 2.0393 
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0665; 1,791.85 Italian lire, down from 
1,815.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold in London closed at $288.45 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$286.80 on Wednesday. In Zurich, the bid price was $288.35, up from 
$286.65. Gold rose $2.50 in Hong Kong to close at $285.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.39 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.36. 
</P>
