<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Plans for Star Wars Opening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Seth Miller has been preparing his clients for a  
month. Come May 19, he and his staff hope to be in a galaxy far, 
far away, soaking in the return of Star Wars. 
</P>
<P>
	Call 'em geeks. Call 'em hip. Just don't look for many Star Wars  
buffs at work on The Big Day, the Wednesday release of the latest 
episode in the galactic epic. 
</P>
<P>
	They're closing down offices, renting out theaters, taking weeks  
of vacation to stand in line for tickets. By one estimate, more 
than 2 million workers could skip work for the opening. An informal 
national holiday is brewing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing's that important that we can't skip work for the  
day,'' said Miller, president of Boston-based Miller Systems, an 
Internet consulting company with a staff of seven. ``As soon as the 
date was announced for the movie, I decided that had to be a 
company holiday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Brandon Herman, May is a self-declared holiday. He told his  
parents that he won't be working at his family's video production 
company most of the month due to the movie -- the first release of a 
Star Wars film since 1983. Tickets go on sale May 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've waited 16 years,'' he said earnestly, standing his ground  
in the ticket line outside a New York cinema as fellow fans around 
him dueled with light-sabers. ``I can't wait any longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once in a while, news, sports or scandals intrude on work life.  
Before the World Series began night games in 1971, fans kept radios 
on at work during games. O.J. Simpson's murder trial distracted 
workers for months; the verdict stopped work nationwide in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``They tend to be events that feel close to home, that feel  
apocalyptic in nature, overwhelming,'' said Talmadge Wright, an 
associate professor of sociology at Loyola University in Chicago 
and a follower of pop culture. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks partly to a service economy that venerates creativity,  
the Star Wars lexicon is already part of many workplaces' culture, 
particularly in high-tech fields. ``May the Force be with you!'', 
co-workers say. ``Try not. Do... or do not. There is no try.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Especially for Baby Boomers, who've grown up with the Jedi and  
now call the shots in many offices, it's a no-brainer to decide to 
shut down the company for the long-awaited movie. 
</P>
<P>
	Ric Edelman, head of Edelman Financial Services in Fairfax, Va.,  
is having the three earlier Star Wars films shown at his firm -- 
twice -- having discovered 7 percent of his 90 employees hadn't seen 
any. He also hopes to take his entire staff to see the new film. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those of us who've seen them find it hard to believe there's  
anybody in America who hasn't,'' roars Edelman. 
</P>
<P>
	Lesley Roberts, Edelman's human resources director and one of  
the 7 percent, is taking her education good-naturedly. She 
describes the excitement as ``interesting.'' Star Wars talk has 
``become more a part of my daily routine,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheree Franklin also finds it hard to concentrate on her work  
these days -- but she's ecstatic. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Franklin, a human resources director who watches the trilogy  
at least twice a month, has been taking a daily break for months to 
look at Web sites devoted to the movie. During opening week, she 
and other employees at GoldMine Software of Pacific Palisades, 
Calif., will see the movie when their boss rents a theater. 
</P>
<P>
	When Wil Schroter heard that the movie was coming, he quickly  
rented a 500-seat theater in Columbus, Ohio, for employees at his 
Internet consulting firm, NGDA Interactive Communications, and 
their guests. But their enthusiasm surprised even Schroter, a 
die-hard fan. 
</P>
<P>
	When he announced his coup, he got requests for 100 tickets in  
10 minutes -- the biggest response he'd ever gotten to a company 
e-mail. To complete the May 21 festivities, he's throwing a 
pre-screening office party and encouraging the staff to work in 
costume that day. 
</P>
<P>
	Office costumes, playing hooky? Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas  
Inc., an employment agency, estimates 2.2 million employees could 
skip work to see the movie on opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	Some might ask if all the hoopla won't hurt productivity. But  
economist Sung Won Sohn, of Wells Fargo in Minneapolis, says any 
dip in labor will be offset by a boost in spending, be it on 
tickets, toys or popcorn. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, you won't catch him taking the day off or standing in  
line to see the movie. He's a Star Wars fan but says he'll wait a 
week or two. 
</P>
<P>
	``My time is more valuable,'' he chuckled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
