<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 06:32:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Scots Are Voting for Own Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) -- Scots voted today for their first  
separate Parliament in three centuries, torn between enthusiasm and 
trepidation about the prospects of having independence-seeking 
nationalists as their main opposition party. 
</P>
<P>
	The three million Welsh also voted for a separate, but less  
powerful assembly under the constitutional shake-up that Prime 
Minister Tony Blair's two-year-old government sees as 
decentralizing the United Kingdom, not breaking it up. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern Ireland has already elected an assembly.  
</P>
<P>
	For 25 million English voters, nothing has changed. Today was  
simply a polling day for local authorities. The balloting is a test 
of Blair's record popularity ratings, although fewer than 
one-in-four eligible Britons are likely to vote. 
</P>
<P>
	In Edinburgh, retiree David Barber was among the first to turn  
out in drizzling rain at an elementary school in the Marchmont 
district. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm voting tactically. I don't want the Scottish National  
Party to get anywhere near Parliament,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedraggled posters of Britain's governing Labor Party, and the  
black thistle of the Scottish National Party flapped on street 
corners as widespread rain poured down from the remote Orkney 
Islands in the north to the big cities of Edinburgh and Glasgow. 
</P>
<P>
	``We won't get independence this time, but we are on our way,''  
said Karen Morgan, 33, after voting nationalist in Edinburgh's 
inner-city South Side district. 
</P>
<P>
	With Labor and the nationalists battling for control of the  
129-member Parliament, opinion polls at the end of a five-week 
campaign indicated that Labor will win the largest bloc of seats 
but fall short of overall control. 
</P>
<P>
	The nationalists were set for transformation from a fringe party  
in the House of Commons in London to the official opposition in 
Scotland. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the very least we should make sure that this Parliament is  
controlled from Scotland, not by Labor in London,'' SNP leader Alex 
Salmond declared late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Blair's Scottish Secretary, Donald Dewar, who is almost sure to  
become Scotland's new leader, argues that England and Scotland both 
benefit from the 300-year union. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea that we go in for the destruction and dismantling of  
all our common endeavors ... I just don't think it makes sense,'' 
added Dewar, a 60-year-old Glasgow lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Parliament will control a swath of domestic affairs,  
including health, education, transport and sport, and -- unlike the 
60-member Welsh assembly in Cardiff -- have powers to legislate and 
raise taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The nationalists, neck-and-neck with Labor 18 months ago, accuse  
the anti-independence Scottish press and the government of playing 
on fears that an independent Scotland would quickly fall billions 
into debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls put the nationalists on 30 percent support, some 12  
points behind Labor, with the rest of decided voters split between 
the minority parties, the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	But some one-fourth of voters were apparently undecided.  
</P>
<P>
	Blair's main problem in the local elections in England is  
getting the vote out. The Scots and Welsh are more likely to vote 
because the local polls coincide with the assembly votes. 
</P>
<P>
	At stake are seats on 362 local councils in England, Wales and  
Scotland. The Conservative Party, the battered, main opposition in 
the Commons, was expected by some analysts to gain around 1,000 of 
those 13,000 seats. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no elections in London this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 06:32:28 </DATE_TIME>
