<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 06:55:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skier Uses Cell Phone in Avalanche </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALTA, Utah (AP) -- A skier buried chest-high in an avalanche  
found his cell phone pushed against his face in a jacket pocket and 
managed to dial for help. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Ron Clark, a Pleasant Grove surgeon, his two sons and 12  
other skiers and snowboarders were swept up by a slide that roared 
down Lone Peak Ridge on Wednesday. In the end, Clark's eldest son, 
12-year-old Craig, broke loose and was able to free his father and 
11-year-old brother before rescuers arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	The slide at the Alta Ski Resort in Little Cottonwood Canyon, 18  
miles southeast of Salt Lake City, ripped down a lower slope for 
about 1,000 yards, snapping thick trees on the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a two-second warning and we were completely unprepared  
for it,'' Clark said. ``The slide just took us forward.'' He said 
his jacket was twisted over his head by the force of the slide, 
placing his cell phone in a pocket in front of his face. 
</P>
<P>
	When they arrived, rescuers used dogs, beacons and probes to  
make sure no one else remained buried. About three hours after the 
slide, authorities called off the search, saying everyone was 
accounted for. No one was seriously hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``These folks are extremely lucky,'' said Sgt. Lane Larkin of  
the Salt Lake County sheriff's department. 
</P>
<P>
	The ski area closed weeks ago, so enthusiasts must climb the  
mountain instead of using lifts. Ski patrol workers are also sparse 
as the season winds down, leaving back country skiers on their own, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Avalanche danger was high on Wednesday, with warming  
temperatures and 40 inches of snow in the area since Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 06:05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Claims Rise by 6,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing applications  
for unemployment benefits rose slightly last week after two 
consecutive weekly declines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported today that 301,000 people filed  
for jobless benefits, an increase of 6,000 from the previous week 
and about in line with economists' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The benefit applications had dipped below the 300,000 level the  
previous week to 295,000. From late January through mid-March, the 
weekly applications number remained below 300,000 for a nine week 
stretch, the longest period since 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is scheduled to issue the unemployment report for  
April on Friday and many economists believe it will remain at a 
29-year low of 4.2 percent, demonstrating that America's sparkling 
economy is continuing to power ahead despite overseas financial 
turmoil that has pushed one-third of the world into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	While more than 300,000 manufacturing jobs have been lost in the  
past year, reflecting lost export markets for American companies, 
the continued low unemployment has kept consumers on a buying 
spree. For the first three months of this year, the overall economy 
grew at a robust annual rate of 4.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The good combination of low unemployment and rapid growth is  
occuring in an environment with little inflation, which has stayed 
under control despite the tight labor markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Most analysts believe the Federal Reserve, which next meets to  
set interest rates on May 20, will be content to leave rates 
unchanged and let the good times keep rolling along. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Fed said that its latest nationwide survey of  
economic conditions found that U.S. manufacturers are bouncing back 
from Asian currency crisis. The Fed said the improvement in 
manufacturing was broad-based -- ranging from increased demand for 
medical and automotive equipment reported by the Fed's Boston 
branch to solid orders for computers and telecommunications 
equipment reported by the San Francisco Fed. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless claims report today showed that a four-week moving  
average for claims was essentially unchanged at 307,000, compared 
to 307,500 the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	In state-by-state data which lags the national figures by one  
week, the Labor Department said 35 states and territories had 
decreases in claims for the week ending April 24 and 17 had 
declines with one reporting no change. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest declines were reported by New York, down 8,563;  
California, down 4,117 because of fewer layoffs in agriculture; 
North Carolina, where claims fell by 2,704 because of fewer layoffs 
in the apparel industry and Ohio, where claims fell by 2,315. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest increase in unemployment claims was in  
Massachusetts, a rise of 4,639, reflecting increased layoffs in 
service industries; Rhode Island, an increase of 1,161 because of 
higher layoffs in service industries and manufacturing and 
Illinois, with an increase of 1,099 because increased layoffs in 
trade, service industries and manufacturing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 14:35:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celtics Need Defense, Conditioning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Red Auerbach shuffled into the winning locker room  
and greeted the smiling coach, who planted a kiss on the bald head 
of the Celtics' 81-year-old patriarch. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe next year that room will belong to Boston, who Auerbach  
coached to nine NBA titles. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday night, the winners were the Charlotte Hornets, who  
had just beaten Boston 133-129 in double overtime in the teams' 
season finale. And the coach, Paul Silas, was a reminder of how far 
the Celtics have dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	Silas played on two of their 16 championship teams in his four  
years with the club from 1972 through 1976. In the last six years, 
the Celtics haven't had a single winning record and reached the 
playoffs just once. 
</P>
<P>
	They have outstanding offensive talent, led by Antoine Walker,  
Ron Mercer and Paul Pierce, but the lack of practice in the 
shortened season may have hurt a young team like Boston more than 
experienced clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This year all we did was give out the exam. Here's what we're  
playing. Here's how we have to play it. We never taught class,'' 
coach Rick Pitino said. ``Now, basically, we have the opportunity 
to do what we enjoy the most and that's teach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In their second season under Pitino, the Celtics dropped from a  
36-46 record to 19-31. In his previous four coaching jobs -- with 
Boston University, Providence College, the New York Knicks and the 
University of Kentucky -- Pitino's teams improved their records in 
his second year. 
</P>
<P>
	His current players are confident that will happen next season  
if they improve their conditioning and defense and avoid health 
problems that plagued them this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now the chemistry is coming along,'' Mercer said. ``We  
just need some defense. After that, if we stay healthy, we can be a 
very good team. There's not too much that you really have to 
change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Celtics got a sample of what it takes to be successful in  
their last 18 games. They finished at 9-9 after starting at 10-22. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody was playing unselfish,'' Mercer said. ``It didn't  
really matter who scored. Everybody went out (and) we passed the 
ball very well. ... Too bad we couldn't do that the whole year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We made strides the last three or four weeks,'' Walker said.  
``We didn't pack it in and that showed a lot of heart by 
everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The surge coincided with a hamstring injury that forced point  
guard Kenny Anderson to sit out the last 15 games. Boston was 7-8 
with Dana Barros filling his spot after going 12-23 before the 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dana had a wonderful year,'' Pitino said.  
</P>
<P>
	So did Pierce, who was determined to show that nine teams made a  
mistake in allowing the Celtics to draft him with the 10th pick. He 
was second among NBA rookies with 16.5 points and 6.4 rebounds per 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to go in and establish myself right away,'' he said.  
``I think I was able to do that. Still, the goals that I wanted I 
wasn't able to achieve, which is going to the playoffs. But we have 
a nice young corps of guys and I think we're going to have a great 
future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Injuries to Walker, who missed eight games with a sprained ankle  
before playing the last two, and Anderson gave Pitino a chance to 
experiment. He saw the stabilizing presence of Barros, a 10-year 
veteran, and a sign of inside strength when Vitaly Potapenko and 
Tony Battie played together in the frontcourt. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pitino preaches defense first and that was lacking.  
</P>
<P>
	``If our conditioning gets better your defense gets better,'' he  
said. ``This year, because of our average conditioning, we couldn't 
play great defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also thinks Walker, the team captain, can expand his game.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's always going to score a lot of points,'' Pitino said.  
``With the way he can pass the ball, his intelligence on the court, 
if he can average six or seven assists a game, we're going to be 
really tough shooting a high percentage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Celtics made just 43.6 percent of their field goal attempts  
and 69.2 percent of their free throws. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercer, one of their top outside shooters, could be gone before  
next season. He has one year left on his contract and negotiations 
for an extension are expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be a Celtic for life,'' he said, while suggesting  
that business considerations may interfere with that goal. 
</P>
<P>
	But Walker, armed with a long-term contract, will be back. And  
if Mercer stays, the Celtics have a solid young nucleus that 
includes Pierce, Battie and Potapenko along with veterans Barros 
and Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe having a little failure may have woken us up a little  
bit and gotten us in the right path in what we need to do,'' Walker 
said. ``Adversity taught us that defense counts first and offense 
second. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody put us on this big pedestal, that we're supposed to  
be the Utah Jazz,'' he added, without saying who made that 
comparison. ``We're a young team. It's going to take some time to 
build this.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
