<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Gets Jenny Jones Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Jurors spent Thursday weighing the  
evidence in the trial of a lawsuit against ``The Jenny Jones Show'' 
over the death of a gay guest who revealed a crush on another man. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury deliberated for almost seven hours and was scheduled to  
reconvene Friday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, attorney Geoffrey Fieger asked the jury to find  
the show and its corporate owner, Warner Bros., liable for Scott 
Amedure's death and award his family $71.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Amedure, 32, died in 1995, three days after revealing his crush  
on Jonathan Schmitz during a taping of the show. Amedure's family 
contends a mentally ill Schmitz was lured onto the show believing 
he would meet a woman, and was humiliated into murder when his 
secret admirer turned out to be Amedure. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Warner Bros. said Schmitz was solely responsible and  
that he might have killed Amedure because the two had a sexual 
encounter. Fieger denied that allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz was found guilty of murder in 1996, but his conviction  
was thrown out on appeal. His retrial is set for Aug. 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
