<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rise Above 7 Percent / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages  
have risen above the 7.0 percent mark for the second time this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The average this week was 7.02 percent, up from 6.93 percent the  
previous week, Freddie Mac, the mortgage company said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, rates have fluctated between 6.74 percent at  
the end of January and 7.11 percent in mid-March. Before March, 
when rates held above 7.0 percent for three weeks, rates had held 
below that mark since last June. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 6.61 percent this week, up from 6.55 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 5.68 percent, up from 5.63 the week before. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
