<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tougher Rules for NY Fight Judge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Strict background checks, including financial  
disclosures, of title fight judges in New York are now required. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't the boxers that got kayoed, it was the fans,'' Gov.  
George Pataki said of the controversial draw between Lennox Lewis 
and Evander Holyfield that spurred the reforms announced Wednesday 
by Pataki and Attorney General Eliot Spitzer. ``My personal opinion 
is that the decision was indefensible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Sadly, today the public sees boxing's credibility on par with  
that of professional wrestling,'' Spitzer said. ``In short, the 
sweet science has turned sour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Manhattan grand jury is looking into the Lewis-Holyfield  
decision. Most observers felt Lewis won the match for the 
undisputed heavyweight title March 13 at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a lucrative rematch is in the works for Nov. 6 or  
Nov. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd like it to take place in New York state,'' Pataki said.  
``If it does, it's going to be under these new rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pursuing the rematch,'' said Ken Munoz, executive vice  
president of the Garden. ``Frankly, it's somewhat difficult. 
(Promoter Don) King has a lot of offers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Las Vegas is being prominently as the site of a rematch.  
</P>
<P>
	Effective immediately, judges must be sanctioned by the state,  
and judges who reside, or are licensed, in other jurisdictions must 
submit a sworn application for a license and make certain 
disclosures. They include a credit check, revealing pending 
litigations such as bankruptcy or criminal proceedings and any 
financial ties with either boxer, promoter, the venue or television 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile in Washington, a Senate committee approved Wednesday a  
bill aimed at reforming the business side of boxing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Muhammad Ali Reform Act now goes before the full Senate,  
which passed a virtually identical version last year by voice vote. 
The House, however, did not take up the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ali Act would protect boxers from exploitation from  
promoters and managers by requiring specific guidelines for 
contracts and disclosure of the complicated financial dealings 
surrounding big fights. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki directed the New York State Athletic Commission, chaired  
by Mel Southard, to work with federal legislators to get the Ali 
Act passed and signed in law. 
</P>
<P>
	Also to be implemented immediately by the New York Commission  
are the way championship fight judges are selected, and tougher 
standards for becoming a judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Each sanctioning body with an interest in a title fight must  
submit a list of three candidates for judge, instead of one, and 
the commission will select one from each set of candidates. It can 
reject the nominations and select a judge without further 
nomination. If only two sanctioning bodies are involved, the 
commission will select at least one independent judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Judges will need to pass written and oral examinations and  
attend a mandatory annual seminar. 
</P>
<P>
	The following reforms for title fights also will be recommended  
to the Association of Boxing Commissioners at its annual meeting in 
July at Baltimore: 
</P>
<P>
	-- A referee would be required to judge the fight, and his card  
would be considered if the decision is a draw. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Each of the three judges' scorecards would be compared on a  
round-by-round basis, and after each round a consensus would be 
reached by rejecting the decision of the judge in the minority. 
</P>
<P>
	-- And independent poll of boxing writers, broadcasters and  
historian would rank fighters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
