<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Boss Defends Administration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson acknowledged  
massive security breaches at nuclear weapons labs Thursday but said 
in an interview that criticism is ``starting to become a blame 
game'' that could hurt the labs and the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said an interview with The Associated Press that  
while he could not guarantee there would be no future security 
lapses at the government research labs, he is convinced the kind of 
failure now under investigation at the Los Alamos lab ``cannot 
occur with the measures we have taken.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department recently ordered new procedures to guard  
against transfer of material from classified to unclassified 
computers, created additional ``firewalls'' to reduce hacker 
attacks on its computer systems and began more extensive monitoring 
of e-mail. In April the labs' computer systems were shut down for 
two weeks to integrate the new security measures. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't admit perfection has been achieved, but I can be  
confident to say we've taken bold, dramatic steps to greatly 
improve the prospects that there would not be any future security 
lapses,'' said Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 45-minute discussion in his office at the Energy  
Department, Richardson defended the administration's response to 
security concerns and espionage at the weapons labs and said: 
</P>
<P>
	--The security breaches at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in  
New Mexico, including the transfer of massive amounts of weapons 
computer codes to an unsecure desktop computer was ``an 
unacceptable, intolerable security breach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--That he was not ``personally aware of any other serious''  
security violations like the one under investigation at Los Alamos 
at any of the labs. 
</P>
<P>
	--There is no evidence that China or any other country obtained  
any of the computer design and performance codes that had been 
moved from the secure computer system, but that one should ``assume 
the worst' and take ``draconian measures'' to avoid a repeat 
incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said that both Republican and Democratic  
administrations have made missteps when it comes to security at the 
federal weapons research labs including Los Alamos in New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's plenty of blame to share,'' said Richardson.  
</P>
<P>
	``We should concentrate on reforming the (security) system  
rather than destroying it for political gain,'' said Richardson. 
``It's starting to become a political issue. ... It is taking on a 
political life of its own that's only going to hurt the labs and 
the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Some are trying to say we reacted much too slowly on cyber  
security. I reject that,'' said Richardson. He said he did not want 
to dwell ``on what happened in the past'' and ``concentrate on what 
we've done to fix the problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least 10 congressional committees are looking into how the  
Clinton administration responded to allegations of lax security at 
weapons labs and the discovery in 1996 of a major theft of secrets 
by China at the Los Alamos National Laboratory. The theft took 
place in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	A Taiwan-born scientist at Los Alamos was fired March 8 after  
being the prime target of an FBI espionage investigation since 
1996. The scientist, Wen Ho Lee, has not been charged with a crime 
and has denied any espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee remains under investigation not only in connection with the  
1980s thefts, but also because investigators found he had allegedly 
transferred hundreds of top-secret computer files of warhead design 
and performance codes from a secure computer system to his unsecure 
desktop computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, some Republican lawmakers compared the Los  
Alamos case to the Julius and Ethel Rosenberg spy case in the 1950s 
and the more recent spy saga involving CIA agent Aldrich Ames. 
Referring to the possible security damage at Los Alamos, Sen. Don 
Nickles, R-Okla., suggested it might be the most damaging case of 
espionage in U.S. history. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's an exaggeration,'' said Richardson. ``The scope, the  
extent of the theft has not been determined. The breach was 
serious,'' he continued. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, said Richardson ``there's no evidence that China or  
anybody else got any of these (computer codes). Before we start 
panicking, we need more facts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said he was concerned that several moves underway in  
Congress to restrict or even ban foreign scientific exchanges at 
labs or to have the FBI take over lab security are unnecessary and 
an overreaction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
