<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer criminals paying restitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The percentage of criminals being ordered to  
pay restitution has dropped despite the 1996 passage of a law 
requiring restitution in certain federal cases, congressional 
auditors said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's counterintuitive. It's puzzling,'' Richard Stana, the  
General Accounting Office's associate director for administration 
of justice issues, told a House subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first seven months of the 1997 fiscal year -- before the  
law took effect at the end of April -- 26 percent of federal 
offenders were ordered to pay restitution, the GAO found. For the 
rest of that fiscal year, ending Sept. 30, only 12 percent of the 
offenders got such orders. 
</P>
<P>
	For robbers, the likelihood of being ordered to pay restitution  
increased by almost half, but it decreased by almost half for 
larceny offenders, and decreased slightly for those convicted of 
fraud, Stana told the House Judiciary Committee's crime panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, a convict's chances of getting slapped with a fine  
or a restitution order varied widely depending on which judicial 
district heard the case, the report said. The range for fines was 1 
percent to 84 percent, and for restitution, 3 percent to 49 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``For example, offenders convicted of fraud in the Eastern  
District of Pennsylvania, which includes Philadelphia, were 13 more 
times likely to be ordered to pay a fine and three times more 
likely to be ordered to pay restitution than fraud offenders in the 
Eastern District of New York, which includes Brooklyn,'' Stana 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	People convicted of drug trafficking crimes in the Western  
District of Texas were 99 times more likely to be fined than people 
convicted of the same offense in the Central District of 
California, which includes Los Angeles, the GAO study found. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, while only 1 percent of drug offenders overall were  
ordered to pay restitution, nearly 66 percent of fraud offenders 
were ordered to pay it, the GAO report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other factors affecting the numbers were the offender's sex,  
race and citizenship, as well as educational levels, length of 
sentence and whether the sentence involved a prison term, probation 
or an alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO study did not examine whether fines or restitution  
ordered actually were paid. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors and court administrators told the GAO that some of  
the differences can be attributed to the type and nature of the 
offenses and differing court management cultures. They also said it 
was probably too early to gauge the effect of the law, since 
officials and prosecutors likely still need time to become familiar 
with it. 
</P>
<P>
	People convicted of a federal crime can be ordered to pay a fine  
or restitution at sentencing. Criminal fines, which are punitive, 
are given to the Justice Department's Crime Victims Fund. A judge 
can waive them if an offender cannot pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mandatory Victims Restitution Act changed restitution law by  
requiring judges to order full restitution to each victim in 
certain cases -- those involving crimes of violence, some property 
offenses, tampering with consumers products, and offenses involving 
fraud or deceit, for example. Previously, judges could waive 
restitution in those cases based on an offender's ability to pay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.N. Gets Big Role in Kosovo Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The new peacekeeping plan for Kosovo approved  
by the United States, Russia and six other nations is designed to 
win over Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic while ensuring 
ethnic Albanian refugees can return to their homes in safety. It 
assigns a prominent role to the United Nations, which could have an 
impact on the troops' mission if Russia, China or other Security 
Council members that opposed NATO's air campaign are able to limit 
the weapons the troops carry or the force they can apply to protect 
returned refugees. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Says It's Defeating Serbs  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO said today it is well on its way  
to pounding Serb forces in Kosovo into ineffectiveness, but 
acknowledged it has failed to stop Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic's ethnic cleansing campaign. Assessing the operation so 
far, an alliance general said Yugoslav forces in Kosovo were 
``being taken apart bit by bit,'' and offered a detailed list of 
successful strikes -- including heavy artillery, tanks, command 
posts, as well as Serb army and special police units. 

</P>
<P>
	Energy Boss Defends Administration  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson acknowledged  
massive security breaches at nuclear weapons labs today but said in 
an interview that criticism is ``starting to become a blame game'' 
that could hurt the labs and the nation. Richardson said an 
interview with The Associated Press that while he could not 
guarantee there would be no future security lapses at the 
government research labs, he is convinced the kind of failure now 
under investigation at the Los Alamos lab ``cannot occur with the 
measures we have taken.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Networks Nix Forbes' Kickoff  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steve Forbes has scuttled secret plans to  
broadcast the kickoff of his Republican presidential campaign live 
on national television, according to an adviser who said TV 
networks would not sell the wealthy businessman air time for the 
Waldorf-Astoria gala. The posh and pricey New York hotel will still 
be the site of his first fund-raiser, a June 16 event scheduled to 
raise $1 million. Forbes originally hoped to broadcast the June 16 
event as part of a 30-minute campaign kickoff. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, AT&AMP;T Form Alliance  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft is investing $5 billion in AT&AMP;T in a  
deal that will ensure that the dominant player in computer software 
won't be left out in AT&AMP;T's plan to use cable TV wires for Internet 
access, telephone calls and entertainment. The companies said today 
they will pick three cities to test a new, pay-one-bill service 
featuring interactive TV with phone service, e-mail and other 
Internet features -- all through one, super-fast cable. Just 
yesterday, AT&AMP;T reached an agreement to acquire MediaOne, the 
nation's fourth-largest cable provider. 

</P>
<P>
	Cholesterol-Lowering Margarine Out  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two margarines that actually cut cholesterol  
will soon appear on supermarket shelves nationwide at a price tag 
four times the regular spread. Market analysts suggest that many 
health-conscious Americans will be ready to try them anyway. Take 
Control, made by Unilever's Lipton unit began hitting the market 
last week, and Benecol, by the drug maker Johnson &AMP; Johnson, is 
nearing approval by the Food and Drug Administration. They're among 
the first major foods that are designed to act like drugs. 

</P>
<P>
	Ventura Refuses Prayer Day  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura refused to sign a  
proclamation making today a day of prayer. Ventura broke with the 
practice of his predecessors, who typically proclaimed a prayer day 
in conjunction with the National Day of Prayer. ``I believe in the 
separation of church and state,'' Ventura said. ``We all have our 
own religious beliefs. There are people out there who are atheists, 
who don't believe at all. ... They are all citizens of Minnesota 
and I have to respect that.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower, Dow Off 8.59  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices ended lower today, unable to shake  
off new worries about inflation. The Dow industrials finished at 
10,946.82, down 8.59. The technology-heavy Nasdaq was down 62.16 at 
2,472.28. 

</P>
<P>
	Cleaves Not Leaving for NBA  
</P>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Michigan State point guard Mateen  
Cleaves will stay in school next season and not declare himself 
eligible for the NBA draft as an underclassman. The 6-foot-2 
All-American led the Spartans to the Final Four of the NCAA 
tournament, where they lost to Duke. Two of his peers -- Duke's 
Elton Brand, and Connecticut's Richard Hamilton -- already decided 
to leave school early. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

</P>
