<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Approves $13.1B for Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House tonight approved $13.1 billion for  
the fight with Yugoslavia and to buttress U.S. forces around the 
globe. The measure would more than double the $6.05 billion 
President Clinton requested last month to wage the air war through 
September and care for hundreds of thousands of refugees who have 
fled Kosovo. The additions include $1.1 billion to buy missiles and 
bombs, $1.3 billion for spare parts, $1.8 billion to improve 
troops' pay and pensions, and $1.1 billion to modernize military 
bases, mostly in Europe. 

</P>
<P>
	Milosevic Quiet on New Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan  
Milosevic yet to comment on a plan devised by the West and Russia 
that could halt NATO's around-the-clock air assault. The plan, 
however, is built on premises his government had previously 
rejected. But with Russia acting as Yugoslavia's broker over the 
past weeks in trying to wrest a settlement from NATO, there are 
reasons Milosevic may agree to at least negotiate seriously on the 
international plan. Milosevic has said airstrikes must stop as part 
of any settlement of the Kosovo crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	Cops Escape Shooting Charges  
</P>
<P>
	RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) -- Four police officers were justified  
when they fired 23 bullets at a young black woman they found 
sitting armed and unresponsive in a disabled car, a prosecutor said 
today. Riverside County District Attorney Grover Trask said the 
officers may have acted hastily and made mistakes in judgment, but 
did not act criminally when they killed Tyisha Miller, 19, in 
December. Ms. Miller's death led to allegations that the officers -- 
three whites and a Hispanic -- were racists. 

</P>
<P>
	School Violence Solutions Debated  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Schools must fight violence on many fronts --  
from increasing counseling for troubled students to keeping weapons 
out of schools with metal detectors -- educators and safety experts 
told a Senate panel today. Policymakers and school leaders are 
asking whether violence prevention or tighter security is the way 
to go. A Cleveland school safety official said many education 
officials don't want their schools to get a reputation for being 
unsafe, so they are reluctant to install metal detectors or take 
other precautions. 

</P>
<P>
	Jury Deliberates 'Jenny Jones' Case  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Jurors began deliberating today whether  
producers of ``The Jenny Jones Show'' did ``everything ... except 
pull the trigger'' when a guest was killed after taping the 
program. Lawyers for the plaintiffs urged jurors to award $71.5 
million in damages, saying the talk show and its corporate owner, 
Warner Bros., were liable for the shooting death of Scott Amedure. 
Amedure, who was gay, was killed after revealing his crush on 
another male guest. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, AT&AMP;T Form Alliance  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft is investing $5 billion in AT&AMP;T in a  
deal that will ensure that the dominant player in computer software 
won't be left out in AT&AMP;T's plan to use cable TV wires for Internet 
access, telephone calls and entertainment. The companies said today 
they will pick three cities to test a new, pay-one-bill service 
featuring interactive TV with phone service, e-mail and other 
Internet features -- all through one, super-fast cable. Just 
yesterday, AT&AMP;T reached an agreement to acquire MediaOne, the 
nation's fourth-largest cable provider. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Strikes U.S. Encryption Rules  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Government limits on the export of computer  
encryption codes, which scramble data to prevent eavesdropping, is 
a violation of freedom of expression, a federal appeals court ruled 
today. The ruling is a blow to the Clinton administration, which 
limits exports of the most powerful encryption technology because 
it fears law enforcement agencies won't be able to read the 
messages of criminals or terrorists. But the high-tech industry 
wants relaxed restrictions so it can take advantage of the market 
for encryption programs as Internet commerce increases. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower, Dow Off 8.59  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices ended lower today, unable to shake  
off new worries about inflation. The Dow industrials finished at 
10,946.82, down 8.59. The technology-heavy Nasdaq was down 62.16 at 
2,472.28. 

</P>
<P>
	Owners Say Royals Group Too Big  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Major league owners will not approve  
Miles Prentice's proposed $75 million bid to buy the Kansas City 
Royals because his group has too many investors, a high-ranking 
baseball official told The Associated Press. Prentice, a New York 
lawyer who has pursued the team for almost two years, will be asked 
to reform his group with fewer investors, the official said. The 
Prentice group numbers between 40 and 50, including golfer Tom 
Watson and Negro Leagues baseball star Buck O'Neil. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
