<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 76ers Pres. Shaves Head For Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia 76ers president Pat Croce has a  
new look for the NBA playoffs -- a bald head. 
</P>
<P>
	He had promised to shave it if his team made the postseason.  
</P>
<P>
	``It looks great!'' Sixers bald center Matt Geiger said, rubbing  
Croce's scalp. ``Needs some sun, though!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Croce got the haircut Thursday as the Sixers prepared for their  
first-round series against Orlando. It was the latest stunt by the 
self-made millionaire whose antics and enthusiasm finally have been 
rewarded with a successful season. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday night, Croce surprised everyone when he slid down a  
rope from the ceiling of the First Union Center between the first 
and second quarters of Philadelphia's overtime win over Detroit. He 
traveled the last 50 feet upside down, then ran around the court 
throwing Sixers playoff T-shirts into the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to get the crowd juiced,'' Croce said.  
</P>
<P>
	At practice Thursday, he removed his baseball cap with a  
sweeping gesture and held his arms in the air as if to say, ``Ta 
da!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Brown, the Sixers' button-down coach, could only chuckle.  
</P>
<P>
	``I told my wife that I thought about doing that a while back,''  
Brown said. ``And she said Pat doing it is enough. I've never had 
an owner like this. He's a unique kind of guy. If anybody deserves 
our team having success, it's Pat.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 06:35:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Docs in Cancer Case Give Up Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATTLEBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Two pathologists accused of mistakenly  
diagnosing 19 men as free of prostate cancer when they actually had 
the disease have volunteered to give up their medical licenses 
temporarily. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Board of Registration in Medicine said Wednesday the  
two doctors, John C. DuVally and F. John J. Krolikowski, signed 
agreements not to practice medicine for 60 days, pending a medical 
board investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreements do not preclude the medical board from taking  
disciplinary action. Should the investigation take longer than two 
months, the suspensions could be extended. 
</P>
<P>
	DuVally signed the agreement Tuesday, Krolikowski on Friday.  
Both doctors have left Sturdy Memorial Hospital. Their phone 
numbers are unlisted and neither could be reached for comment 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Between January 1995 and December 1997, the two pathologists  
allegedly misread 20 biopsies on 19 patients, incorrectly telling 
the men they were free of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the patients later died of unrelated causes, the hospital  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sturdy Memorial discovered the errors last month after a review  
of 279 tests prompted by a urologist who discovered one of his 
patients had been misdiagnosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Sturdy Hospital last week said it had hired a consultant to  
retest 6,000 tissue samples. A hospital representative did not 
return telephone calls seeking comment Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital's president and CEO, Linda Shyavitz, has said the  
hospital now requires two pathologists to read all breast and 
prostate biopsies, along with similar checks on other tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bulls Honor Phil Jackson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Phil Jackson will be back at the United Center  
again, maybe even as early as next season if he finds a team that 
intrigues him and the offer is right. 
</P>
<P>
	But this was the last time Chicago Bulls' fans could claim  
Jackson as their own, and they savored every minute of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to thank you from my heart. I think this has been a  
wonderful night,'' he said Wednesday as he was honored during a 
halftime ceremony. ``We had a wonderful nine years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it's truly over now. Almost 11 months after Jackson roared  
off on his Harley-Davidson with a sixth NBA championship, the Bulls 
hung a banner with his name right next to Michael Jordan's in the 
rafters. 
</P>
<P>
	There were gifts, including a $10,000 donation in his name by  
the Bulls to the Oglala Sioux tribe, and tributes from his former 
coaches and assistants during the 20-minute ceremony. Even Michael 
Jordan sent his regards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if you get another job somewhere else, you'll always be  
known as the Chicago Bulls' head coach,'' Jordan said in a 
videotaped greeting. ``So I wish you the best. If you need me, give 
me a yell. But not for playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fans were on their feet and yelling as soon as Bulls  
broadcaster Johnny ``Red'' Kerr introduced Jackson. When the former 
coach walked on the floor, the noise in the United Center rose to a 
level not heard since last season. 
</P>
<P>
	In nine seasons with the Bulls, Jackson compiled a 545-193  
record and was coach of all six of their championship teams. He has 
higher winning percentages, .738 overall and .733 in the playoffs, 
of any coach in NBA history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been looking forward to this all year long. It's about  
the only thing I have looked forward to,'' Tex Winter, an assistant 
to Jackson and new coach Tim Floyd, said as the crowd roared. 
</P>
<P>
	But the night wasn't a complete lovefest. When Jackson thanked  
chairman Jerry Reinsdorf, there were loud boos. Jackson ignored the 
fans and went on to thank general manager Jerry Krause, drawing 
even more boos. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans blame Reinsdorf and Krause for running off Jackson and  
breaking up the six-time champions. While both were there -- Jackson 
sat in Reinsdorf's box for part of the game -- neither was on the 
floor for the halftime ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to encourage you all to remain Bulls basketball fans,''  
Jackson said. ``We had a wonderful time, didn't we?'' 
</P>
<P>
	And then Jackson was gone, leaving the floor for good with his  
family as the Grateful Dead's ``Trucking'' began playing. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a much different -- and much happier -- goodbye than  
Jackson's last exit. When he zoomed off on his Harley-Davidson last 
summer, he was burned out and sick of the squabbling with Krause. 
He was so weary he didn't know if he ever wanted to coach again. 
</P>
<P>
	But a year off has done wonders. The bags and shadows under  
Jackson's eyes are gone, and he looks about 10 years younger. His 
rancor toward Krause has eased, and he said there was never any 
animosity toward Reinsdorf. 
</P>
<P>
	He talks regularly with Winter and assistant Frank Hamblen, and  
occasionally with Floyd. He even watched a few Bulls games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course it's been heartrending to see them lose to the Miami  
Heat with only 49 points. But they won last Saturday with 101,'' he 
said. ``(But) I think I was spared a lot of remorse probably and a 
lot of heartache perhaps. ... In my regard, it was something for 
myself in which I wasn't going to be able to compare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He has no doubt the Bulls would have been ``at the top of the  
heap'' if they'd stayed together one more year, but he has no 
regrets about leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad about retiring at the appropriate time,'' he said.  
``I have no regrets at all. I don't think there could have been a 
greater scenario than to have been part of this thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson thought a year off would give him time to find something  
else to occupy his mind, but he found he still loves the NBA. Some 
teams already have contacted him through his attorney, Todd 
Musburger, but there haven't been any serious negotiations, nor has 
Jackson made any decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basketball is, right now, a sport in which many people say  
still needs leadership and direction from coaching,'' he said, 
``and that is an arena that intrigues me still.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:23:32 </DATE_TIME>
