<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 21:14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Beer Ad in Gay Mag Draws Response </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A Budweiser advertisement showing two men  
holding hands in a free magazine for gays and lesbians has drawn so 
much response that Anheuser-Busch Inc. set up special hotlines to 
handle calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad for Bud Light in the April 22 issue of EXP magazine says  
``Be Yourself and Make It a Bud Light,'' and carries a tagline 
saying ``Proud Sponsor of the St. Louis PrideFest '99.'' PrideFest 
is a gay and lesbian festival held in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the ad ran, leaders in the gay community began  
distributing e-mail, urging people to call Anheuser-Busch in 
support of the ad. The St. Louis brewer was so overwhelmed with 
calls that it set up a hotline for supporters to use. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative Christian leader Jerry Falwell subsequently urged  
his followers to call Anheuser-Busch, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's keep the heat on Anheuser-Busch so that they understand  
that pro-family Americans are terribly concerned about homosexual 
images coming into our homes through reckless advertising 
campaigns,'' Falwell wrote in his Falwell Confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's surprising to us that one print ad placed in select  
gay-oriented magazines has attracted attention,'' the St. Louis 
brewer said in a written statement. ``Today's consumer is not one 
of a specific gender, race, geography or orientation. We appreciate 
and respect the views of all our customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch officials declined to comment about the results  
of the calls or whether they will have any effect on further plans 
for the advertisement. 
</P>
<P>
	Falwell was unavailable for comment Thursday, his spokesman  
said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:55:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Businesses Reel From Tornadoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIDWEST CITY, Okla. (AP) -- A handmade sign lay propped against  
the mountain of twisted metal, soggy insulation and crumbled 
sheetrock that once was a Super Surplus store: ``Clearance Sale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was an appropriate message in a two-block area leveled by a  
monster tornado Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Silsby, an owner of the store, used his fingers to count  
off the 15 or so family-owned businesses that once lined the 
heavily traveled street. An automotive repair business, a tire 
store, a lawn mower shop. They all looked the same -- nothing but 
rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday was the shock of, `I've lost everything,''' he said  
Wednesday. ``Now it doesn't matter. We can replace it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Jim Anderson, putting back the pieces will be a little more  
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	The same tornado that destroyed his used-motorcycle shop in  
Midwest City stopped first in Moore to suck up his house and 
hundreds of others. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it hasn't sunk in yet,'' he said. ``Yesterday,  
I woke up and said, `It has to be a dream.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The nightmare is far from over for dozens of business owners  
devastated by Monday's storms, which killed at least 41 people in 
Oklahoma and five in Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	The business owners must negotiate with insurance companies,  
hope for a fair and quick settlement, and eventually -- if they can 
manage it -- get back to business. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial help is available for businesses located within the  
counties designated as federal disaster areas. They are eligible 
for low-interest and long-term Small Business Administration loans 
and can file an amended federal tax extension to deduct their 
property losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitch Morris said he hopes to work out a speedy insurance  
settlement so he can start rebuilding his engine repair business. 
</P>
<P>
	But first he must figure out a way to untwist the giant steel  
frames that were used to hoist vehicles weighing up to 9,000 
pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``See those big blue posts?'' Anderson said. ``The tornado just  
picked them up and twisted them around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two blocks away at Second Hand Sports, owner John Coles boarded  
up huge panels of broken glass. 
</P>
<P>
	His business is one of the few in the area still standing. And  
despite the blown-out windows, many of the basketballs, exercise 
benches and weightlifting gloves still neatly line the shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, who had no insurance to cover the contents of his  
business, says he lost about $10,000 in merchandise. And he doesn't 
know if his landlord will repair the building. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just glad I have another job,'' said Coles, who works as  
an aircraft mechanic at the nearby Tinker Air Force Base. 
</P>
<P>
	Just south of the strip of businesses are four motels that front  
Interstate 40. Three were demolished in Monday's storm. The power 
remained off at the fourth, La Quinta Inn. 
</P>
<P>
	The owner of Comfort Inn said he was too upset to talk about his  
loss. The 150-room hotel is missing its roof and the walls are 
askew, as in a Jenga game ready to topple. 
</P>
<P>
	In Midwest City, 124 businesses were hit by the storm and at  
least 20 were heavily damaged, said Stan Greil, president of the 
city's chamber of commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma City Mayor Kirk Humphreys said 16 business were  
destroyed in his city and nine received major damage. At least 
eight businesses were destroyed in Choctaw and more than 10 were 
hit when the storm passed through Dell City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
