<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 10:15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poundstone Vision to 'Home Movies' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Paula Poundstone's new comedy  
series, ``Home Movies,'' had a spare, engagingly wobbly style of 
animation that its creators have dubbed Squigglevision. 
</P>
<P>
	Seems fitting for Poundstone. Her world, by her own description,  
appears to be done in a kind of Paulavision -- equally funny and 
equally unsteady on its feet. 
</P>
<P>
	It's certainly a rich world. Besides providing the mother's  
voice in ``Home Movies,'' a wry little gem airing 8:30 p.m. EDT 
Monday on UPN, Poundstone is a fixture on the club and campus scene 
with her stand-up act. 
</P>
<P>
	She's a frequent TV talk show guest, has produced a children's  
audio book and is a real-life single mom to two daughters. And she 
regularly expands her household to include foster children, such as 
the 11-month-old boy who recently joined the circle. 
</P>
<P>
	Can a comedian, one with a dry-as-dust wit and her own new world  
order, be a typical mom in any regard? You be the judge, based on 
these actual Poundstone comments: 
</P>
<P>
	-- ``I have really pretty, pretty kids, which makes me suspect my  
next one's going to be an ugly baby. The odds are really good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- ``I used to watch 'The Waltons' and just sob, not because the  
episodes were that moving but because my family was nothing like 
that. I figured if I came from a bigger family there'd be at least 
one person that I liked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- ``At the end of last summer, I was diagnosed with  
obsessive-compulsive disorder. One thing I always did was scrub the 
kitchen floor every night. I don't do it every night now, but I am 
constantly looking around at home to see if there's a place that 
needs a little spot job. ... My daughter told me, 'You're VERY 
strict about the floor.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	That off-kilter take on life helped give birth to ``Home  
Movies.'' The show is from the same company, Tom Snyder 
Productions, that makes ABC's kid's program ``SquiggleVision'' 
(formerly ``Science Court'') and ``Dr. Katz: Professional 
Therapist.'' The ABC show is named for the quivering animation 
process used in ``Dr. Katz'' and ``Home Movies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the course of lending her voice via telephone hookup to ABC's  
``SquiggleVision,'' Poundstone entertained the producers with tales 
from the home front. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be telling them about how things were going at home,  
which generally wasn't well, telling one frustrating story after 
another about my kids. They got approached to make a show about 
family for UPN, so they said, 'Why don't you just do what you were 
doing over the phone for us?''' Poundstone recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	The result is ``Home Movies,'' about divorced mom Paula Small  
(Poundstone), her precocious, 8-year-old son Brendon -- a budding 
Steven Spielberg armed with a video camera and a taste for mischief 
-- and baby Josie. 
</P>
<P>
	(UPN has committed to a five-episode run for the series, which  
debuted April 26, so catch it quick.) 
</P>
<P>
	In the first episode, Paula Small goes on a really bad date with  
the school's dense soccer coach, Mr. McGuirk (voiced by H. Jon 
Benjamin of ``Dr. Katz''), who admits to an excess of ``trademarked 
products'' tattoos on his body. 
</P>
<P>
	``Excuse me, waiter, can I get another one of these as soon as  
possible?'' says the despairing cartoon Paula, cocktail glass in 
hand. ``I'm not supposed to mix it with medication, but I'm going 
to make a rare exception to the rule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Poundstone contributes to the show's often ad-libbed  
dialogue, she judges some of it to be a tad unrealistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have the 8-year-old who makes movies, and I have an  
8-year-old, and maybe she's slightly mature. But recently, at her 
sister's birthday party, I let her borrow the camera and we got 
pictures of the drinks at the table, people's heads cut off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they guessed wrong about how a kid would be at 8, but  
that's the beauty of television,'' said Poundstone. Much of it, she 
says, is pretty unrealistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of TV is something people can't relate to. I'm not sure  
anybody will exactly be able to relate to this, but hopefully 
they'll think it's funny. I don't think anybody will go, 'Oh, my 
family's just like that. 
</P>
<P>
	``For one thing'' -- she pauses a comic beat -- ``they're  
cartoons. 'My mom was erased once'; no one's going to say that.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	After nibbling neatly on miniature crab cakes and potato chips  
at a seaside hotel, Poundstone must bring this interview to a 
close. Checking her watch, she mentions that one of her girls has a 
physical therapy appointment. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has cerebral palsy. Unless she's faking it,'' says  
Poundstone, smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	That's Paulavision, no doubt about it.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	EXPECTATIONS ARE HIGH: Ioan Gruffudd, a swashbuckling standout  
in A&AMP;E's ``Horatio Hornblower'' miniseries, takes on the role of 
Pip in PBS' new production of Charles Dickens' ``Great 
Expectations.'' The Mobil Masterpiece Theatre miniseries, airing 
9-11 p.m. EDT Sunday and Monday (May 9-10), also features Justine 
Waddell, Charlotte Rampling and Bernard Hill. Orphaned Pip learns 
about life and love at the hands of the cold Estella, manipulative 
Miss Havisham and a mysterious benefactor. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
