<DOCNO> APW19990506.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:24:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Dip; Dow Falls 8.59 Points / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fluctuated Thursday but ended lower  
as cautionary remarks by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan 
fed investors' increasing worries about inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 8.59 at 10,946.82.  
The Dow fell as much as 103 points during the day, then tried but 
failed to recover ground just before the close. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader market indicators also were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 15.26 at 1,332.05, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 62.16 at 2,472.28. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are increasingly concerned that the robust economy  
will reawaken inflation and prompt the Fed to push rates higher 
when its policy writers meet in two weeks. Higher rates are the 
market's nemesis because they can quickly eat into corporate 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	In remarks to bankers in Chicago, Greenspan praised the  
performance of the U.S. economy in recent years, but warned that 
gains in productivity cannot keep inflation at bay forever. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I have said on previous occasions, there are imbalances in  
our expansion that, unless redressed, will bring this long run of 
strong growth and low inflation to a close,'' he said. He said 
tight labor markets, for example, could ultimately threaten the 
expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	As he has in the past, Greenspan also expressed concern that the  
high-flying stock market could suddenly come back to earth, causing 
a reversal of the wealth effect that has powered consumer spending 
</P>
<P>
	His morning speech caused already jittery stock and bond markets  
to fall throughout the day. The Treasury's 30-year bond carried a 
yield of 5.78 percent, its highest level since June. The bond had 
closed late Wednesday with a yield of 5.70 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hawkish tone from Greenspan is shaking the trees of growth  
stocks and, as a result, continuing to put downward pressure on 
growth and financial stocks,'' said Tom Galvin, chief equity 
strategist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks were particularly hard hit by the  
interest rate worries. The discount broker Schwab Corp. fell 4 1/8 to 
103 3/8, while Chase Manhattan was down 2 5/8 to 77 9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail stocks also felt the pinch, despite the announcement  
Thursday that many big storeowners had better-than-expected sales 
in April. Gap Inc. fell 5 1/4 to 64 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T rose 5 to 61 15/16 after announcing that Microsoft will  
invest $5 billion in the telecommunications company. In return, 
AT&AMP;T said it will increase its use of Microsoft's software. 
Microsoft fell 1 3/16 to 77 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, AT&AMP;T negotiated its victory in a bidding war with  
Comcast over MediaOne Group Inc., the nation's fourth-largest cable 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Internet stocks fell Thursday, perhaps at the threat from  
the Microsoft-AT&AMP;T communications alliance. Intel fell 4 5/16 to 59 
11/16, while Amazon.com slipped 9 1/8 to 137 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancers outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume came to 1.056 
billion shares, down from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 4.32 at 636.22, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 2.32 at 787.81. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index, which reflects the performance of  
smaller-company stocks, fell 0.89 at 433.38. 
</P>
<P>
	European stocks were little changed. The CAC 40 in Paris ended  
0.79 percent lower, London's FTSE 100 index closed down 0.07 
percent, and the DAX in Frankfurt dropped 0.61 percent. In Tokyo, 
the Nikkei rose 3.58 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
