<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 54.40 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today, pulled down by a jump in bond  
market yields that revived fears of rising interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 54.40 at 10,901.01. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 10.18 at 1,337.13, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 11.78 at 2,522.67. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest rates have replaced earnings reports as the main focus  
of the market. There are increasing worries among investors that 
the strong economy will revive inflation and prompt the Federal 
Reserve to push rates higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind today's uncertain start was a jump in bond market yields.  
The Treasury's 30-year bond carried a yield of 5.77 percent, up 
sharply from late Wednesday's 5.70 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Cautious optimism by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan  
also caught the market's attention. He called the U.S. economy's 
performance phenomenal, and cited the country's high productivity, 
but Greenspan warned that the global recovery from a severe 
financial crisis remains fragile. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks were down amid the nervousness over  
interest rates. J.P. Morgan was down 2 3/16 at 136 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest retailers released mostly better than  
expected sales figures for April. But Wal-Mart was down 2 at 43 
1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 286.45 million 
shares, up from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 4.23 at 636.31, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 1.55 at 787.04. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
