<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Autoworkers Threaten Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Fearing mass dismissals with the end of  
a job-saving, sales-boosting agreement, Brazilian autoworkers today 
threatened to bring the assembly lines of local car factories to a 
complete standstill. 
</P>
<P>
	In what one labor leader said was ``prelude to a general  
strike,'' some 20,000 workers from the Brazilian subsidiaries of 
Ford Motor Co., Volkswagen AG and DaimlerChrysler AG's Mercedes 
Benz unit marched through the streets of Sao Bernardo do Campo, the 
industrial suburb of Sao Paulo where the automakers are 
headquartered. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not accept a single dismissal,'' said Luiz Marinho,  
president of the Sao Bernardo do Campo Metalworkers Union. ``If we 
have to, we'll unleash a general strike and stop the factories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The union's growing concerns of unemployment came to a head on  
Tuesday when automakers hiked car prices by up to 10 percent, 
effectively bringing to an end a tax-reduction agreement aimed at 
saving thousands of jobs and increasing sales. 
</P>
<P>
	In early March, the government, manufacturers and labor unions  
signed an agreement that cut the federal excise tax levied on cars 
by up to 13 percentage points, depending on the model. Some states 
also trimmed their taxes by three percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers agreed not to raise prices or lay off workers for at  
least 90 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement helped the industry recover from a months-long  
slump caused by high interest rates and recession. By the end of 
March sales had soared 236 percent from a month earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts to extend the agreement for at least another 30 days  
failed as automakers insisted on hiking their prices to compensate, 
they said, for increased costs of imported components caused by the 
January devaluation of Brazil's currency, the real. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Carlos Pinheiro Neto, president of the National Association  
of Vehicle Manufacturers, on Thursday said manufacturers couldn't 
afford to keep producing cars at a loss. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first three months of the year, Brazil's big four  
manufacturers -- Volkswagen, Fiat SpA, General Motors Corp. and Ford 
-- lost about $774 million, according to a study by Ernst and Young, 
Pinehiro Neto said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's secretary of Industrial Policy, Helio Mattar, said the  
government hopes to resume negotiations with manufacturers, the 
Estado news agency reported. He also asked manufacturers to ``be 
sensible'' and not raise prices until a new agreement is reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Mattar said the government is willing to maintain the lower  
taxes on cars with some price increases by manufacturers, but will 
ask automakers to prove that they've actually suffered losses, the 
report added. 
</P>
<P>
	Neto said manufacturers are open to negotiating an extension of  
the accord, but only if the new agreement allows for price 
increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, auto sales in April were 16 percent lower than the  
previous month, despite the tax-reduction agreement. Compared to 
April of last year they were 7.9 percent lower. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first four months of the year, Brazilian vehicle sales  
totaled 335,878 units, down 18 percent from the same period last 
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
