<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Warriors Make Progress in 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- When the Warriors announced Wednesday  
night during their season-ending loss to San Antonio that a lucky 
fan had won a basketball autographed by coach P.J. Carlesimo, there 
were boos in the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	That's what happens when a team, despite showing improvement  
over the previous year, finishes with a losing record and out of 
the playoffs for the fifth straight season -- and does little to 
convince fans those streaks won't stretch to six seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, Golden State's 21-29 record in this lockout-shortened  
season was a lot better than the 19-63 mark last season. And there 
were flashes of brilliance down the stretch from rookie Antawn 
Jamison, the Warriors' first productive draft pick in years. 
</P>
<P>
	But a year after Latrell Sprewell choked Carlesimo, depriving  
the Warriors of their best player and turning Golden State from a 
bad team into a woeful club, there perhaps was not enough 
rebuilding to promise better times ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlesimo gave plenty of playing time to veterans such as Terry  
Cummings and Muggsy Bogues, taking those minutes away from young 
players such as Jamison, Erick Dampier, Jason Caffey and Tony Delk. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting center Dampier, who will be eligible for free agency,  
did not play down the stretch in some tight games and might have 
that in mind when he decides whether to re-sign with the Warriors. 
Delk, a backup point guard, already has said he expects to be 
elsewhere next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlesimo defended his decision to go with veterans at times,  
saying he simply was trying to put the best team on the floor as 
the Warriors made a bid for the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've found out a lot more about (our young  
players),'' Carlesimo said. ``Had they done better, they'd be 
playing more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the Warriors led the NBA in rebounding for the second  
straight season, they continued to struggle on offense. Shooting 
guard John Starks, obtained from the New York Knicks as part of the 
Jan. 26 trade for Sprewell, led the team with 13.8 points per game 
-- the lowest team-leading average since the Warriors moved west 
from Philadelphia in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	But Starks shot just 37 percent, including a 3-for-14  
performance in the season-closer against the Spurs. And the 
Warriors still lack a quality point guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Starks remained upbeat, though, focusing on the team's  
improvement. 
</P>
<P>
	``This organization has been through some tough times the last  
few years, but as you can see they have made a lot of improvements 
to turn that around,'' he said. ``There is a great future ahead for 
us. I look forward to finishing my career here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The future depends a lot on the development of Jamison. Instead  
of picking a point guard such as Jason Williams, who was selected 
after Jamison in the draft and helped lead the Sacramento Kings 
into the playoffs, the Warriors went for a player who had trouble 
adjusting to the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamison was the college player of the year at North Carolina  
last season, but struggled with the switch from power forward to 
small forward. He ended up playing behind Chris Mills and Donyell 
Marshall, and not starting until the 26th game of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he played well down the stretch, such as his 22-point,  
16-rebound performance in Wednesday's game against San Antonio, 
Jamison shot poorly from outside and had trouble handing the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know what I've got to do. I know what I need to work on,''  
he said. ``I experienced a lot of downs, and every once in a while 
I got a lot of ups. I think it is good that I struggled a lot this 
year and experienced a lot of lows. Right now it's time for me to 
work and improve every day.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
