<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mutual Fund Assets Are Up / Money Market Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's money market mutual funds  
rose in the latest week, despite a drop in retail funds, the 
Investment Company Institute reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets in retail money market mutual funds, which are held by  
individual investors, fell by $187.4 million in the week ended 
Wednesday to $858.41 billion, the Washington-based mutual fund 
trade group said. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category rose  
by $26.2 million to $713.31 billion, while tax-exempt fund assets 
fell by $213.6 million to $145.11 billion, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of institutional money market funds rose by $7.42 billion  
to $584.21 billion for the same period. Among institutional funds, 
taxable money market fund assets rose by $4.77 billion to $537.09 
billion; assets of tax-exempt funds rose by $2.65 billion to $47.12 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Total money market assets stood at $1.443 trillion for the week.  
</P>
<P>
	Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.435 trillion to  
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds 
reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in  
the week ended Tuesday to 4.33 percent from 4.28 percent the 
previous week, said IBC's Money Fund Report, a trade journal 
published in Ashland, Mass., by IBC Financial Data Inc. But the 
30-day average yield fell to 4.31 percent from 4.32 percent, IBC 
Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day compounded yield rose to 4.42 percent from 4.37  
percent the previous week, while the 30-day compounded yield fell 
to 4.40 percent from 4.41 percent, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was  
61 days, unchanged from a week earlier, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The online, service bankrate.com said its survey of 100 leading  
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks 
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage 
yield available on money market accounts fell to 2.09 percent as of 
Wednesday from 2.10 percent a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based unit of Intelligent Life Corp.  
said the annual percentage yield available on interest-bearing 
checking accounts fell to 0.92 percent from 0.93 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankrate.com said the annual percentage yield was 4.12 percent  
on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 4.13 percent the 
previous week. Yields were 4.36 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 4.34 
percent; 4.47 percent on 2 1/2-year CDs, unchanged from a week 
earlier; and 4.63 percent on 5-year CDs, also unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
