<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Hamilton Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LEE, N.J. (AP) -- New York Giants defensive tackle Keith  
Hamilton pleaded guilty Thursday to driving while intoxicated. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton was arrested on the George Washington Bridge in  
November after police said they clocked him traveling at 71 mph in 
an area where the speed limit is 45 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	A municipal court judge allowed Hamilton to avoid jail time on  
criminal charges of possession of marijuana, possession of drug 
paraphernalia, and being under the influence of cocaine, said 
municipal prosecutor Matthew Fierro. 
</P>
<P>
	He was ordered to pay about $2,000 in fines, and his driver's  
license was suspended for six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of serving jail time, Hamilton was allowed to enroll in  
the municipal equivalent of a pre-trial intervention program, under 
which he entered no plea to the criminal charges and agreed to 
undergo a drug test immediately and a second drug test in six 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	If Hamilton tests negative for drugs both times, and if he is  
not arrested again during the next six months, the charges will be 
dismissed, Fierro said. 
</P>
<P>
	Giants officials have said it was unlikely that Hamilton, a  
starter, would face suspension, because it is his first drug 
offense. A DWI often results in a half-game fine up to $20,000, the 
team said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
