<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawsuit Over Atlanta Olympic Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The group that initiated Atlanta's bid for the  
1996 Olympics is suing to stop the state from forcing it to open 
thousands of additional boxes of records to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Amateur Athletic Foundation filed suit late  
Wednesday after receiving a letter from Georgia Attorney General 
Thurbert Baker, who threatened legal action if the additional files 
were not opened. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation opened nine boxes of documents last week.  
</P>
<P>
	Baker's letter said the files should be made public because of  
the ``overwhelmingly public nature of the 1996 Olympics (and) the 
inextricable link between private interests and government entities 
in the pursuit'' of the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Roy Barnes already has said the records should be opened.  
</P>
<P>
	The foundation's suit asked the court to preserve ``the  
established rights to privacy of the foundation's donors, 
volunteers and staff,'' said Lee Echols, a spokesman for the 
foundation, which Billy Payne created in 1987 to begin Atlanta's 
Olympic bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation has been embroiled in a legal dispute with The  
Atlanta Journal-Constitution over the records related to Atlanta's 
bid for the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker helped strike a deal between the newspaper and the  
foundation that he says was intended to open all records, without 
litigation, except those that would be exempted under the Open 
Records Act. 
</P>
<P>
	But Baker said records were withheld for privacy reasons with no  
explanation of what those papers contained. He also said such 
records could not be withheld entirely -- they could only be 
redacted to remove private information. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker also said he understood archivists were deciding which  
papers to withhold instead of the foundation's lawyers. He said 
such decisions are legal ones and should be handled by attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker said if the terms of his letter are not agreed to by  
Friday, ``I will initiate litigation'' to determine if the records 
should be opened. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked later about the foundation's suit, Baker said, ``If they  
want to litigate this in court, we'll litigate this in court.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
