<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lockheed Leads Satellite Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lockheed Martin is leading a $3.6 billion  
satellite venture that will beam high-speed, high-capacity Internet 
and multimedia services to customers with small satellite dishes. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint venture with TRW and Telecom Italia, named Astrolink,  
plans to launch the first of four satellites in 2002, providing 
service in Europe and North and South America beginning in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	The next three satellites are to be launched at six-month  
intervals, expanding the network worldwide, the companies said in a 
press release Thursday. Another five satellites may be added to the 
system, depending on market demand. 
</P>
<P>
	The initiative by Lockheed, the big aerospace contractor based  
in Bethesda, Md., follows a similar project started by Hughes 
Electronics, a unit of General Motors Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Astrolink has been given initial $900 million in funding, with  
Lockheed Martin providing $400 million, and TRW and Telecom Italia 
providing $250 million apiece. Each company will hold a minority 
stake in the venture. 
</P>
<P>
	The system will carry high-speed data traffic for Internet,  
multimedia and corporate networks, the statement said, noting a 
forecast that the global market for broadband communications will 
grow to nearly $200 billion by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, by the consulting firm Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton, also  
predicted that space-based systems will capture 10-15 percent of 
that market. 
</P>
<P>
	The satellite system would be differentiated from leased-line  
systems in that customers would pay only for the connection time 
and data transmission services they use, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Celso Azevedo, a former executive for the satellite television  
service DirecTV, has been named president and chief executive of 
Astrolink. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have taken the lead in the race to deploy the first of a  
new generation of flexible, reliable, high speed, global wireless 
data services,'' said Azevedo. ``We are in active discussions with 
additional investors and service providers, and we plan to announce 
agreements with them in the near future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Martin will provide Astrolink's spacecraft, systems  
integration and launch services, with Lockheed Martin Global 
Telecommunications acting as one of Astrolink's service providers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland-based TRW will build the digital communications  
payloads for the satellites, and will have the opportunity to be an 
Astrolink service provider. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia will supply the worldwide ground systems for the  
venture and manage the satellite and network control systems. 
Telecom Italia will sell Astrolink services in Italy and through 
its affiliated companies in Europe and Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
