<DOCNO> APW19990506.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 08:55:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> University Ends Psychosis Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The University of Cincinnati has dropped  
psychiatric studies in which patients were given a chemical that 
may cause psychosis. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement Wednesday comes as federal investigators are  
examining research practices at the university and Cincinnati's 
Veterans Administration Medical Center, which are affiliated. 
</P>
<P>
	The university's study that raised concern was a 1997 clinical  
trial in which 13 patients who were delusional or hallucinating 
were asked to take amphetamines, which can make the symptoms worse. 
Giving people chemicals that may induce psychosis -- a severe form 
of mental illness -- was intended to help researchers learn how 
psychosis happens, or to test a treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics complained that people with psychoses severe enough to  
be hospitalized were denied treatment for their illnesses for five 
days just to complete the study. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Randy Hillard, head of the university's department of  
psychiatry, said the amphetamine study was conducted with adequate 
safety measures. But he said that no more of those studies will be 
done by his department until critics are satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nationwide, there is enough of a question ... that we will  
stop doing them until there is a consensus about how they should be 
done,'' Hillard said. 
</P>
<P>
	He commented after meeting Wednesday with four Cincinnati-area  
advocates for the mentally ill. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, a presidential advisory commission recommended  
increased protections for people with mental disorders involved in 
research, including giving family and friends more say in what 
happens. The National Bioethics Advisory Commission proposed new 
federal guidelines to try to ensure that people with disorders such 
as dementia, schizophrenia and delirium are not exploited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:55:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Gordon Allan Aulis    	
</P>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Gordon Allan ``Jack'' Aulis, a North  
Carolina journalist who worked in radio, television and newspapers, 
died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	Aulis wrote a column for The News &AMP; Observer of Raleigh in the  
1970s, hosted a state public television news program and wrote 
several nature books. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the Marine Corps at age 17 during World War II and  
lost his right arm during the Battle of Iwo Jima. 
</P>
<P>
	Entering journalism in 1951, Aulis worked for The Daily Advance  
in Elizabeth City, radio station WGAI in Elizabeth City, and The 
Virginian-Pilot in Norfolk, Va. before going to The News &AMP; Observer 
in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	After leaving the N&AMP;O in 1977, Aulis was deputy executive  
director of ElectriCities of North Carolina, wrote a weekly column 
for The Greensboro Daily News and hosted a public TV news show 
until 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	His books included ``Eagles Have Bad Breath'' and ``Plants Don't  
Do What You Tell 'Em To.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his wife, Lois Ruth Horne Aulis, survivors  
include a daughter and a grandson. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Robert P. Bergman    	
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Robert P. Bergman, director of the Cleveland  
Museum of Art since 1993, died Thursday of a rare blood disorder. 
He was 53. 
</P>
<P>
	During his tenure in Cleveland, the museum hosted three of its  
five highest-attended exhibitions, Egyptian art from the Louvre, 
Renaissance and Baroque art from the Vatican and Faberge items from 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual attendance grew from about 450,000 to 650,000 during his  
tenure. He oversaw the renovation or reinstallation of 30 of 70 
galleries. 
</P>
<P>
	Before coming to Cleveland, Bergman served as director of the  
Walters Art Gallery in Baltimore from 1981-93. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergman taught at Princeton, Harvard University and Lincoln  
University in Oxford, Pa. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Carlos Fuentes Lemus    	
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Carlos Fuentes Lemus, a photographer and the  
son of Mexican novelist Carlos Fuentes, died Wednesday. He was 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuentes Lemus' body was found at a hotel in the Pacific coast  
resort of Puerto Vallarta, and prosecutors said the cause of death 
was apparent complications from hemophilia. 
</P>
<P>
	In June 1998, Fuentes Lemus published the book ``Portraits in  
Time,'' (``Retratos en el Tiempo'') in which his photographs of 
artists were accompanied by his father's profiles. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Maj. John Howard    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Maj. John Howard, a D-Day commander whose troops  
flew silently into occupied France in gliders to seize a vital 
bridge at the start of the Allied invasion, died Wednesday. He was 
86. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard's 180 infantrymen, the first Allied forces into Normandy,  
took the Germans by surprise in the early hours of June 6, 1944, 
and seized Pegasus Bridge. They held on until they were relieved 
later that day by troops making their way inland from the invasion 
beachheads. 
</P>
<P>
	The story of Pegasus Bridge and Howard's Oxford and  
Buckinghamshire Light Infantry was part of the 1962 D-Day movie 
``The Longest Day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Howard was awarded the Distinguished Service Order for  
gallantry, Britain's second-highest military honor, and France's 
Croix de Guerre with Palm. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired from the army in 1945 and went into agricultural  
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The major's achievements are commemorated in Normandy by a  
bronze bust, which marks the spot where the gliders landed near 
Ouistreham. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Mark Tuinei    	
</P>
<P>
	PLANO, Texas (AP) -- Football star Mark Tuinei, who helped lead  
the Dallas Cowboys to three Super Bowl championships during his 
15-year career, died Thursday after a friend found him unconscious 
in his car outside his home. He was 39. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death was not immediately known. Foul play, alcohol  
or drugs were not believed to be involved, and Tuinei was not known 
to have had a life-threatening medical condition, Police Chief 
Bruce Glasscock said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-5, 320-pound Tuinei came to the Cowboys in 1983 as a  
free agent from Hawaii and made the team as a defensive lineman. He 
switched to offense in 1985, settling in at the crucial position of 
left tackle. 
</P>
<P>
	His protection of quarterback Troy Aikman and his run-blocking  
for running back Emmitt Smith were big reasons the Cowboys went 
from 1-15 in 1989 to Super Bowl champions in 1993, 1994 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuinei played in the Pro Bowl after the 1994 and 1995 seasons.  
Knee problems ended his career after the 1997 season. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Stan Wood    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Stan Wood, whose University of Southern  
California golf teams played in 22 NCAA championships in his 25 
years as coach, died Monday of a heart attack. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Several of his players at Southern Cal won major titles as  
professionals, including PGA champions Al Geiberger and Dave 
Stockton; Masters champion Craig Stadler; and U.S. Open champion 
Scott Simpson. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 25 years at USC, Wood's teams won 14 conference  
championships and had a dual meet record of 462-37. He also helped 
create the Golf Coaches Association of America and served as 
chairman of the NCAA Golf Committee from 1965 to 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood attended Southern Cal and worked for the Los Angeles Mirror  
as a golf writer before returning to coach at his alma mater. He 
became head coach in 1955 and retired in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood is survived by his wife Marianne and two stepsons.  
</P>
