<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 23:25:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves $13.1B for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican congressional leaders hope to ship  
legislation to President Clinton next week financing the clash with 
Yugoslavia and shoring up the U.S. military around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	The House moved in that direction Thursday, approving a $13.1  
billion package by a resounding 311-105 vote. Republicans supported 
the bill by more than 4-to-1 and Democrats backed it by more than 
2-to-1, as both parties signaled support for U.S. troops in week 
six of the air campaign against Serb forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the strongest expression of support we can give them  
with this bill today,'' said House Appropriations Committee 
Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate has not produced its own measure, but GOP leaders  
there want to keep the package close to the $6 billion Clinton 
proposed last month. Most of the funds would come from this year's 
projected Social Security surplus, and Senate Republicans are 
squeamish because they have repeatedly pledged not to touch that 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon expressed thanks for the House  
vote. But he added, ``Our biggest fear was that this would get held 
up somehow, and frankly that's still a concern'' because the Senate 
has not acted. 
</P>
<P>
	Underlining the difficulty of opposing defense spending while  
U.S. troops are in combat, the White House budget office did not 
threaten a presidential veto of the House bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead it urged lawmakers ``to avoid confrontation'' by cutting  
the bill and adding aid for U.S. farmers and Central America. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hope to work out a compromise and attach the  
military spending measure to another bill sought by Clinton but 
slowed in Congress. It bears aid for Central American nations 
battered by last fall's Hurricane Mitch and for U.S. farmers hurt 
by plummeting commodities prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the House measure included liberals unhappy that  
Clinton's request for the Pentagon had been doubled, and 
conservatives who oppose a conflict they say the president forced 
without congressional consultation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Donald Manzullo, R-Ill., said supporting the troops means  
more than just supplying them with weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It means giving them the constitutional protection not to be  
put into the war'' without Congress' consent, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	An effort led by Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla., to bar a ground  
war without lawmakers' approval was defeated 301-117. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 249-180 last week for nearly identical language  
requiring congressional approval for a ground campaign, a symbolic 
measure lawmakers knew Clinton would veto. With Democrats warning 
of a veto of the entire spending bill if Istook's language was 
attached, Istook's proposal was defeated. 
</P>
<P>
	A Democratic attempt to shrink the spending measure lost  
260-164. It would have left the bill at $11.6 billion -- including 
$1.3 billion for Central America and U.S. farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	In another vote eight days ago, the House refused to support the  
U.S.-led NATO air campaign, with Republicans supplying most of the 
opposition. Democrats contrasted that with Thursday's passage of 
twice the $6 billion Clinton wanted to wage the air war through 
September and care for hundreds of thousands of refugees who have 
fled Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have frankly got whiplash from watching the majority party  
reverse its position,'' said Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, top 
Democrat on the Appropriations panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The House's additions include $1.1 billion to buy missiles and  
bombs, $1.3 billion for spare parts, $1.8 billion to improve 
troops' pay and pensions, and $1.1 billion to modernize military 
bases, mostly in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Republicans used Thursday's debate to try pinning the need  
for the extra money on Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``The White House has bombed its way around the globe while  
dropping troops far and wide for ill-defined peacemaking duties,'' 
said House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas. ``This policy has 
gutted the American military -- which now must be rebuilt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By voice vote, lawmakers approved language by Rep. Tom Latham,  
R-Iowa, adding nearly $110 million in assistance to American 
farmers. A provision by Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., adding $67 
million in refugee aid was also added by voice vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
