<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> East Timorese Still in Fear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- International officials hope a  
U.N.-sponsored ballot in East Timor will end the bloody violence 
among factions for and against independence from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	But after decades of human rights abuses and weeks of escalating  
fighting, some in the former Portuguese colony were still too 
afraid Thursday to say what they want -- casting doubt on whether 
the vote can be held freely. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can die for talking about such things,'' said Domingos  
Sequera, who sells cabbages in a market in Dili, East Timor's 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't ask me what I will vote for. It's a secret,'' said  
another vendor, Ijoalina Belo. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia and Portugal signed an agreement Wednesday allowing  
the East Timorese to vote Aug. 8 on whether to become an autonomous 
state within Indonesia or break away. 
</P>
<P>
	In a show of broad international support, 36 nations offered to  
give financial support for the ballot during a meeting at the 
United Nations on Thursday, although they are waiting to hear the 
needs for the vote before making specific pledges. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal and Australia have already made contributions of $10  
million and $7 million respectively to a U.N. trust fund set up for 
the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia invaded East Timor in 1975 and later annexed it. In a  
surprise reversal, it said this year it would grant independence if 
East Timor's people reject the autonomy offer struck after 15 years 
of negotiations between Portugal and Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal would give the East Timorese control over local  
administration, education and cultural affairs, while Indonesia 
would stay responsible for security and defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after the U.N. agreement was signed, about 100 students  
demonstrated for independence outside the state University of East 
Timor, and raised a banner that read, ``Reject autonomy in every 
form.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has called for an immediate  
end to violence and the disarming of all factions so the vote can 
proceed. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is also deeply troubled by the unrestrained  
activities of militias who ``seek to bias the consultation through 
terror and intimidation,'' State Department spokesman James Foley 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	About 600 U.N. officials and advisers, including foreign police  
officers, were expected to start arriving in East Timor soon. 
</P>
<P>
	It's unclear, though, how they will end the bloodshed.  
</P>
<P>
	Anti-independence militiamen have killed dozens of civilians in  
recent weeks, and separatist rebels who have fought a guerrilla war 
for two decades have stepped up attacks against the military. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of villagers have fled their homes in terror. Armed  
gangs block roads in the countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	Militia leaders have criticized the U.N. agreement and  
threatened U.N. police advisers. Some said they accepted the ballot 
because they had no choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will accept any kind of outcome,'' activist Basilio Araujo  
said. ``Now we are powerless to stop the process that has been 
going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eurico Guterres, the leader of one militia group accused of  
attacking civilians recently, said he accepted the ballot plan but 
could not ensure the safety of U.N. staff or that the violence will 
stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor could he say whether his group would disarm in line with the  
U.N. agreement covering security for the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	``Disarmament won't be successful if it is not done fairly,'' he  
said. Pro-independence rebels ``must put down their weapons first 
before we will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Independence activists say the vast majority of East Timorese  
want to be separate from Indonesia, and accuse sections of the army 
of backing the militias in an attempt to derail the U.N. ballot 
through fear. Indonesia's generals deny the charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Separatist rebel leader Jose Alexandre ``Xanana'' Gusmao, who is  
under house arrest in the Indonesian capital Jakarta, hailed the 
agreement as ``historic'' and called on Indonesia to live up to 
U.N. demands that it keep the peace during the ballot period. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no doubt that there will be difficulties on the  
ground and that numerous obstacles will continue to be placed in 
the path of the preparation of a fair, democratic and transparent 
consultation,'' he said in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
