<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fraud Alleged in Tobacco Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEXARKANA, Texas (AP) -- The attorney general of Texas has  
accused his predecessor of conniving to enrich a lawyer friend with 
a massive payout from the state's $17.3 billion tobacco settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge David Folsom was to hear arguments today  
over whether former Attorney General Dan Morales, a Democrat, 
fabricated contracts with attorney Marc Murr that led to $260 
million in legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	John Cornyn, a Republican who replaced Morales as attorney  
general, claims the fee award was obtained through fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	A state arbitration panel awarded the fees to Murr for his role  
in the settlement obtained by Texas from the tobacco industry. 
Other attorneys in the case have said Murr did little or no work; 
Morales has said Murr played a crucial role in negotiating the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornyn tried to compel Morales to testify at today's hearing,  
but Folsom on Wednesday denied the request. 
</P>
<P>
	Morales' attorney, Sam Millsap, accused Cornyn of trying to turn  
the hearing ``into a political circus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm frustrated, as is Dan, that these bizarre allegations will  
hang out there until the appropriate time and place for response. 
There was no fraud. That simply is untrue,'' Millsap said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornyn's office is investigating whether Morales tried to funnel  
a portion of the settlement to Murr. The Justice Department and FBI 
are also conducting investigations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
