<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Role in Mideast Peace Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The American mediation role in the  
Arab-Israeli dispute is expanding, and it could influence the 
outcome of Mideast peace talks, Israel's U.S. ambassador says. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a need for a sheriff, but the sheriff should not be  
put in the position of a judge,'' Ambassador Zalman Shoval said 
Wednesday night. ``And the sheriff should remember who the good 
guys are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech and in response to questions at the American  
Enterprise Institute, a private research group, Shoval emphasized 
the unique role the United States played in mediating between 
Israel and the Arabs. 
</P>
<P>
	He stressed how the United States sometimes stood alone in  
support of Israel in world forums. 
</P>
<P>
	But, the veteran diplomat said, the U.S. role in mediating  
between Israel and the Palestinians has changed over the years to 
the point where it could influence the outcome of negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Any Israeli accord with the Palestinians must be worked out by  
the two sides and have their approval, he said. ``We should not 
slide into a situation where we say `Let George do it, let Bill do 
it, let Dennis do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shoval's remarks seemed intended for President Clinton and  
Dennis Ross, the senior U.S. mediator, although he also underscored 
the importance Israel attaches to America's friendship for the 
Jewish state. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, the Israeli envoy criticized Russia for providing  
advanced technology to Iran and other ``rogue states'' that he said 
could threaten Israel with nuclear weapons and destabilize the 
Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are concerned about that,'' Shoval' said, even as his  
government strengthens its ties with Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, in an interview, Shoval drew positive conclusions from  
a letter Clinton sent Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
<P>
	He said its most important message was that negotiations were  
the only way for the Palestinians to achieve their goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The letter is a total denial of unilateral actions on the part  
of the Palestinians,'' Shoval said after casting absentee ballots 
in Israel's national elections. ``We fully agree with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wrote Arafat the Palestinians deserved ``to live free,  
today, tomorrow and forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While he did not explicitly call for a Palestinian state, his  
letter was bound to boost Palestinian hopes for U.S. support toward 
that goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoval said, however, ``the Palestinians may read into this  
message more than is actually said in it. That's their problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department spokesman, James Foley, said the Clinton  
administration was not going to take a position on statehood. Asked 
whether the Bush administration's assurance to Israel that it did 
not back statehood was still in effect, Foley said: ``That is a 
matter to be determined in negotiations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter was timed to the passing of a target date set by  
Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization for dealing with 
statehood and other tough issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton assured Arafat the Palestinians had a right to  
``determine their own future on their own land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat had vowed to establish a state, with its capital in  
Jerusalem, if the Palestinians did not achieve statehood in 
negotiations with Israel by May 4. Under pressure from the Clinton 
administration to curb his rhetoric, the Palestinian leader 
subsequently spoke in terms of aspirations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
