<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of of AP Poll on Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Associated Press poll on guns is based on telephone  
interviews with 765 randomly selected adults from all states except 
Alaska and Hawaii. The interviewing was conducted April 16-19 by 
ICR of Media, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	The AP poll on guns and school violence is based on telephone  
interviews with 1,006 people taken April 28-May 2 by ICR. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were weighted to represent the population by key  
demographic factors such as age, sex, region and education. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first poll, no more than one time in 20 should chance  
variations in the sample cause the results to vary by more than 4 
percentage points from the answers that would be obtained if all 
Americans were polled. The margin of error in the second poll is 
plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	This margin of sampling error is larger for responses of  
subgroups, such as income categories. There are other sources of 
potential error in polls, including the wording and order of 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	The AP poll questions (because of rounding, sums may not total  
100 percent): 
</P>
<P>
	--Do you favor stricter gun control laws or do you oppose them?  
</P>
<P>
	(April 16-19) Favor, 55 percent; oppose, 34 percent; don't know,  
11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	(April 28-May 2) Favor, 63 percent; oppose, 31 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	--Which of these is more likely to decrease gun violence ...  
</P>
<P>
	(April 16-19) Better enforcement of existing gun laws, 47  
percent; tougher gun laws, 42 percent; neither, 7 percent; don't 
know, 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	(April 28-May 2) Better enforcement of existing gun laws, 39  
percent; tougher gun laws, 51 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Three gun questions asked in the April 16-19 poll.  
</P>
<P>
	--As you may know, several cities have filed lawsuits against gun  
manufacturers to recover money spent by hospitals and police 
departments dealing with gun violence. Do you think gun 
manufacturers should be held responsible for these costs, or not? 
</P>
<P>
	Should be held responsible, 21 percent; should not be held  
responsible, 70 percent; don't know, 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--The federal government requires background checks for most gun  
purchases. Do you think these background checks help reduce the 
number of crimes committed with guns, or not? 
</P>
<P>
	Helps, 52 percent; doesn't help, 42 percent; don't know, 5  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Does anyone in your household own a gun?  
</P>
<P>
	Yes, 44 percent; no, 55 percent; declined to answer, 1 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Three questions on school violence asked April 28-May 2.  
</P>
<P>
	--Which one of the following measures do you think would be the  
most effective way to stop violence in schools? 
</P>
<P>
	Reducing violence in TV shows and movies, 27 percent; putting  
metal detectors in schools, 23 percent; increasing counseling for 
teens, 21 percent; passing stricter gun laws, 10 percent; 
restricting Internet content, 9 percent; none of the above, 7 
percent; don't know, 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Thinking about the shootings last week at a Colorado high  
school, please tell me which one of these do you think is most to 
blame? 
</P>
<P>
	The boys' parents, 39 percent; availability of guns, 24 percent;  
television and movies, 14 percent; the Internet, 8 percent; school 
officials, 4 percent; none of the above, 6 percent; don't know, 4 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Do you think the parents should face charges if they have a  
child under 18 who commits a crime with a gun? 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, 39 percent; no, 52 percent; don't know, 9 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 05:25:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Bankruptcy Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation that would make it harder for  
people to sweep away their debts in bankruptcy easily passed the 
House despite a White House veto threat. 
</P>
<P>
	The House, seeking to stem the rising tide of personal  
bankruptcies, gave the bipartisan bill a 313-108 veto-proof vote 
Wednesday. The legislation, sought by credit card companies, got 
solid Republican support but split the Democrats. The Senate hasn't 
yet voted on a parallel measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration especially criticized the measure's  
creation of a ``means test'' based on debtors' income to determine 
whether they must gradually repay their debts or erase them 
entirely while under bankruptcy court protection from creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the White House called the means test  
``inflexible and arbitrary,'' while reaffirming its support in 
principle for rewriting the bankruptcy laws. 
</P>
<P>
	In another setback for the administration Wednesday, the Senate  
defeated, 52-45, an amendment that would have removed provisions in 
a financial services overhaul bill that Democrats saw as an attack 
on the 1977 Community Reinvestment Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, wants to  
exempt small rural banks from the community-lending law and make it 
harder for the government to use satisfactory community-lending 
ratings as a requirement for banks being allowed to expand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate also rejected, on a party-line 54-43 vote, a  
Democratic version of the financial services legislation, which 
would lift Depression-era barriers separating banks, securities 
firms and insurance companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the House vote on the bankruptcy bill, Judiciary  
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and Rep. John Conyers of 
Michigan, the panel's senior Democrat, tried to soften the means 
test provision, which uses the Internal Revenue Service's living 
expense standards to help determine how much debtors can repay. But 
their effort was rebuffed in a 238-184 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Big bank-owned credit card networks, notably Visa and  
MasterCard, and retail-business groups say their losses from debts 
forgiven in bankruptcy have forced them to raise interest rates for 
consumers who handle credit responsibly. 
</P>
<P>
	But consumer groups, unions, civil rights groups and bankruptcy  
attorneys maintain the legislation favors corporate profits over 
the needs of families struggling with debt who need a fresh start. 
They insist that the credit card companies share the blame by 
flooding consumers with mailed solicitations to entice them into 
easy credit. 
</P>
<P>
	By voice vote, the lawmakers adopted an amendment requiring  
credit card companies to clearly disclose their late-payment fees 
and how long it would take customers to pay off balances if they 
make only minimum monthly payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies also would have to clearly reveal the expiration  
dates of introductory ``teaser rates'' and the higher interest 
rates replacing them. The same disclosures would have to be made in 
offers for credit card accounts made over the Internet, which have 
attracted an estimated 7.8 million people in the last five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents also maintain that the bill, by barring certain credit  
card debts from being erased in bankruptcy, would force single 
mothers and children owed support by bankrupt fathers to compete 
with credit card companies in collecting debts. 
</P>
<P>
	But the measure's sponsors, led by Reps. George Gekas, R-Pa.,  
and Jim Moran, D-Va., say it gives highest priority among debts to 
child support and alimony payments, putting them ahead of credit 
card debt and other obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, bankruptcy overhaul legislation cleared the  
Banking Committee last month and went to the full chamber, but the 
key issue of providing information to credit card users remained 
unresolved. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers are responding to a rising tide of personal  
bankruptcies, which reached a record 1.4 million last year despite 
the strong economy, up more than 300 percent since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second straight year the House passed bankruptcy  
overhaul legislation. Last year, the administration threatened to 
veto a House-passed bill and the Senate adjourned without voting on 
the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislative action has come during a lobbying blitz by  
credit card companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies complain that too many people take shelter under  
the more lenient Chapter 7 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, which 
erases debts, when they could afford to restructure debts according 
to a court-ordered plan under Chapter 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:42:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  N. Ireland Talks Reach Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Seven hours of negotiations in London failed again  
Thursday to overcome the central dispute preventing Northern 
Ireland's Protestant-Catholic government from being formed -- the 
IRA's refusal to start surrendering its weaponry. 
</P>
<P>
	All the invited negotiators said they would meet again next week  
at British Prime Minister Tony Blair's Downing Street office. 
</P>
<P>
	They are trying to resolve an argument over whether the Irish  
Republican Army must start to disarm as a condition for the 
outlawed group's allied Sinn Fein party to take part in the 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``People want to see this chicken-and-egg situation resolved,''  
said Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble, the Protestant 
politician who would lead the 12-member government -- but who 
refuses to accept two Sinn Fein politicians as government 
colleagues unless the IRA first commits itself to disarming. 
</P>
<P>
	Sinn Fein's chairman, Mitchel McLaughlin, said the party's  
delegation had pressed Blair to force Trimble to form the 
government. But Trimble insists that move would only precipitate 
his ouster as Ulster Unionist leader in favor of a more hard-line 
figure. 
</P>
<P>
	Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern announced that many of his key  
advisers on Northern Ireland would remain in London this week to 
keep working alongside British government officials to draft 
various compromise proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahern said he didn't want the peace process to go on  
``drifting'' and expected some sort of conclusion within the next 
10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern Ireland's April 1998 peace accord envisioned that the  
government would be formed within six months, and that the IRA and 
outlawed pro-British paramilitary groups would have completely 
disarmed by May 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Blair and Ahern jointly proposed that Sinn Fein  
should be allowed to receive its two government posts if the IRA 
promised to start disarming within a month as part of a new 
national day of reconciliation. 
</P>
<P>
	Trimble accepted the formula, but Sinn Fein and the IRA rejected  
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:42:11 </DATE_TIME>
