<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Focusing on Fund Raising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Moving to politics after a focus on war,  
President Clinton is raising $700,000 from Democrats in Texas, a 
state whose Republican governor hopes to follow him to the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, who returned Thursday evening from a fast-paced trip to  
Europe, was flying to Houston and Austin for a pair of fund-raisers 
for the Democratic National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The president was to speak at a lunch in a fashionable Houston  
restaurant where the minimum donation was $20,000 a couple. 
Expected tally: $450,000. 
</P>
<P>
	At an evening outdoor fiesta at a private home in Austin, the  
Democrats expected $250,000 in contributions from some 125 guests 
paying a minimum of $1,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president is a popular fund-raiser and is looking forward  
to being with our friends and supporters in Texas,'' said Peter 
Kaufman, a party spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Clinton plans to shift gears again, moving on to  
Oklahoma to view the devastation left in the state by furious 
tornadoes. 
</P>
<P>
	In Europe, Clinton got reports on the NATO bombing of  
Yugoslavia, offered thanks to U.S. pilots flying missions over the 
Balkan nation and met in Germany with ethnic Albanians who have 
fled Serbian ethnic cleansing in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there is a real peace process under way,'' Clinton  
said during a stop in Bonn for a meeting with German Chancellor 
Gerhard Schroeder. ``But it has no chance of reaching a 
satisfactory conclusion unless we maintain allied unity and 
firmness.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
