<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11:30 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russia, NATO Agree on Kosovo Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Russia and Western powers agreed today on a  
common approach to seeking peace for Kosovo, including terms for an 
armed international force to secure the return of refugees. ``The 
Russians have accepted the proposition there needs to be a security 
presence on the ground in Kosovo,'' President Clinton's national 
security adviser, Sandy Berger, told reporters. Foreign ministers 
of the Group of Eight countries settled on a seven-point plan to be 
endorsed by the U.N. Security Council, German officials said. 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the security force 
``will have NATO at its core,'' adding that Russia will be ``part 
of it.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets Kosovo Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	INGELHEIM, Germany (AP) -- President Clinton comforted victims of  
ethnic cleansing in Kosovo, promising the refugees today: ``You 
will go home again in safety and in freedom.'' Clinton and German 
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder promised computer terminals at refugee 
centers to help track down lost relatives and ``so that you can 
constantly get news in your own language'' of the NATO effort to 
drive Serb forces from Kosovo. After an emotional discussion with 
refugees on a cluster of metal chairs, Clinton appealed to ethnic 
Albanians to resist hatred despite their plight. 

</P>
<P>
	Steele's Defense Calls No Witnesses  
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- Julie Hiatt Steele's lawyers rested their  
case today without calling any witnesses, saying the prosecutors 
failed to show that her statements, even if false, had hindered 
Kenneth Starr's investigation of President Clinton. The surprise 
move came after defense lawyers unsuccessfully sought a mistrial, 
asking U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton to dismiss all three 
counts of obstruction of justice and the single count of making a 
false statement to the FBI. 

</P>
<P>
	Amy Fisher Gets Parole After 7 Years  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Amy Fisher, who at 16 became the tabloid  
headline ``Long Island Lolita'' after shooting her lover's wife in 
the face, was granted parole today after nearly seven years in 
prison. Officials said she would be released within one week from 
Albion state prison where she is currently being held. ``She's been 
served (with the decision) this morning and granted release,'' 
state Parole Board spokesman Thomas Grant said. 

</P>
<P>
	Jury Gets 'Jenny Jones' Case  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Jurors began deliberating this morning  
whether producers of ``The Jenny Jones Show'' did ``everything ... 
except pull the trigger'' when a guest was killed after taping the 
program. Lawyers for the plaintiffs urged jurors yesterday to award 
$71.5 million in damages, saying the talk show and its corporate 
owner, Warner Bros., were liable for the shooting death of Scott 
Amedure. Amedure, who was gay, was killed after revealing his crush 
on another male guest. Eight of the nine jurors have to agree for a 
verdict. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Die in Tennessee Storms  
</P>
<P>
	LINDEN, Tenn. (AP) -- Powerful storms blew through western  
Tennessee early today, closing schools, damaging buildings in 30 
counties and killing at least four people. In North Carolina, high 
winds downed trees and closed the high school in Asheville today. A 
tornado was spotted 14 miles south of Burnsville, but the National 
Weather Service received no reports of damage. Severe thunderstorms 
moved across north Georgia today, knocking out power to about 
10,000 in the Atlanta area and dumping hail and heavy rain on some 
areas. 

</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales Strong in April  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sales at many of nation's biggest retailers  
soared to better-than-expected levels in April as the continued 
strength of the U.S. economy encouraged Americans to do lots of 
shopping last month. It was the third straight month of 
surprisingly strong sales, boding well for first-quarter earnings. 
A number of chains -- including the Limited and Ann Taylor -- have 
said they will top forecasts for the quarter. The big winners in 
April were specialty clothing chains. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, AT&AMP;T Form Alliance  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Deepening an alliance of titans of  
communications and technology, Microsoft Corp. said today it will 
invest $5 billion in AT&AMP;T Corp. and AT&AMP;T said it will increase its 
use of Microsoft's software. AT&AMP;T, the nation's No. 1 long-distance 
telephone company, is becoming the top cable TV business. It will 
own and operate cable systems serving approximately 25 million 
homes after its pending acquisition of MediaOne Group Inc., the 
nation's fourth-largest cable company. Microsoft is seeking to 
widen its role in the Internet. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Slips 54; Nasdaq Drops 11  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials  
were down 54.40 points at 10,901.01. Declining issues on the New 
York Stock Exchange led advancers 1,396-1,063. The Nasdaq was down 
11.56 at 2,522.88. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Dallas Cowboy Mark Tuinei Dies  
</P>
<P>
	PLANO, Texas (AP) -- Mark Tuinei, a star offensive lineman for  
the Dallas Cowboys in the mid-1990s, has died at age 39, a 
spokeswoman for the Collin County medical examiner said today. The 
cause of death was unknown, the spokeswoman said. Tuinei, a 
two-time Pro-Bowler at left tackle, played 15 years for the Cowboys 
before he was released in April 1998. He had played only six games 
in the 1997 season because of knee problems. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  


</P>
</TEXT>
