<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10:15 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russia, NATO Agree on Kosovo Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Russia and Western powers agreed today on a  
common approach to seeking peace for Kosovo, including terms for an 
armed international force to secure the return of refugees. ``The 
Russians have accepted the proposition there needs to be a security 
presence on the ground in Kosovo,'' President Clinton's national 
security adviser, Sandy Berger, told reporters with the president. 
Foreign ministers of the Group of Eight countries meeting outside 
Bonn settled on a seven-point plan to be endorsed by the U.N. 
Security Council, German officials said. German Foreign Minister 
Joschka Fischer called the agreement ``a considerable step 
forward.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets Kosovo Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	INGELHEIM, Germany (AP) -- President Clinton met today with  
victims of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's ethnic cleansing 
in Kosovo and promised that Milosevic ``will not succeed in erasing 
your presence from the land of your parents and grandparents.'' 
Clinton said the major industrial powers and Russia are nearing 
agreement on an international security force to protect ethnic 
Albanians once the fighting stops in Kosovo. ``You will go home 
again in safety and in freedom,'' Clinton pledged to the refugees. 

</P>
<P>
	Amy Fisher Gets Parole After 7 Years  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Amy Fisher, who at 16 became the tabloid  
headline ``Long Island Lolita'' after shooting her lover's wife in 
the face, was granted parole today after nearly seven years in 
prison. Officials said she would be released within one week from 
Albion state prison where she is currently being held. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Hails Productivity Gains  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Calling the performance of the U.S. economy in  
recent years ``truly phenomenal,'' Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan today credited a strong pickup in workers' productivity 
for the good times, but he warned that the global recovery from a 
severe financial crisis remains fragile. In a speech to an 
international banking conference in Chicago, Greenspan said 
productivity -- output per hour of work -- had clearly risen recently 
and he credited large investments being made in computers and other 
high-tech products of the information age. 

</P>
<P>
	Powerful Storms Strike Tennessee  
</P>
<P>
	LINDEN, Tenn. (AP) -- A line of powerful storms blew through  
western Tennessee early today, closing schools, damaging buildings 
in 30 counties and killing at least four people. Two of the 
victims, a man and woman, died in a Linden home that was destroyed 
by straight-line winds. A missing 14-year-old girl was found early 
today and taken to a hospital where she died on arrival. The fourth 
victim was killed when his car hit a tree that had been blown 
across a highway about 80 miles northeast of Memphis. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Inspect North Korean Site  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A U.S. team will begin inspecting a  
possible nuclear weapons site in North Korea on May 18, South 
Korean officials said today. About 15 American officials and 
nuclear experts will spend several days inspecting the site at 
Kumchang-ri, northwest of the North's capital of Pyongyang, they 
said. At least two inspections are planned to clear U.S. suspicions 
that the communist country may be reactivating a nuclear weapons 
program frozen under a 1994 agreement with Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Docs in Cancer Case Give Up Licenses  
</P>
<P>
	ATTLEBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Two pathologists accused of mistakenly  
diagnosing 19 men as free of prostate cancer when they actually had 
the disease have volunteered to give up their medical licenses 
temporarily. The state Board of Registration in Medicine said 
yesterday the two doctors, John C. DuVally and F. John J. 
Krolikowski, signed agreements not to practice medicine for 60 
days, pending a medical board investigation. The agreements do not 
preclude the medical board from taking disciplinary action. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, AT&AMP;T Form Alliance  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Deepening an alliance of titans of  
communications and technology, Microsoft Corp. said today it will 
invest $5 billion in AT&AMP;T Corp. and AT&AMP;T said it will increase its 
use of Microsoft's software. Under the agreement announced this 
morning, AT&AMP;T will expand its use of Microsoft software for 
advanced set-top devices, which provide access to telephone service 
and the Internet for cable TV users. But AT&AMP;T said it is not ruling 
out similar agreements with other technology businesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Slips 40 in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices have opened lower with the Dow  
Jones industrial average down 40 points in today's early going. 
Losers on the New York Stock Exchange hold a 4-3 lead over gainers. 
The Nasdaq Composite Index is down 3 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Dallas Cowboy Mark Tuinei Dies  
</P>
<P>
	PLANO, Texas (AP) -- Mark Tuinei, a star offensive lineman for  
the Dallas Cowboys in the mid-1990s, has died, a spokeswoman for 
the Collin County medical examiner said today. He was 39. The cause 
of death was unknown, the spokeswoman said. Tuinei, a two-time 
Pro-Bowler at left tackle, played 15 years for the Cowboys before 
he was released in April 1998 in a cost-cutting move even. He had 
played only six games in the 1997 season because of a sprained left 
knee and surgery to repair degenerating bone in his right knee. He 
had problems with his knees for years. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  


</P>
