<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:53:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Churchill Downs Buys Hollywood Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Think televised horse racing 24 hours a  
day. Think bettors sitting home at their computers, placing wagers 
on daily doubles at tracks from coast to coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeing dramatic changes on the horizon for the horse racing  
business, Churchill Downs is adding Hollywood Park to its string of 
tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The future of racing has never been better since I've been  
involved than what it is going into the new century,'' R. D. 
Hubbard, who agreed to sell Hollywood Park for $140 million, said 
during a news conference Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the major contribution going into the new century is  
TVG and home wagering and a 24-hour racing channel, and the overall 
simulcasting that is spreading across the country. That fits in 
with the strategy of what Churchill is trying to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So why did Hubbard decide to sell?  
</P>
<P>
	``Our strategy has shifted to where we want to become a  
single-purpose, gaming casino company,'' he said. ``There has been 
some confusion on Wall Street, are we a racing company or are we a 
casino company? I think this pretty well clarifies that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Meeker, Churchill Down's president and chief operating  
officer, was pleased to be in the West Coast market. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are thrilled at the prospect of expanding our racing  
operations from coast to coast,'' he said. ``With the recent 
acquisition of Calder Race Course in Miami and now possibly the 
Hollywood Park race track in Southern California, Churchill Downs 
will be positioned to be the premier race track operator and 
simulcast broadcaster in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Santa Anita, in the Los Angeles suburb of Arcadia, was sold last  
November to Canadian horse breeder and owner Frank Stronach, who 
paid $126 million for the track and 305 acres of land. 
</P>
<P>
	Meeker, noting that Hollywood Park was one of the few attractive  
racing facilities available, plans to put together a TV package. 
</P>
<P>
	``We control a lot of content right now. What we're trying to do  
is aggregate the quality products, and we're well down the road to 
getting that done,'' he said. ``Hopefully by the first quarter of 
next year, we will be able to unveil, in a coordinated way, our new 
simulcast programming. 
</P>
<P>
	``The programing we hope to provide to the industry is one that  
is not currently being provided, a program that has some continuity 
to it, high-quality production to it, and new features that make it 
much more user friendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marketing has been scattered since individual track owners were  
making their own deals for simulcasts and so on. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to use a coordinated approach to bring our product to  
the marketplace,'' Meeker said. ``We hope to create a product that 
is much like ESPN is to cable operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is to say, if you're a cable operator delivering a cable  
system in a particular market, you will not be able to go into that 
cable system unless you have ESPN as part of that portfolio. If 
you're an OTB operator, you will not will be able to deliver your 
simulcast products unless you have the Churchill Downs simulcast 
network. That's our objective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase of Hollywood Park, which opened in 1938, follows  
Churchill Downs' purchase of Calder Racecourse in Miami for $86 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, which must be approved by the California Horse  
Racing Board and other regulatory agencies and is expected to close 
in the third quarter of this year, Churchill Downs will acquire 237 
of Hollywood Park's 378 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	Included are the track, the casino adjoining it, and other real  
estate around the track. Hubbard's company will keep the remaining 
acreage at the track and will lease the casino, a California card 
club, from Churchill Downs for $3 million per year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbard plans to use the $140 million to develop a hotel and  
river boat casino in Indiana, scheduled to open next year upstream 
from Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
	His company also will seek to develop its remaining acreage  
around the track. Hubbard, who had sought to bring an NFL team to 
Hollywood Park, still did not rule out that possibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Churchill Downs has racing and simulcast wagering operations at  
Ellis Park in Henderson, Ky., Hoosier Park in Anderson, Ind., as 
well as a minority interest in Kentucky Downs in Franklin. It also 
holds interests in various other racing services companies. 
Churchill Downs, home of the Kentucky Derby, is the company's 
flagship operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``In selecting Churchill (as the buyer), the main thing in  
addition to money was to assure that racing will continue to be 
viable here,'' said Hubbard, who will continue to be active as a 
horse owner. ``I can assure you that with Churchill, that will 
happen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:35:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shot-Free Insulin Treatments Tested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers who tested more than 50,000  
natural and synthetic substances say they have found a fungus 
compound that acts like insulin, raising the possibility that 
diabetics in the future may take pills instead of shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists at Merck Research Laboratories isolated the  
insulin-like compound from a fungus found in the jungles of Congo 
in West Africa. When it was tested on mice that have diabetes, the 
researchers found that it significantly lowered the sugar in the 
animals' blood. The researchers said the compound is a mimic of 
insulin, the natural hormone that allows the body to metabolize 
sugar. 
</P>
<P>
	``This could potentially be used to replace insulin shots in  
diabetics,'' said Dr. Bei Zhang of Merck, the lead author of a 
study to be published Friday in the journal Science. She cautioned, 
however, that ``it is still very early,'' and that years of 
research remain before the compound could be tested in humans. 
</P>
<P>
	The compound, called L-783,281, was found by a team that  
laboriously tested 50,000 substances collected from around the 
world, checking each one for its ability to mimic the action of 
insulin. 
</P>
<P>
	L-783,281 was found to be promising in test tube studies, so the  
researchers carried it to the next step -- testing on animals. 
</P>
<P>
	Two strains of mice that naturally develop diabetes were treated  
with the compound and tests showed that L-783,281 helped the mouse 
cells to take glucose, or sugar, from the blood stream. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhang said the compound works in much the same way as insulin.  
L-783,281 links up with a specific molecule on the surface of each 
cell. This activates an enzyme that sets off a series of biological 
steps, enabling the cells to absorb and use sugar. 
</P>
<P>
	Diabetes is caused when the body is unable to make insulin, or  
becomes unable to use insulin properly. 
</P>
<P>
	People with Type I diabetes, the most serious form of the  
disease, may require up to four insulin shots a day to maintain the 
proper glucose level. Type I diabetes most commonly is diagnosed 
among children and young people. 
</P>
<P>
	In type II diabetes, which affects about 10 percent of Americans  
over the age of 40, patients are able to make insulin, but cells in 
the body become insensitive to the hormone. Type II diabetes 
usually is controlled by diet, weight loss and taking pills that 
improve the body's utilization of insulin. Some drugs recently 
approved by the Food and Drug Administration are for the treatment 
of Type II diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	All diabetic patients must frequently check glucose levels in  
their blood in order to properly control their disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhang said that, unlike insulin, L-783,281 can be taken as  
pills. The compound can be absorbed by the digestive system and 
still act on the cells of the body. Insulin is destroyed by 
digestion and, for this reason, must be given by injection, a 
regimen that is often difficult for patients to accept. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Robert Goldstein, vice president of research at the Juvenile  
Diabetes Foundation, said the discovery of L-783,281 ``is a real 
advance'' in diabetes research. 
</P>
<P>
	``It offers the promise of an alternative approach in which  
patients would not have to have insulin shots,'' he said. But 
Goldstein cautioned that a great deal more study is needed before 
L-783,281 could be safely tested on humans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This still needs a lot of work,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
