<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 07:05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AmeriCorps Has Serious Money Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite some progress, serious financial  
management problems still hamper the Corporation for National 
Service, which runs President Clinton's AmeriCorps program, 
auditors told a House panel Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is still pretty ugly,'' remarked Rep. Peter Hoekstra,  
R-Mich., after hearing the conclusions of Luise Jordan, the 
corporation's inspector general, and Karyn Molnar, a partner in the 
accounting firm of KPMG LLP. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is progress but we haven't solved the problem,'' said  
Hoekstra, chairman of the House Education Committee's oversight and 
investigations panel, which held a hearing on an audit of the 
corporation's statements for fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said the audit cited eight areas of the agency's  
financial operations as being ``materially weak,'' including its 
financial management and reporting, its financial systems and the 
management of millions of dollars in grants. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous audits identified six such areas, she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Also, until last year, the corporation could not even produce  
financial statements suitable for auditing. 
</P>
<P>
	The corporation received $714 million this year. Its programs  
include AmeriCorps, which enlists ordinary citizens for community 
service projects nationwide. Young adults get college tuition 
assistance in return. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning, Molnar said some of the problems are linked  
to the lack of strong financial management. The agency lost its 
chief financial officer and its deputy CFO last year; neither has 
been replaced. 
</P>
<P>
	``It cannot be overemphasized how important strong financial  
management is,'' Molnar said, adding that filling the CFO post is 
``the most important thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harris Wofford, the former Pennsylvania senator who heads the  
organization, said he expected the White House to nominate a 
candidate for the top financial slot in about six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Wofford said the agency has made steady progress in recent years  
and was ``within striking distance'' of solving its outstanding 
financial management issues. But installation of a new program to 
modernize accounting and funds control has been delayed until July 
to minimize disruptions and to permit certain grants to get out on 
time, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoekstra said that showed that officials were not serious about  
getting the corporation's financial house in order. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is unacceptable,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 10:45:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force To Review Failed Launches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Air Force today said it will convene a  
special review of the recent string of failed Titan IV rocket 
launches that have set back its space satellite programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Acting Air Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters said the review  
will be done jointly with the National Reconnaissance Office, which 
operates the government's military and intelligence satellite 
programs, and will recommend changes in practices and procedures to 
``assure continued access to space for the Defense Department.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, a Titan IV rocket left a military communications  
satellite in an orbit thousands of miles too low. And on April 9, a 
missile-warning satellite ended up in a useless orbit following its 
launch aboard a Titan IV, which is built by Lockheed Martin Corp. A 
Titan IV also failed in August 1998. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:48:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rugova Release May Affect NATO Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic's decision  
to let Kosovo's most prominent ethnic Albanian leader leave the 
country may be the most critical development yet affecting NATO's 
strategy of using force to impose a settlement in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibrahim Rugova arrived Wednesday in Rome along with his family.  
Rugova was elected president of the unrecognized Republic of Kosovo 
by ethnic Albanians who rejected Milosevic's heavy-handed rule in 
Kosovo, a Serb province with an ethnic Albanian majority. 
</P>
<P>
	Presumably, the 54-year-old intellectual is now free to speak  
freely about how he believes the crisis should be resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	If Rugova repeats statements attributed to him while he remained  
in Yugoslavia, it will undermine the Western strategy of using NATO 
planes and missiles to force Milosevic to settle the crisis on 
Western terms and enable an estimated 700,000 ethnic Albanian 
refugees to return home. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, if he repudiates those statements and  
endorses the NATO strategy, it would silence critics in the West 
and stiffen Western resolve to pursue the air campaign. It would 
also allay concerns among the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army that 
Rugova has sold out to the Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first news conference, held today in Rome, Rugova avoided  
saying whether he supported the NATO bombing campaign or whether 
meetings he had with Serb leaders had been held under duress. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he endorsed U.S. calls for NATO participation in an  
international peacekeeping force for Kosovo and also for the 
withdrawal of Serb forces so that all ethnic Albanian refugees 
could return safely. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Yugoslav media reported that Rugova and Serbia's  
president, Milan Milutinovic, signed a joint statement calling for 
an immediate resumption of talks between Serbian government and 
ethnic Albanian political leaders on a settlement granting ``wide 
self-rule'' with ``full equality'' for all in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement also called for an end to NATO bombing, although  
for weeks before the March 24 air campaign began, Rugova -- a 
lifelong pacifist -- had been urging Western military intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	Western and NATO officials have discounted the joint  
declaration, claiming Rugova and his family were under house arrest 
in the Kosovo capital of Pristina and that such statements were 
probably made under duress. 
</P>
<P>
	If Rugova were to repeat a call for an end to the bombing  
campaign, it would have a major impact, since the stated purpose of 
the Western air assault is to protect and defend the very people 
whom many Western governments believe he represents. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps because of the uncertainty of where Rugova stands, State  
Department spokesman James Foley reacted to news of his appearance 
in Italy positively but with restraint. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very glad he was able to leave,'' Foley said. ``It's a  
positive development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Washington considers Rugova the leader of the ethnic  
Albanians, Foley replied simply: ``That's for the Kosovars to 
decide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting with Milutinovic, however, followed talks between  
Rugova and Milosevic on April 1. That led to suspicion among some 
Kosovo Albanians that Rugova may have been willing to deal with the 
Milosevic government, perhaps trying to spare his people further 
suffering or enhance his own position against militant rivals in 
his community. 
</P>
<P>
	Baton Haxhiu, chief editor of Kosovo's Koha Ditore newspaper,  
told reporters Wednesday that Rugova ``has been brought'' to Italy 
to unveil a ``compromise'' peace plan worked out with Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Robert Reid is the East European bureau chief  
for The Associated Press, based in Vienna. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:48:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rugova Release May Affect NATO Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic's decision  
to let Kosovo's most prominent ethnic Albanian leader leave the 
country may be the most critical development yet affecting NATO's 
strategy of using force to impose a settlement in Kosovo. 
