<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) -- A group of Springfield ministers says  
white supremacists have been passing off their annual convention in 
the area as religion for too many years, and they've had enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than organizing a demonstration, they're trying to  
undermine the meeting by asking area hotel and convention 
facilities to turn away the group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saying nothing gives them the idea of acceptance ... If  
they've been coming back, they must feel acceptance,'' said Mike 
Adamek of First Unitarian Universalist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	Making the convention feel unwelcome won't be easy. It is  
organized by Everett Ramsey, pastor of Faith Baptist Church in 
Houston, Mo., who says there's no reason to worry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been there seven years and never had any trouble. We're  
nothing but a Baptist group. I have nothing else to say,'' said 
Ramsey. 
</P>
<P>
	However, national organizations that monitor extremist activity  
claim Ramsey's church is a hate group and belongs to the Christian 
Identity movement. 
</P>
<P>
	Devin Burghart, director of a center in Oak Park, Ill., which  
monitors and reports on organized hate groups, said Christian 
Identity has about 25,000 members nationwide who believe Jews are 
satanic and nonwhites are inferior. Many of the speakers expected 
at Ramsey's convention have Christian Identity ties, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Burghart suggested ministers educate their congregations about  
the group and organize against the meeting in mid-May. Such 
tactics, he said, kept a similar meeting from taking place in 
Quincy, Ill., in March. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Bishops' letter urging better care for river    	
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Roman Catholic bishops are weighing in on the  
debate over the Columbia River and its resources. 
</P>
<P>
	The bishops, whose territory covers the Columbia River  
watershed, are writing a pastoral letter urging people to be better 
caretakers of the river. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastoral letters are rare. In the past, they've been written on  
issues like war, peace, homosexuality and poverty in America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time has come for us to do this,'' said Bishop Carlos  
Sevilla of Yakima. ``They're talking about breaching dams and 
commercializing the Hanford Reach... .'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter, to be released this month, emphasizes the river's  
position as the spiritual lifeblood of the region, not as the 
economic workhorse it has become. It is earning praise simply for 
putting a fresh perspective into the lengthy debate over water 
quality and salmon health. 
</P>
<P>
	John Harrison, information officer for the Northwest Planning  
Power Council, welcomes it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot in the Bible about protecting what's good and  
what God gave us,'' he said. ``If the church really has something 
to say here, about the cultural conflicts as well as the 
environmental crisis, it puts a different spin on it... .'' 
</P>
<P>
	James Anderson, a University of Washington fisheries professor,  
also says the bishops' approach is different. 
</P>
<P>
	``We usually just focus on the science, but it's becoming a  
question of community values. To me the most interesting question 
now is how we can blend science with advocacy, with our emotional 
and intuitive sense of what we want for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *For Vietnamese, a church of their own    	
</P>
<P>
	EASTPOINTE, Mich. (AP) -- Vietnamese Catholics have more than a  
place of worship in a new church in suburban Detroit. They also 
have a place to share their experiences, which for many are stories 
of their escape from Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Ypsilanti autoworker Kiem Hoang says as a boy in Vietnam he  
would walk his blind grandmother to the local Catholic church every 
morning before school. After fleeing Vietnam in 1975 and arriving 
in the United States, the church helped his family find jobs and 
housing and to learn English. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been a big part of my life,'' said Hoang, 38. ``Now I'm  
trying to make my children understand the religion and culture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoang was among hundreds of worshippers at the recent formal  
opening of Our Lady of Grace Church in Eastpointe, the first 
Vietnamese Catholic Church in Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels good to be in your own home,'' Father Vincent Nguyen  
An Ninh told the Detroit Free Press. ``It gives the Vietnamese 
community, not only Catholics, a face here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The majority of Vietnamese are Buddhist. But in the United  
States, about 25 percent practice Catholicism, which was introduced 
to Vietnam by a French missionary in the 17th century. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the Vietnamese Catholics were anti-Communists and fled,  
beginning with South Vietnam's fall in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	There are now about 10,000 Vietnamese in Michigan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 14:31:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Death Toll Rises After Tornadoes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Wearing hand-me-down clothes and driving  
borrowed cars, residents struggled to put their lives back together 
Thursday from the ruins of this week's twisters. The death toll, 
meanwhile, rose to 46 in Oklahoma and Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Kimberly Taylor wore a plaid overshirt, striped T-shirt and blue  
sweatpants as she collected clothes for her six children at a Del 
City church. She laughed at her mismatched outfit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our house was destroyed,'' she said. ``I don't have a car to  
even drive around in. Everything is just borrowed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 3,000 homes and businesses were destroyed in  
Oklahoma. About 1,500 buildings were destroyed in Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	The smell of hamburgers and sauteed onions wafted down one  
ravaged street in Moore, where volunteers served up free meals to 
residents picking through the ruins of their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Bulmer, a pastor at Oakcrest Church of Christ, handed out  
sandwiches, water and gloves to people with nothing left. Some were 
so grateful, they were speechless, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of times we have to insist they take things,'' he said.  
``These are proud people. They're not used to being on the 
receiving end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Incredible stories of survival came from hospital beds Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Angie Todd, her face swollen and bruised, had a broken shoulder,  
a shattered hand and a finger that will probably have to be 
amputated. The 29-year-old woman, her boyfriend and young son 
survived after being pulled from their bathroom and tossed four or 
five houses down the street. 
</P>
<P>
	``I actually remember being in the funnel of the tornado,'' Ms.  
Todd said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the injured died overnight, bringing the number of dead  
from Monday's tornadoes in Oklahoma to 41. Five people died in 
Kansas. About 750 people in Oklahoma and 150 in Kansas were 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The phone at the Oklahoma Medical Examiner's Office continued to  
ring with calls from people worried about relatives unaccounted for 
since the storms. Fifty-four people were on the missing person's 
list Thursday morning, but the number dropped as loved ones were 
located safe and sound during the day, spokesman Ray Blakeney said. 
Searchers have combed devastated neighborhoods with dogs and 
infrared devices. 
</P>
<P>
	James Scarberry, 30, driving a pickup truck lent by a co-worker,  
felt lucky to have found his wallet and ATM card under the bed in 
what was left of his bedroom. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess you don't realize everything you're missing until you  
have to look for it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Masteller stood on top of her house, now 2 feet tall, in a  
T-shirt, jeans and shoes that were obviously too big for her. She 
wore an old pair of flowered-rimmed glasses that her son pulled 
from the rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all I've got,'' she said, tugging at the shirt. ``I  
don't have credit cards. I don't have a checking book. Not even my 
wedding ring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The school system in the suburb of Moore, which lost an  
elementary school and a high school, said classes will resume on 
Monday. The 2,200 displaced students will finish the last two weeks 
of school at a nearby college, another elementary school and an old 
administration building. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms damaged or destroyed the homes of at least 1,500  
students and those of nearly 100 teachers and administrators, 
district spokeswoman Susan Pierce said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel strongly that in a time of crisis, one thing the  
school can offer is routine, stability and structure in the school 
day,'' she said. ``It's important for those students who have 
suffered a great loss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore toured the tornado damage in  
Haysville, Kan., and hugged people who lost their homes. He said 
the Labor Department will spend $5.7 million to help clean up the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims of the storm were remembered Thursday during a ceremony  
at the Oklahoma Capitol to observe the National Day of Prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been through many devastating things,'' Lt. Gov. Mary  
Fallin said. ``This is a time Oklahoma can be revived. It's a time 
when Oklahoma can be renewed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 14:31:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
