elementary school and a high school, said classes will resume on 
Monday. The 2,200 displaced students will finish the last two weeks 
of school at a nearby college, another elementary school and an old 
administration building. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms damaged or destroyed the homes of at least 1,500  
students and those of nearly 100 teachers and administrators, 
district spokeswoman Susan Pierce said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel strongly that in a time of crisis, one thing the  
school can offer is routine, stability and structure in the school 
day,'' she said. ``It's important for those students who have 
suffered a great loss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore toured the tornado damage in  
Haysville, Kan., and hugged people who lost their homes. He said 
the Labor Department will spend $5.7 million to help clean up the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims of the storm were remembered Thursday during a ceremony  
at the Oklahoma Capitol to observe the National Day of Prayer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been through many devastating things,'' Lt. Gov. Mary  
Fallin said. ``This is a time Oklahoma can be revived. It's a time 
when Oklahoma can be renewed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
