<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Still Seeks Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization tried to break a  
deadlock today on whether a former prime minister from New Zealand 
or his rival from Thailand should be its new director-general. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the two rivals met for the fourth time since  
Italy's Renato Ruggiero vacated the post last Friday, a year after 
he announced his intention to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	A prolonged leadership vacuum could damage the WTO's efforts to  
mediate high-profile trade disputes and prepare for a November 
summit in Seattle to lower barriers to exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Former New Zealand Premier Mike Moore looked set to win last  
week after the diplomat conducting the selection process ruled out 
Thai Deputy Premier Supachai Panitchpakdi. 
</P>
<P>
	But Supachai's supporters, led by Japan and the Association of  
Southeast Asian Nations, refused to concede defeat. Saying the 
consultation process was flawed, they questioned the authority of 
Tanzanian Ambassador Ali Mchumo to exclude a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Supachai supporters say more than 50 members of the 134-nation  
WTO are holding out for the Thai candidate. Kenya has proposed that 
Mchumo try to reach a consensus around Supachai. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore's supporters, which include the United States and many  
Latin American countries, said they still believe consensus around 
their candidate is possible and called for Supachai to withdraw 
with dignity. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know that any time with 134 members, it takes time to  
build consensus, and we are on our way,'' U.S. trade ambassador 
Rita Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO has appointed David Hartridge, head of its services  
division, as acting director, but only to handle routine matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
