<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amy Fisher Gets Parole After 7 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Amy Fisher, the ``Long Island Lolita'' who  
shot her lover Joey Buttafuoco's wife, was paroled Thursday after 
serving more than six years in prison in a case that became a font 
of tabloid stories and TV movies. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Parole Board voted 2-1 to free Ms. Fisher, 24, who  
will be released within a week and live in the New York City area, 
parole board spokesman Thomas Grant said. An assistant to Ms. 
Fisher's lawyer said she has a job lined up in the fashion 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher pleaded guilty in 1992 to assault and was sentenced  
to five to 15 years in prison for shooting Mary Jo Buttafuoco in 
the head. Mrs. Buttafuoco, then 37, survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher, then 17, had been having an affair with Buttafuoco,  
the 38-year-old owner of an auto body shop. He pleaded guilty to 
statutory rape and served six months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buttafuocos now live in Los Angeles, where Buttafuoco has  
been a cable television talk show host and is pursuing an acting 
career. A publicist for the couple had no comment on the parole 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Ms. Fisher apologized to Mrs. Buttafuoco, who  
forgave her. The two had corresponded for several months. With the 
support of prosecutors and Mrs. Buttafuoco, a judge reduced Ms. 
Fisher's sentence to 3 1/2 to 10 1/2 years, making her immediately 
eligible for parole. 
</P>
<P>
	She will be on parole until 2003.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher's mother, Rose Fisher, said in a statement that she  
had ``prayed and waited for this moment to arrive. Knowing my 
daughter is coming home is the best Mother's Day gift I could wish 
for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She added: ``I am looking forward to holding her in my arms,  
telling her I love her, and getting started on the rest of our 
lives together.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
