<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Americans in Diving Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Mark Ruiz, coming off the first  
four gold-medal performance in national competition, qualified 
fourth today for the men's 3-meter finals in the USA Diving Grand 
Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruiz was the highest-finishing American diver, qualifying behind  
China's Xiong Ni, Russia's Dimitry Sautin and Mexico's Fernando 
Platas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been doing very well internationally. I've been diving  
very good and I'm just having fun,'' said Ruiz, one of four 
Americans to reach the final. 
</P>
<P>
	P.J. Bogert, Troy Dumais and David Pichler also were among the  
12 men who advanced to Saturday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruiz swept all three individual titles in last month's U.S.  
Spring Nationals in his hometown of Orlando, something that hadn't 
been achieved since Greg Louganis did it in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	He added a gold in the synchronized platform event, which will  
be making its Olympic debut next year in Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	The sweep has brought inevitable comparisons to Louganis, but it  
doesn't bother Ruiz. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's great,'' Ruiz said. ``Nobody else is going to be  
like Greg, to tell the truth. He's unique in the world, just like 
there's never going to be another Michael Jordan. I just try to do 
my best and hopefully I'll bring a gold to the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the Olympic Trials only a year away, this week will be a  
good test of how well Ruiz matches up on the international stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I do my dives good, I'm happy,'' he said. ``Hopefully, I'll  
end up in the top three.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The competition, which features many of the world's top divers,  
runs through the weekend. Finals in both men's and women's 
competition are Saturday and Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
