<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Up Vs. Dollar on Peace Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hopes for a peace agreement in Kosovo helped  
lift the European currency against the dollar Thursday. Trading 
against the yen was quiet following a holiday in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0802, up  
from $1.0740 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 120.50 Japanese yen, down slightly from  
120.65, in subdued trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Japan were closed Monday through Wednesday  
for the nation's Golden Week holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	News that Russia and the major Western powers had drafted a plan  
to end the conflict in Kosovo jolted the euro higher against the 
dollar. The euro had been declining on concerns that continued 
fighting in the province could affect the overall European economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Wide fluctuations on Wall Street also drove the dollar lower.  
Stocks seesawed again Thursday as cautious remarks from Federal 
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan fanned fears that inflation may 
return to the robust U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4870 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4944, and 1.4552 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4515. The British 
pound rose to $1.6415 from $1.6377. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8106 German 
marks, down from 1.8212; 6.0716 French francs, down from 6.1087; 
and 1,792.11 Italian lire, down from 1,801.80. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops Seek Gunman Who Killed Four </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) -- A man who got into an early morning  
argument Thursday at a nightclub walked up to a booth and shot a 
man in the head, then gunned down three others seated near him. All 
four were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators studied a security camera videotape of the  
killings hoping to identify the gunman, who fled. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting happened shortly before 2 a.m. inside the  
International Club in El Monte, about 12 miles east of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 patrons were inside when the gunman pulled a handgun  
and fired at the first victim. The man then sprayed bullets across 
the booth, shooting the first victim's friend and two other people 
sitting with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they did not know what prompted the argument.  
</P>
<P>
	The first victim and his friend died at the scene, as did a  
third man. A 23-year-old woman died at a hospital shortly 
afterward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
