<DOCNO> APW19990506.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:42:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suns Looking To Win in Portland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Cliff Robinson can think of no better place to  
erase his image as a playoff flop than Portland's Rose Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	For eight seasons, Robinson played for the Trail Blazers, and  
when he and the rest of the Phoenix Suns begin their first-round 
playoff series in Portland Saturday, he knows he will be reminded 
loudly and rudely of his postseason failures there. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what will make it so much better when things go well,''  
Robinson said Wednesday, ``that it's there in Portland where I've 
had such a bad reputation in the playoffs. It would be a great 
place to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At age 32, finishing his 10th NBA season, Robinson is a much  
less intense and thoroughly a no-nonsense player, far from his 
``Uncle Cliffy'' days in Portland. The red, black or white headband 
he always wore on his shaved head was discarded when he left the 
Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point in my career, as far as having individual  
accomplishments, the only accomplishment I want is to win a 
championship,'' Robinson said. ``At this point in the season, you 
want to lose yourself in the team. You want to forget about all 
that other stuff. My only goal is to go out there and play hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson still has a home in Portland and his son lives there.  
He said it will be a little more hectic than usual because he has 
so many friends there. But he says he is relishing the opportunity, 
and his teammates think he'll come through fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it will be tough. I think he's going to thrive  
on going back home and playing in Portland,'' guard Jason Kidd 
said. ``I think he's excited about that challenge. He's really 
committed, and if he plays the way he has all season, he shouldn't 
have any problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Phoenix, Robinson is not expected to be ``the'' star. That  
role goes to Kidd and Tom Gugliotta. Robinson, though, has been 
critical to a team sorely lacking in athletic ability. 
</P>
<P>
	This year has been one of Robinson's best. Playing small forward  
almost exclusively, he's averaged 16.4 points per game, shooting 
.475 from the field. He finished eighth in the NBA in 3-point 
accuracy at .417 percent (58-for-139), was second only to Kidd 
among the Suns in steals with 75 and blocked 59 shots, 21 more than 
anyone else on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Kidd said Robinson was among the top two or three defensive  
small forwards in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cliff has had a great year,'' coach Danny Ainge said. ``Cliff  
is going into a playoff series this year where he has to just 
continue the role that he's played always for us. If he just plays 
the role he's played all year, he'll be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson has averaged just over 16 points per game in his NBA  
career in the regular season. In the playoffs, the number drops to 
10.1. 
</P>
<P>
	His first three seasons, when he was part of a powerhouse  
Blazers team that twice made it to the NBA Finals, he had strong 
postseason efforts. But since then, he has shot better than 40 
percent only once is six playoff appearances. For his career, he's 
shot 21 percent from 3-point range in the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem followed him to Phoenix, where he shot .273  
(9-for-33) from the field and missed his only 3-pointer in the 
Suns' first-round loss to San Antonio last year. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't help that Robinson had to play center or big forward  
against San Antonio's David Robinson and Tim Duncan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cliff is more comfortable with his role this year,'' Ainge  
said. ``He's more suited to the small forward position as opposed 
to playing center. I anticipate good things out of Cliff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's Rex Chapman. The Suns' guard had shown signs of  
breaking out of his season-long shooting slump in recent games, a 
trend of great importance to the Suns. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a totally different team when Rex is stroking it from  
outside,'' Kidd said. 
</P>
<P>
	But two weeks ago in a game at Utah, Chapman was poked in the  
eye. He missed the next game and then was ordered to wear 
protective goggles. 
</P>
<P>
	Chapman hates them. He threw the goggles at the bench twice when  
Ainge tried to get him to wear them in Wednesday night's 
regular-season finale against Minnesota. During practice Thursday, 
when someone handed them to him, Chapman threw the goggles on the 
floor, stomped on them, then kicked the shattered remains away. 
</P>
<P>
	Ainge shrugged away the incident as if to say there's little he  
can do about it, and Chapman likely won't be wearing them in the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Chapman's emotion is a small concern. The emotion the Suns will  
face in Portland Saturday is of far greater importance to Ainge. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to be ornery. It's going to be loud,'' Ainge  
said. ``We have to try to keep close while the emotions are going 
crazy to start this series.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
