<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russia, NATO Agree on Kosovo Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Russia and Western powers agreed today on a  
common approach to seeking peace for Kosovo, including the basic 
terms of an international force to secure the return of refugees, 
diplomats said. Foreign ministers of the Group of Eight countries 
meeting outside Bonn were expected to announce formal agreement 
shortly on a seven-point plan to be endorsed by the U.N. Security 
Council, German officials said on condition of anonymity. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets Kosovo Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	INGELHEIM, Germany (AP) -- President Clinton met today with  
victims of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's ethnic cleansing 
in Kosovo and promised that Milosevic ``will not succeed in erasing 
your presence from the land of your parents and grandparents.'' 
Clinton said the major industrial powers and Russia are nearing 
agreement on an international security force to protect ethnic 
Albanians once the fighting stops in Kosovo. ``You will go home 
again in safety and in freedom,'' Clinton pledged to the refugees. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Strikes Yugoslavia Fuel Depots  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets struck fuel depots  
throughout Yugoslavia as diplomats from the United States, Russia 
and major European powers gathered today to try to agree on the 
outlines of a Kosovo peace accord. Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright joined European foreign ministers today in Bonn, Germany, 
to discuss an interim administration for Kosovo and the creation of 
a military force to protect ethnic Albanian refugees returning to 
the Yugoslav province. 

</P>
<P>
	Powerful Storms Strike Tennessee  
</P>
<P>
	LINDEN, Tenn. (AP) -- A line of powerful storms blew through  
western Tennessee early today, closing schools, damaging buildings 
in 30 counties and killing at least four people. Two of the 
victims, a man and woman, died in a Linden home that was destroyed 
by straight-line winds. A missing 14-year-old girl was found early 
today and taken to a hospital where she died on arrival. The fourth 
victim was killed when his car hit a tree that had been blown 
across a highway about 80 miles northeast of Memphis. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Inspect North Korean Site  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A U.S. team will begin inspecting a  
possible nuclear weapons site in North Korea on May 18, South 
Korean officials said today. About 15 American officials and 
nuclear experts will spend several days inspecting the site at 
Kumchang-ri, northwest of the North's capital of Pyongyang, they 
said. At least two inspections are planned to clear U.S. suspicions 
that the communist country may be reactivating a nuclear weapons 
program frozen under a 1994 agreement with Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Source: Amy Fisher Granted Parole  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A parole board has voted 2-1 to release Amy  
Fisher after nearly seven years in prison for shooting her lover's 
wife in the face, The Associated Press has learned. She is expected 
to be freed next week, according to a state official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. A Division of Parole spokesman would say 
only that Ms. Fisher would be notified of the panel's decision 
today. Ms. Fisher was 16 when she shot Mary Jo Buttafuoco in the 
head on New York's Long Island in 1992. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, AT&AMP;T Form Alliance  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Deepening an alliance of titans of  
communications and technology, Microsoft Corp. said today it will 
invest $5 billion in AT&AMP;T Corp. and AT&AMP;T said it will increase its 
use of Microsoft's software. Under the agreement announced this 
morning, AT&AMP;T will expand its use of Microsoft software for 
advanced set-top devices, which provide access to telephone service 
and the Internet for cable TV users. But AT&AMP;T said it is not ruling 
out similar agreements with other technology businesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Rise by 6,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing applications  
for unemployment benefits rose slightly last week after two 
consecutive weekly declines. The Labor Department reported today 
that 301,000 people filed for jobless benefits, an increase of 
6,000 from the previous week and about in line with economists' 
expectations. The government is scheduled to issue the unemployment 
report for April tomorrow and many economists believe it will 
remain at a 29-year low of 4.2 percent, demonstrating that 
America's economy is continuing to power ahead despite overseas 
financial turmoil. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Surge  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks surged 3.59 percent today, with the  
Nikkei Stock Average gaining 599.08 points to close at 17,300.61. 

</P>
<P>
	Dodgers 8, Expos 2  
</P>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Jamie Arnold allowed only one hit in 6 2/3  
scoreless innings in his first major league start, and Gary 
Sheffield homered twice last night as the Los Angeles Dodgers 
defeated the Montreal Expos 8-2. Arnold, pitching in place of 
injured Carlos Perez, held the Expos hitless until Orlando Cabrera 
singled leading off the sixth. Sheffield hit a three-run homer off 
Javier Vazquez in the third for a 3-0 lead. He hit his seventh home 
run, a solo shot, in the ninth. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  


</P>
