<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russia, NATO Agree on Kosovo Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Russia and the major Western powers set  
aside their differences over NATO airstrikes today and drafted a 
joint plan to end the Kosovo conflict, including the deployment of 
an international force to keep the peace after the withdrawal of 
Yugoslav forces. President Clinton and other Western officials 
welcomed Russia's backing for ``effective international civil and 
security presences'' in Kosovo, where a NATO campaign has failed to 
halt the expulsions of one-third of the ethnic Albanians in the 
southern Serb province since March. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Refugee Gives Birth in N.J.  
</P>
<P>
	FORT DIX, N.J. (AP) -- A Kosovo refugee woman gave birth to a new  
American today, a son born the day after she was airlifted to 
sanctuary from the chaotic Balkans. The 7-pound, 7-ounce boy, born 
at 2:11 p.m., is the first child for Lebibe Karaliju, 21, and her 
husband, Naim Karaliju, 28. The Karalijus were among 453 refugees 
from Kosovo who arrived in New Jersey yesterday. The group was met 
by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and U.S. officials, who are 
coordinating the $100 million resettlement effort. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate OKs Consumer Privacy Measure  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today adopted a measure aimed at  
protecting consumers' privacy by making it a federal crime for 
anyone to misrepresent himself to obtain someone's private 
financial data. The vote was 95-2 for the amendment to legislation 
the Senate is considering that would let banks, securities firms 
and insurance companies get more deeply into each other's 
businesses. The measure responded to Americans' growing concern 
over privacy in an era of consolidations creating huge financial 
institutions selling everything from checking accounts to mutual 
funds. 

</P>
<P>
	Steele's Defense Calls No Witnesses  
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- Charges that Julie Hiatt Steele gave  
false testimony in Kenneth Starr's investigation of President 
Clinton were sent to the jury today after her lawyers abruptly 
rested their case without calling any witnesses. Ms. Steele is 
charged with lying to FBI agents and grand jurors investigating 
former White House employee Kathleen Willey's allegation that 
Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance. Clinton has denied Mrs. 
Willey's account under oath. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Visit Littleton, Colo.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will visit Littleton, Colo.,  
May 20 to meet with Columbine High School students to discuss the 
April 20 massacre that left 14 students and one teacher dead. 
Clinton will visit students and their parents on the one-day trip. 
In response to the shootings, Clinton has called a White House 
strategy session for Monday with representatives of the Internet 
and entertainment industries, the gun lobby, government and the 
clergy. 

</P>
<P>
	Amy Fisher Gets Parole After 7 Years  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Amy Fisher, the ``Long Island Lolita'' who  
shot her lover Joey Buttafuoco's wife, was paroled today after 
serving more than six years in prison in a case that became a font 
of tabloid stories and TV movies. The state Parole Board voted 2-1 
to free Ms. Fisher, 24, who will be released within a week and live 
in the New York City area. Ms. Fisher's legal team said she has a 
job lined up in the fashion industry. Ms. Fisher pleaded guilty in 
1992 to assault and was sentenced to five to 15 years in prison for 
shooting Mary Jo Buttafuoco in the head. Mrs. Buttafuoco, then 37, 
survived. 

</P>
<P>
	Louima Testifies Against NYC Cops  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A composed Abner Louima took the witness stand  
today in the brutality trial of five officers, saying officers were 
``very angry'' from the first moments of an arrest that allegedly 
ended in his torture in a police-station bathroom. Louima said he 
had a heated confrontation with police outside a Brooklyn nightclub 
on the night of Aug. 9, 1997, when he heard that a fellow patron 
had been punched by an officer. After yelling at the officers, he 
heard someone behind him say, ``Shut up,'' then felt himself being 
knocked to the ground and handcuffed. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 1.71; Nasdaq Down 41.66  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the close, the Dow industrials were  
down 1.71 at 10,953.70. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,603-1,324. The Nasdaq was down 41.66 at 
2,492.78. 

</P>
