<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Says Weigh Soldiers' Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Military commanders making battle decisions  
should consider the potential long-term health effects on their 
troops in addition to any immediate danger, says a panel advising 
the government on medical issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to do, it's very hard to do,'' admitted Dr. Fred A.  
Mettler Jr. of the University of New Mexico, chairman of the 
Institute of Medicine committee that submitted the report and 
series of recommendations Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he added, ``just because it's difficult doesn't mean  
they shouldn't try to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As one goes toward peacekeeping type missions where you're not  
expecting a lot of fatalities, and things are not as urgent to get 
done, you really should be thinking about long-term effects and not 
say 'No one got killed so everything is wonderful,''' said Mettler, 
chairman of the Department of Radiology at the university's School 
of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Col. Carl Curling of the Army Surgeon General's office said  
commanders began looking at long-term health considerations 
following the Persian Gulf War. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really began to be concerned about this as far back as  
1992,'' Curling said, when troops were sent into Bosnia on 
peacekeeping duty. 
</P>
<P>
	``In general we're very happy with the report,'' he said, noting  
that it is still being reviewed by Army officials. ``I haven't seen 
a tremendous problem in any of the recommendations they provided,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The risk of global nuclear war has been reduced, but less  
intense exposure of troops can occur in small-scale nuclear 
exchanges, terrorist attacks, the use of radioactive materials in 
conventional explosives and in accidents at nuclear power plants. 
</P>
<P>
	The Institute was asked to study the threat of radiation  
exposure on soldiers, but didn't limit its recommendations to that 
threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``The long-term effects to be considered in operational  
decisions should include not only those from radiation but also 
those from conventional injuries, chemical and biological agents, 
and psychological stress,'' said the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditional risk evaluation in planning military action focuses  
on acute injuries that could affect the ability to accomplish a 
mission, while long-term consequences are left to the Department of 
Veterans Affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The report acknowledged that in many cases a commander ``is not  
likely to have hard data to use in assessing most long-term risks, 
and the long-term effects of some agents may not even be known.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, the panel added: ``That task of making difficult decisions  
is the precise job of the commander.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Institute of Medicine is an arm of the National Academy of  
Sciences, an independent organization that gives the government 
scientific advice. 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, the Army requested a study of the effects on  
soldiers of radiation doses of 700 milliSieverts. That amount would 
not have any immediate impact on an individual but would pose an 
increased risk of leukemia and other cancers in future. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the committee urged the Army to develop a philosophy of  
radiation protection including making sure that in peacetime or 
non-emergency situations, soldiers receive the same level of 
protection as civilian radiation workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also recommended:  
</P>
<P>
	--Increased training for soldiers in dealing with radiation.  
</P>
<P>
	--Keeping records of exposure to radiation in soldiers' permanent  
medical files. 
</P>
<P>
	--Seeking ways to minimize the radiation dose of their troops.  
</P>
<P>
	--Making sure the benefit of the action is worth the risk.  
</P>
</TEXT>
