<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Leases Sold in Alaska Wilds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- A vast wilderness set aside for  
commercial oil leases in 1923 had appeared safe from drilling after 
companies failed to find oil in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	But technological advances have made oil exploration more  
feasible, reigniting companies' interest in the 23 million acres of 
the National Petroleum Reserve-Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlantic Richfield Co. and a partner, Anadarko Petroleum Corp.,  
were the leading bidders Wednesday in the government's first sale 
of drilling leases in 15 years on the land 75 miles west of Prudhoe 
Bay. Arco and Anadarko won exploration and production rights to 93 
tracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Bids totaling about $105 million were accepted for 134 tracts in  
the northeast corner of the oil reserve, which was established by 
President Warren G. Harding to ensure that the Navy would always 
have enough fuel. The state and the federal government will split 
the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Lease sales in the 1980s were a flop, with only one dry well  
drilled, in part because exploration techniques were relatively 
primitive and the means to get oil to market underdeveloped. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, high-tech seismic exploration using powerful computers to  
locate underground reserves has companies interested again, and 
branches of the trans-Alaska oil pipeline now are closer to the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to environmental concerns, Interior Secretary Bruce  
Babbitt set a number of stipulations on the sale to protect key 
areas. He placed 600,000 acres off-limits to leasing, and 
restricted surface activity on another 900,000 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, The Sierra Club, one of the environmental groups that  
fought to block the lease sale, contends the Interior Department 
didn't do enough to keep oil activities away from wildlife. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen temporary protections fall by the wayside before,''  
said spokeswoman Sara Callaghan. ``In less than 30 years of North 
Slope development, we have hundreds of miles of roads, pipelines 
and toxic waste sites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists argue the reserve's wetlands are important  
waterfowl breeding grounds that can't withstand oil exploration. 
</P>
<P>
	It likely will take at least five years before any commercial  
production begins, said Kevin Meyers, Arco Alaska's president. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
