<DOCNO> APW19990506.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:55:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Lower; Dow Ends Off 8.59 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fluctuated again today and ended  
lower, unable to shake off growing worries about inflation that 
were fed by cautionary remarks from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 8.59 at 10,946.82.  
The Dow followed the same path it took in yesterday's session, 
changing direction several times. It fell as much as 103 points 
during afternoon trading today before regaining ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader market indicators also were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 15.23 at 1,332.08, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 61.27 at 2,473.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancers outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 873.7 million shares, 
down from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 4.32 at 633.05, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 2.32 at 787.81. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index, which reflects the performance of  
smaller-company stocks, fell 0.89 at 433.38. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are increasingly worried that the robust economy will  
reawaken inflation and prompt the Federal Reserve to push rates 
higher when its policy writers meet in two weeks. Higher rates are 
the market's nemesis, because they can quickly eat into corporate 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	In remarks to bankers in Chicago, Greenspan praised the  
performance of the U.S. economy in recent years, but warned that 
gains in productivity cannot keep inflation at bay forever. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I have said on previous occasions, there are imbalances in  
our expansion that, unless redressed, will bring this long run of 
strong growth and low inflation to a close,'' he said. He said 
tight labor markets, for example, could ultimately threaten the 
expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	His morning caused already jittery stock and bond markets to  
fall. The Treasury's 30-year bond carried a yield of 5.77 percent, 
up sharply from late Wednesday's 5.70 percent and from the 5.55 
percent levels of two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hawkish tone from Greenspan is shaking the trees of growth  
stocks and, as a result, continuing to put downward pressure on 
growth and financial stocks,'' said Tom Galvin, chief equity 
strategist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks were particularly hard hit by the  
interest rate worries. The discount broker Schwab Corp. was down 
sharply, and Chase Manhattan and J.P. Morgan were also among the 
losers. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail stocks also felt the pinch, despite the announcement  
today that many big retailers had better-than-expected sales in 
April. Gap Inc. fell sharply, partly because Easter sales were 
reported in March. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T was up after announcing that Microsoft Corp. will invest $5  
billion in the telecommunications company. In return, AT&AMP;T said it 
will increase its use of Microsoft's software. Microsoft fell 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, AT&AMP;T negotiated its victory in a bidding war with  
Comcast over MediaOne Group Inc., the nation's fourth-largest cable 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Internet stocks fell, perhaps at the threat from the  
Microsoft-AT&AMP;T communications alliance. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 05:21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Oklahomans Return to Tornado Scene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- In her debris-littered front yard,  
7-year-old Megan Varva leaped across chunks of concrete and wood 
like a gazelle on an obstacle course. 
</P>
<P>
	``My outfit is new,'' she said proudly, tugging at her  
pink-and-white striped shorts set. ``My mom said I'm going to be 
getting about a new outfit a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Megan's new wardrobe isn't a luxury. Her old clothes, like much  
of her neighborhood, lay twisted in the dirt after Monday's deadly 
tornadoes in Oklahoma and Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to go in there,'' the first-grader said of what  
little was left of her house. ``It isn't nice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many in the twister-scarred southern Plains would agree. Their  
homes are now nothing more than a jagged nest of splintered wood, 
mangled furniture, shattered glass -- and broken dreams. 
</P>
<P>
	The big orange ``U'' spray painted along a wall of 9-year-old  
Sara and 5-year-old Rebecca Johnson's home in Haysville, Kan., said 
it all: Uninhabitable. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 3 inches of rain have poured in through the roof. The  
house must be inspected for structural damage before Dave Johnson 
and his daughters can even think of returning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just picking up the pieces,'' Johnson said Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	All around Oklahoma City, cars -- some with smashed windows --  
lined up at police and National Guard checkpoints as families came 
to dig through the debris before an 8 p.m. curfew. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheryl and John Molsbee drove slowly past mounds of debris that  
obliterated neighborhood landmarks before finally pulling up to 
their brick-and-frame home. It no longer had a roof. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's worse than I thought,'' said John Molsbee.  
</P>
<P>
	Officials said 38 people died and more than 751 people were  
injured in the deadliest tornado to hit Oklahoma since 1947. The 
twisters killed five in Kansas and injured nearly 150 people. 
</P>
<P>
	More twisters swarmed across parts of Texas and Arkansas on  
Tuesday, killing one person. And late Wednesday, strong winds were 
blamed for several deaths in Tennessee as storms destroyed homes in 
dozens of counties and temporarily shut down the Nashville 
International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials had received about 100 missing persons reports in  
Oklahoma, but they were uncertain how many were duplicates. A 
master list of the missing was expected to be released today. 
</P>
<P>
	John Long, chief of the public education office for the Oklahoma  
City Fire Department, said he didn't expect the fatality count to 
grow by much. Rescuers have made at least three searches of each 
damaged home. 
</P>
<P>
	The damage estimate has been placed at more than $225 million in  
Oklahoma and more than $140 million in Kansas, where 1,129 
buildings were destroyed in Monday's storms. 
</P>
<P>
	A disaster housing program through the Federal Emergency  
Management Agency will provide rental assistance for up to 18 
months, said Ben Frizzell of the Oklahoma Office of Civil Emergency 
Management. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those trying to get their lives together was Calvin  
Waters, a sheet metal worker in Haysville whose home was heavily 
damaged. He spent a second day trying to clear the debris, patch 
holes in the roof and mop up. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters called himself fortunate. He was shaken by the deaths of  
a woman and her month-old baby near his home -- two people he didn't 
know. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always think a child should get a chance to grow up,'' he  
said. ``If you have to take two people, don't take a baby child. 
Take me, I'm 44 years old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has authorized emergency disaster declarations  
for both Oklahoma and Kansas, paving the way for federal emergency 
funds for home and business owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Anderson will likely need both forms of aid. Before a  
tornado destroyed his used motorcycle shop in Midwest City -- just 
outside Oklahoma City -- it stopped first in Moore, sucking up his 
home and leaving it a shattered pile of glass and metal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it hasn't sunk in yet,'' he said. ``Yesterday,  
I woke up and said it has to be a dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For hundreds of regional business owners, the nightmare has  
begun. 
</P>
<P>
	They must negotiate with insurance companies, hope for a fair  
and quick settlement, and eventually -- if they can manage it -- get 
back to business. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Silsby, an owner of a destroyed surplus store in Midwest  
City, tried to put a positive spin on things as he surveyed the 
wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday was the shock of, `I've lost everything,''' he said.  
``Now it doesn't matter. We can replace it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
