<HEADLINE>  Asian Markets Rise; Tokyo Surges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets rose Thursday, with  
Japan's key index soaring 3.59 percent to an 18-month high. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, growing expectations that Japan may intensify efforts  
to repair its economy pushed the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock 
Average up 599.08 points to 17,300.61 points -- its highest close 
since 17,363.74 on Oct. 24, 1997. The index fell 1.42 percent on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Japan were closed Monday through Wednesday  
for the nation's ``Golden Week'' holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said Monday in Washington that he  
would guarantee a revival of the Japanese economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshiro Mori, secretary-general of the ruling Liberal Democratic  
Party, reportedly hinted at the need to increase public spending to 
boost growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are expecting more spending,'' said Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi  
of Daiwa Securities in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese yen. The  
dollar bought 120.48 yen in late afternoon, up 0.90 yen from late 
last Friday in Tokyo but below its late New York level Wednesday of 
120.65 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares ended a volatile session lower as a recent  
rally that started early last month started running out of steam. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng index fell 15.97 points, or 0.1 percent, to close  
at 13,570.24. The index rose 0.2 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Hang Seng Index has failed to break through the 13,700  
level in the past several sessions, showing the market might have 
run out of steam,'' said Patrick Yiu of Kingsway SW Securities Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares rose 1.4 percent on last-minute buying in Thai  
Airways. The SET index rose 6.94 points to 512.69. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares rose despite a mild fall in telecommunication  
blue-chips. The JSX Composite Index rose 17.065 points, or 3 
percent, to 580.905 points. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose on the back of a recovery in other  
regional markets. The Composite Index rose 6.99 points, or 0.97 
percent, to 717.58. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares fell, although electronic shares helped support a  
market that had no clear direction. The Weighted Price Index fell 
12.11 points, or 0.15 percent, at 7,560.05. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: The STI rose 9.46 points, or 0.5 percent, at  
1,974.64. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares rose to a new 21-month high as an improving  
economic outlook sent blue chips on a rebound. The PSE index surged 
69.16 points, or 2.8 percent, to 2,516.83. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares fell as weak finance-related stocks outweighed a  
strong showing in the resources sector. The All Ordinaries index 
fell 3.1 points, or 0.1 percent, at 3,038.6. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose on strong investor demand for cyclical  
stocks such as Carter Holt Harvey Ltd. and Fletcher Challenge Ltd. 
The NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 14.57 points, or 0.65 percent, at 
2,248.89. 

</P>
</TEXT>
