<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 05:25:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Analysts Mull Pan-Europe Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The wave of consolidation reshaping European  
banks, phone companies and carmakers has reached the trading floors 
of the region's stock exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	Directors of eight leading stock markets hope to create the  
first pan-European exchange for blue-chip stocks that would provide 
unified trading rules. 
</P>
<P>
	While such a combination could lower costs for investors and  
enable Europe to better compete with Wall Street, some analysts 
said Wednesday that management and technical problems could stymie 
the international effort. One critic suggested that it was a 
throwback to an inefficient era of state-sponsored monopolies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a massive project. If they don't get it right the first  
time, it's going to be very difficult to get it off the ground,'' 
said Chris McKellick, director of trading at Societe Generale Asset 
Management U.K. Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	The heads of the eight exchanges signed an agreement Tuesday to  
work toward creating a Europewide stock market. The London Stock 
Exchange and Germany's Deutsche Boerse, which formed a strategic 
alliance last July, are the nucleus of the group. Joining them were 
leading exchanges in the Netherlands, Belgium, Spain, Italy, France 
and Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	The participants hope to create an efficient and low-cost market  
for the trading of shares in the region's strongest companies. And 
they're holding open the door to other national exchanges that may 
choose to participate. 
</P>
<P>
	Their project developed partly as a consequence of the adoption  
by 11 European nations of a single currency, the euro. That single 
currency lowered one barrier to cross-border trading, the cost of 
converting one country's currency to the currency in which the 
stock was being traded. But a pan-European market still would have 
currency problems because Britain and Switzerland have not adopted 
the euro, 
</P>
<P>
	Competition from U.S. stock exchanges has also played a part.  
The New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market both are 
considering extending hours to overlap with more of the trading day 
in Europe and Asia, putting pressure on profit margins for 
exchanges in those regions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is perfectly normal to expect a fully integrated  
pan-European exchange,'' said Paul Horne, an economist with Salomon 
Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts, however, foresee substantial challenges to the  
development of a truly regional bourse. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight European exchanges have refused to say how they expect  
to oversee their creation and to share profits from it. Technical 
problems are likely to slow efforts to integrate different 
electronic trading systems, while eight sets of regulations may 
prove tough to unify, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``One set of rules cannot suit every size of trade and every  
type of investor,'' said Narayan Naik, an associate professor of 
finance at London Business School. 
</P>
<P>
	Medium-sized and smaller firms will continue to trade on  
national stock markets, while specialized stock exchanges will try 
to lure away niche business from a pan-European market, Naik said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden's Stockholm Stock Exchange withdrew from the enterprise  
because it felt participants were moving in an anti-competitive 
direction. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this cartel is reactionary. They're trying to  
preserve an old sort of structure,'' spokesman Gustaf Sahlman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swedish exchange prefers offering clients a full range of  
trading, including such risky investments as derivatives and 
options, as well as stocks. It also plans to do more than the other 
eight exchanges to accommodate trading on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	McKellick of Societe Generale believes a pan-European exchange  
would be of greatest benefit to small investors, who would have 
centralized access to stocks from across the region. 
</P>
<P>
	But as in telecommunications, banking and other industries, the  
brokerage companies that stand to gain the most from a pan-European 
stock market are those that are biggest. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller brokerages will probably need to develop specialized  
skills in order to survive. Charterhouse Securities, a London-based 
brokerage, has chosen to focus strictly on analyzing British 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe some investors would like to come to a house that  
has a good, strong presence in the local market,'' said managing 
director Steve Adams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
