<DOCNO> APW19990506.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs Riding High in Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- After four huge victories in five days, the  
San Antonio Spurs finally indulged in some celebrating Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs, dominant down the stretch in the regular season, won  
the Midwest Division title and secured the No. 1 seed throughout 
the playoffs with an 88-81 victory at Golden State on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The games have come so fast and every one of them has been so  
important to us we haven't had a lot of time to relax and enjoy 
what was happening,'' said Spurs center David Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to enjoy it a little bit,'' Robinson said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs face No. 8 Minnesota in a best-of-5 Western Conference  
series beginning Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Saturday, the Spurs beat Portland in overtime in the  
Alamodome, then defeated Utah the next day in the dome. On Tuesday 
the Spurs beat the Trailblazers in Portland before the game in 
California on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of jubilant San Antonio fans, cheering and carrying  
signs saying ``Go Spurs Go,'' greeted the players on a warm, 
cloudless afternoon at the airport Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty awesome,'' said forward Sean Elliott. ``I wonder  
what's going to happen if we win this thing. They're going to rip 
the roof off this city. That'd be cool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing shirts proclaiming ``Midwest Division Champions,'' the  
players said they were trying to enjoy the moment before practice 
resumes Friday in preparation for the Timberwolves. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Spurs had lost to the Warriors, San Antonio would have  
been seeded No. 3 in the Western Conference behind Utah and 
Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio and Utah each went 37-13 this season, but the Spurs  
claimed the Midwest Division crown and the conference title because 
they won their season series against the Jazz 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than us getting the best record in the NBA, we wanted to  
win the last game going into the playoffs. But we understood that 
last game going into the playoffs had a lot of ramifications,'' 
said guard Avery Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he believes Utah will be the most formidable opponent in  
the postseason, Robinson said the Spurs must be ready to face a 
strong Timberwolves team in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been playing well. We've just got to keep doing the  
things we've been doing. Our defense has been at a great level, and 
that's what we need to carry us through,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team is farther along than any team I've ever been on,''  
said Robinson, a 10-year veteran. ``So I'm excited.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 14:35:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grizzlies' Worst Season Finally Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- For a franchise that has seen  
it's share of lows in its short four-year existence, the Vancouver 
Grizzlies out-did themselves this season. 
</P>
<P>
	They were the worst. The worst in the NBA with an 8-42 record.  
Their won-loss percentage of .160 was the worst in franchise 
history. And they lost a league-worst 24 road games, including 
their last 23 in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	How bad was this season? Three of their wins came against the  
Los Angeles Clippers, the NBA's second-worst team. On the other 
hand, they were a mere 3-24 against plus-.500 teams, with their 
biggest win coming against the Los Angeles Lakers, which was the 
last game for Lakers coach Del Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grizzlies suffered through a 13-game losing streak and lose  
seven in a row to end the season. Their 87-84 loss at home to 
Denver on April 7, marked the Nuggets' first road win in 25 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have mixed emotions about it. It was a very trying season,''  
said Grizzlies coach Brian Hill, who is 27-113 in two seasons with 
Vancouver. ``You're probably happy that it's over, because you 
don't want to see your team going through that anymore. And yet at 
the same time you want to immediately get started to rectify the 
situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody needs to step back away from it.''  
</P>
<P>
	When Shareef Abdur-Rahim was asked if he was happy to get this  
season out of the way, he said, ``Yeah, you kind of want to get the 
misery over with. ... The kind of season we had, I don't think 
there's anything encouraging about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abdur-Rahim, who entered this year signing a six-year contract  
extension, had a 23-points per game average, fourth best in the 
league. The only other bright spot was the play of rookie Mike 
Bibby, who stepped into the starting point guard role and finished 
averaging 13.2 points a game and 6.5 assists, 13th in the league, 
and tops among first-year players. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grizzlies were behind the eight-ball from the start when  
center Bryant Reeves reported to camp about 40 pounds overweight, 
and they then lost veteran point guard Lee Mayberry (ankle surgery) 
who missed all but nine games this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves' troubles didn't end. He started the season coming off  
the bench. By the time he got in game-shape, he suffered a 
season-ending knee injury and missed the last 25 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Down the stretch, the Grizzlies were forced to go with a  
starting lineup that featured journeyman Tony Massenburg at center, 
and two rookies -- Bibby and Felipe Lopez -- in the backcourt. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grizzlies, who's all-time record stands at 56-240, will now  
have their first shot at getting the No. 1 pick in this June's 
draft. Under the expansion rules introduced when they entered the 
NBA, the Grizzlies and fellow expansion Toronto Raptors were barred 
from getting the top pick in their first three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Grizzlies president and general manager Stu Jackson isn't sure  
what he will do with the pick, considering he has expressed a 
desire to add veteran experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be under enormous pressure to really trade that  
pick and really do the whirly-bird,'' Jackson said. ``But at the 
same time, we could have in front of us potentially an NBA All-Star 
of the future, which is ultimately the way you gain ground in this 
league. So it's going to be a tough dilemma.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, in the fourth year of his five-year contract, remained  
optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``A fan wrote me something the other day that I'll share with  
you. They wrote, `Gold has to undergo through some intense heat 
before it becomes a true metal.' And maybe this is the time when 
we're going through a little of that heat before we realize what it 
is we have,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how much more heat the team can take, Jackson said, ``I'm  
not a magician or a mind-reader. I don't have a crystal ball. I'll 
just leave it at that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 07:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
