<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Action Figures Hot As Gov. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- If every doll has its day, then today  
belonged to Jesse Ventura's. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of action figures in the likeness of Minnesota's  
governor flew off shelves at the Mall of America on Thursday, their 
first day in stores. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a grandmother won't do for her grandchildren,'' said Mary  
Lou Carlson, a Bloomington woman who bought the first four action 
figures around 9:30 a.m. at the megamall in suburban Bloomington. 
</P>
<P>
	The action figures became popular during Ventura's upstart  
campaign for governor. In one of the unusual television ads that 
helped him win, two boys were depicted playing with a Ventura doll 
who banged his fist on a desk and dismissed Evil Special Interest 
Man. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlson and dozens of other shoppers began lining up outside  
Pady Regnier's gift shop around 9 a.m. for the dolls' debut. Nearly 
3,000 action figures were sold in the first few hours the store was 
open, Regnier said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're mobbed,'' she said. ``I'm running out of SEALS and  
coaches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The action figures come in three outfits. The ``SEAL'' is an  
action figure of Ventura dressed in fatigues from his days in the 
Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two figures have Ventura dressed as a high school  
football coach -- he volunteers his services as conditioning coach 
at Champlin Park High School in Brooklyn Park -- and Ventura in a 
suit, his usual attire for his new job. Each doll costs $19.95. 
</P>
<P>
	After Ventura's election in November, entrepreneur Steve  
Tierschel created his own toy company and began manufacturing the 
action figures. Tierschel made the action figures in cooperation 
with Ventura for Minnesota Inc., a nonprofit company created by the 
governor to monitor and authorize use of his name and likeness on 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the company has contracts for Ventura action figures,  
pants, T-shirts, baseball caps, key chains and refrigerator 
magnets. 
</P>
<P>
	Any royalties due to Ventura's company from sales of the action  
figures will go to charity. 
</P>
<P>
	Tierschel said more than 70,000 action figures have been  
produced. The toys were distributed Thursday among five gift shops 
in the mall, but in coming weeks they will be available at larger 
retail outlets around Minnesota and the rest of the country, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Wodele, a spokesman for Ventura, referred questions to VMI,  
saying the figures are separate from the governor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The action figures are not a first for Ventura.  
</P>
<P>
	He said profits from a doll in his likeness during his pro  
wrestling days paid for his first Porsche. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 07:05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barney's Tabs Former Federated CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three months after emerging from bankruptcy,  
Barney's has hired the former top executive of Federated Department 
Stores to lead the clothing retailer's revival bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Barney's announced Wednesday that Allen Questrom will be its new  
CEO, replacing Tom Shull, who earlier this year said he planned to 
leave the high-end merchant. 
</P>
<P>
	Questrom, 59, joined Barney's board of directors in January, two  
years after he retired from Federated, where he worked for more 30 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, after a two-year stint as the head of Dallas-based  
Neiman Marcus, Questrom returned to Federated as chairman and CEO, 
guiding the Cincinnati-based retailer out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy 
reorganization. He also presided over a period of major growth as 
Federated bought R.H. Macy &AMP; Co. Inc. and Broadway Stores Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``Questrom proved himself to be a miracle worker at Federated,''  
said Kurt Barnard, who publishes Barnard's Retail Trend Report. 
``He is a man with great vision and the ability to execute that 
vision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barney's will be better served than ever before.''  
</P>
<P>
	Questrom is receiving no salary and will be compensated with  
equity in the company, according to officials for Barney's new 
owners, Bay Harbour Management and Whippoorwill Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in the 1920s in New York City by the Pressman family,  
Barney's evolved into a retailer known for expensive merchandise 
and a hip, urban clientele. It's not unusual for Barney's shoppers 
to find $500 jeans and $2,000 suits from top designers such as Jil 
Sander and Gucci. 
</P>
<P>
	But the company ran into financial trouble in the 1990s as it  
launched an aggressive expansion plan. By 1996, it was forced to 
file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy court protection. 
</P>
<P>
	Barney's emerged from bankruptcy in January under Shull, a  
former executive with Meridian Ventures Inc., which had been hired 
two years earlier to help shore up the company's finances. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pressman family, which ran Barney's until last year, no  
longer has an active role at the company. 
</P>
<P>
	When Shull announced plans to leave at the end of May, there  
were reports that Barney's was looking for a leader with both 
strong merchandising and financial skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that Barney's will have a total revitalization under  
his leadership,'' said Walter Loeb, who runs the retail consulting 
firm Loeb Associates. ``Barney's has always been a meeting point 
for the elite, and I think he will use that to help them grow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barney's now owns seven stores and 13 outlet shops.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:53:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Legion Backs US Pullout From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The American Legion is urging the Clinton  
administration to apply lessons learned in Vietnam and devise a 
clear military mission or immediately withdraw U.S. soldiers from 
the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our troops are not pawns in a chess game. They are our sons  
and daughters,'' said Harold L. ``Butch'' Miller, the national 
commander of the nation's largest veterans organization. ``They 
must not be sent into harm's way. If they are, it must be upon 
careful reflection by their commander in chief, and the consent of 
Congress and the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The legion's national executive committee voted 65-0 on  
Wednesday to approve a resolution calling for the withdrawal of 
troops unless Clinton provides a clear statement of U.S. interests 
and establishes campaign guidelines, including an exit strategy. It 
also urged Congress to pass a formal resolution supporting the 
military action and called for U.S. forces to be commanded only by 
U.S. officers. 
</P>
<P>
	It's an unprecedented move for the group, with about 2.9 million  
American veterans. The Legion had questioned some actions prior to 
U.S. involvement in Vietnam, but never called for troop 
withdrawals, Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's experience in Vietnam influenced several committee  
members who felt the organization should have taken a stronger 
position then, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The wisdom we have from Vietnam must be employed now,'' said  
Miller, a 51-year-old Vietnam veteran from Woodbridge, Va., whose 
son is serving in Operation Allied Force on a relief effort in 
Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	The legion supported Operation Desert Storm because troops had  
clear goals and all the resources they needed to complete their 
mission, legion members said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Russia and Western powers agreed on a common  
approach to seeking peace for Kosovo, including terms for an armed 
international force to secure the return of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said even with a possible peace accord near, the troops  
won't be safe until they are out of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We support the troops 100 percent,'' Miller said. ``That's the  
best we can do for anybody's son over there -- including mine.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:53:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UMass Lacrosse Player Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOLYOKE, Mass. (AP) -- Medical investigators hope an autopsy can  
help explain the death of a University of Massachusetts lacrosse 
player who collapsed when hit in the chest with a ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Sopracasa, 21, of Farmingville, N.Y., stopped breathing  
when he was struck during practice Wednesday afternoon on the 
Amherst campus, school officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was revived briefly and taken to Cooley Dickinson Hospital in  
Northampton. But he later died there, according to Jo-Anne Vanin, 
an associate vice chancellor for student affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Loren Mednick of Holyoke, a medical examiner, conducted an  
autopsy Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mednick listed the death as apparently accidental, but he did  
not issue a preliminary finding on a cause. It wasn't clear if the 
student's death could have involved any underlying cause, and the 
medical examiner did not plan a final report until toxicological 
and other tests are completed. 
</P>
<P>
	The junior was a clothing marketing major and a starting  
defensive midfielder for the lacrosse team. 
</P>
<P>
	Sopracasa, who was an All-American at Sachem High School in  
Farmingville, had apparently been in good health, university 
spokeswoman Kay Scanlan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Greg Canella, who met with the team for more than two  
hours Thursday, wept as he read a prepared statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eric was a great kid, a great teammate, a great supporter,''  
Canella said. 
</P>
<P>
	The team, which has a record of 4-8, was scheduled to play its  
final game of the season against Brown in Rhode Island on Saturday. 
On Thursday night, however, the team decided not to play the game. 
</P>
<P>
	No college player has died from a lacrosse injury since at least  
1982, according to surveys by the National Center for Catastrophic 
Sports Injury Research at the University of North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	But one college lacrosse player died of a heart attack during an  
offseason practice, according to the survey. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's incredibly tragic, but it's extremely rare,'' said Steve  
Steersen, director of U.S. Lacrosse, the national governing body 
for men's and women's lacrosse. 
</P>
<P>
	A lacrosse ball, which is made of hard rubber and weighs five  
ounces, can reach speeds of 80 mph when shot, Steersen said. 
</P>
<P>
	He had never heard of a player of any age dying from being  
struck in the chest. ``Players, especially defensemen, often get 
hit,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, doctors have found that even a moderate blow of a ball  
to the chest, if struck at precisely the wrong moment in the 
heartbeat cycle, can be fatal, said Dr. Adolph Hutter, past 
president of the American College of Cardiology and a cardiologist 
for the New England Patriots and Boston Bruins. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although it is extremely rare, it is the most common cause of  
sudden death in athletes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the blow causes the heart to quiver rather than beat  
steadily. ``The only way to get it back is to shock the person,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most cases have involved baseballs, he said, leading some  
doctors to urge softer balls and chest protectors for children in 
youth leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Hutter did not know of any instances in lacrosse, but said cases  
have also been reported in softball, karate, football, and hockey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 20:25:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Airline Seeks Injunction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Alaska Airlines filed suit in federal court  
today, seeking an injunction against a mechanics union and damages 
related to hundreds of forced flight cancellations since mid-April. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline said it has been forced to cancel more than 300  
flights for maintenance-related reasons. It alleges the job 
slowdown was orchestrated by members of the Aircraft Mechanics 
Fraternal Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The union, which represents 1,100 mechanics, referred all  
questions to Scott Petersen, a New York lawyer. He could not be 
reached for comment late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The union has previously denied any knowledge of a work  
slowdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``These problems were a result of normal operational wear and  
tear, and all were identified and addressed by maintenance 
personnel in a timely, conscientious manner,'' a recent union 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The carrier filed suit in U.S. District Court, seeking a  
permanent injunction against the union that would preclude illegal 
job actions. The airline also seeks unspecified damages. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're asking the courts to step in and order the union to  
compel its members to stop the slowdown,'' airline spokesman Jack 
Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 70 flights -- 27 on Thursday and 47 on Wednesday -- have  
been canceled in the past two days, Evans said. The usual number of 
daily cancellations hovers around five, he said, adding that the 
union's denials are not credible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's hard not to know about (the slowdown),'' he  
said. ``We're an airline with the youngest fleet in the nation. 
It's hard to have problems of such nature that it would take so 
long to repair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska Airlines schedules about 500 departures daily.  
</P>
<P>
	More than 10,000 travelers were affected when about 350 workers  
called in sick in mid-April. 
</P>
<P>
	All the airline's unions are negotiating contracts except  
pilots, whose most recent package was signed in 1997. Workers have 
complained that the talks are progressing slowly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:06:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cleaves Not Leaving for NBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- He could have followed the money.  
Instead, Mateen Cleaves followed his heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves, the point guard who led Michigan State to the NCAA  
tournament Final Four for the first time in 20 years last season, 
will stay in school next season rather than declare himself 
eligible for the NBA draft as an underclassman. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-2, 190-pound All-American from Flint made his  
announcement during a news conference Thursday at the Breslin 
Center, where he has led the Spartans to consecutive Big Ten 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the players on this team. I love Michigan State,''  
Cleaves said. ``I'm not ready to leave them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves had said after Michigan State's 68-62 loss to Duke in  
the national semifinals in March that he would stay in school. 
</P>
<P>
	``That last game left an empty feeling in my stomach,'' Cleaves  
said. ``This year, I want to bring it home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves is following the plan endorsed by Spartans coach Tom  
Izzo and by his mother, Fran Cleaves, who had said repeatedly she 
would like her son to finish work on his degree in communications. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you this is one of the happiest days of my life,''  
Fran Cleaves said. ``I want my son to get a college degree. My 
words to him were, `Do what your heart says, and listen to my 
heart, also.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Two of his peers -- Duke's Elton Brand, and Connecticut's Richard  
Hamilton -- already have decided to leave school early. But some NBA 
scouts believe Cleaves would be better off staying at Michigan 
State and working on his shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Chris Monter said Cleaves -- had he declared himself  
eligible for the draft -- probably would have been selected between 
15th and 20th in the first round of a draft fairly deep in point 
guards. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves, apparently aware of those reports, chafed at the  
suggestion that his game wasn't up to NBA standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do I think I can play in the NBA? Yes,'' Cleaves said.  
``Despite what people say, I'm not staying here to work on my game. 
I think I can play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the fact that he won Big Ten Player of the Year honors  
for the second straight season, Cleaves' scoring average dipped 
from 16.1 points per game in 1998 to 11.7. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there are few who can match Cleaves in clutch situations.  
</P>
<P>
	He scored the winning basket with 3.7 seconds remaining against  
Northwestern in the Big Ten tournament. Cleaves also hit the 
winning shot with 1.2 seconds left in a late-season game against 
Minnesota, and with four-tenths of a second remaining against Penn 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	With Cleaves back to run the show, the Spartans figure to be a  
threat to win the Big Ten championship again. They might also get 
another shot at their first NCAA title since Magic Johnson led the 
team to victory in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't imagine the sacrifice he's making,'' Izzo said. ``If  
he wanted to go, he'd be a millionaire. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a great day for Michigan State and for people  
around the country who are looking for a kid to be a role model.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There had been signs all along that he would remain in East  
Lansing. An example: Cleaves never registered with an agent, 
according to Pam Burke of the NBA Players Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a tough decision to tell you the truth,'' Cleaves  
said. ``My family and coaches just thought I ought to check 
everything out. The education is very important to me. I want my 
degree. I don't want to be known as just a jock.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:06:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
