<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Volkswagen Sued for `Nazi Nursery' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- German automaker Volkswagen has been sued in  
federal court, accused in the deaths of up to 400 Russian and 
Polish children who were in a company-run nursery while their 
parents were forced to work during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Milwaukee on  
Wednesday, says the children died between 1943 and 1945 as a result 
of maltreatment and inhumane conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they had been German they would have been cared for,  
period,'' attorney Lyn Rahilly said. ``They were not cared for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen's actions constitute ``genocide, war crimes and  
crimes against humanity,'' said the lawsuit, which seeks 
unspecified damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit lists only one plaintiff: 78-year-old Anna Snopczyk  
of Poland, whose 2-month-old baby died at the nursery. Rahilly said 
the lawyers hope the case would encourage others to come forward. 
</P>
<P>
	The nursery was established by Volkswagen to care for the babies  
of Polish and Russian forced laborers working at an automobile 
factory and neighboring farms in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen A.G. reissued a statement first released in November  
after CBS News aired a report on the deaths. It ``is a tragic 
chapter from one of the darkest times of modern history,'' the 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The widespread practice of forcing infants and children to be  
taken from their mothers and placed in special children's homes 
throughout Germany was another manifestation of the inhumanity of 
the Third Reich in World War II,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	A company spokesman said there would be no other comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Snopczyk, who worked at the factory, gave birth to a boy, Jozef,  
in February 1945. The nursery where her son was sent was infested 
with bugs and vermin, the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one told her what caused her son's death, the lawsuit said.  
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was based on information from war-crimes  
investigations and trial records, Rahilly said. It was filed in 
Milwaukee partly because of the area's large Polish population. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other lawsuits in the United States have been brought by  
former slave laborers against Volkswagen and other German 
companies, seeking compensation for their experiences during World 
War II. 
</P>
<P>
	A lead attorney in the Volkswagen lawsuit filed Wednesday,  
Michael Hausfeld, also was involved in a $1.25 billion settlement 
with Swiss banks for Holocaust survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrea Kupfer Schneider, an assistant professor of law at  
Marquette University, said the Volkswagen case goes beyond previous 
cases that involved compensation for slave laborers or insurance 
claims for Holocaust survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Accusing a private company of genocide and war crimes is  
pretty unique,'' said Schneider, who teaches international law and 
human rights. ``It really asks the question as to how far you can 
take these cases.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
