<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Citizens To Buy Part of State Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Citizens Financial Group will buy State Street  
Corp.'s commercial and retail banking business for $350 million in 
cash. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal strengthens the position of Citizens, a subsidiary of  
the Royal Bank of Scotland that started out as a small retail bank 
in Providence, R.I., but has grown its commercial lending portfolio 
from $1 billion to $5 billion in the past six years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something Citizens has always aspired to,'' said Lawrence  
K. Fish, chairman, president and CEO of Citizens. ``We'll have the 
opportunity to become a powerhouse in middle-market, small-business 
lending.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Citizens is buying a loan portfolio that averaged $1.9 billion  
for 1998 and totaled $2.2 billion on March 31. The deal, which is 
subject to regulatory approval, also includes $1.6 billion in 
deposits, two branches in Quincy and two in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	About 300 State Street employees will move to Citizens as a  
result of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Boston-based State Street, the sale completes a  
transition that began in 1975. That was when State Street decided 
to focus on serving institutional investors worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The company now has more than $5 trillion in assets under  
custody, and manages $525 billion through its investment management 
arm. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition, which is Citizens' 16th, will transform the  
institution into a $21 billion financial services company. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Citizens will be overshadowed in the region by the  
financial services giant that will be created when Fleet Financial 
Services completes its acquisition of Bank Boston Corp., creating a 
company with about $180 billion in assets. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
