<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices tumbled Thursday as Federal Reserve  
Chairman Alan Greenspan expressed concern over ``imbalances'' in 
the continued expansion of the U.S. economy. Yields reached their 
highest levels since last June. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond dropped 1 1/16  
point, or $1.06 1/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, shot up to 5.78 percent from 5.70 
percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's remarks at a banking conference in Chicago fueled  
concern that the Fed will raise interest rates in order to cool off 
the economy, although some analysts said they don't expect any 
immediate change. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher rates hurt the value of bonds and other investments that  
pay a fixed rate of return. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of most concern is how long this remarkable period of  
prosperity can be extended,'' Greenspan told an audience. ``There 
are imbalances in our expansion that, unless redressed, will bring 
this long run of strong growth and low inflation to a close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, Greenspan voiced concern over today's tight labor  
market. Unemployment now stands at a 29-year-low of 4.2 percent, 
far below the 6 percent level the Fed typically considers a sign of 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders also turned away from bonds as they anticipated the  
Labor Department's monthly unemployment report, due out Friday, 
will show continued job growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices plunged in the broader market as well. Prices of  
short-term Treasury securities were down 5/32 to 9/32 point. 
Intermediate maturities fell between 15/32 and 3/4 point, reported 
Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.60 percent as the  
discount remained unchanged at 4.48 percent. Six-month yields were 
4.67 percent, as the discount rose 0.02 percentage point to 4.50 
percent. One-year yields were 4.78 percent as the discount rose by 
0.04 percentage point from late Wednesday to 4.55 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.87 percent from 4.63 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 122 20/32 from 123 3/32 Wednesday. 
The average yield to maturity rose to 5.34 percent from 5.31 
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
