<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Sent to Indonesia Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LHOKSEUMAWE, Indonesia (AP) -- Riot police will be sent to  
restore order in northwestern Aceh province, Indonesia's military 
chief said Thursday, following the deaths of dozens of civilians 
this week in a clash between soldiers and villagers. 
</P>
<P>
	The reinforcements heading to Aceh, where separatist rebels have  
been fighting for years, would include bomb squads, said Gen 
Wiranto, who like many Indonesians uses only one name. 
</P>
<P>
	The new force, based in the capital, Jakarta, was set up to  
quell riots that have swept parts of Indonesia in the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, troops searching for a kidnapped soldier in the  
village of Pulo Rungkom opened fire on a crowd of residents, some 
of whom carried rocks, knives and sticks. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of dead civilians -- many shot in the back -- rose to  
39 on Thursday with the death of a 32-year-old woman, said Basri A. 
Gani, a member of a fact-finding team set up by the local 
government investigating military atrocities in Aceh. 
</P>
<P>
	The military said civilians in the crowd fired first, forcing  
soldiers to shoot back in self-defense. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, unidentified assailants with AK-47 rifles killed a  
police sergeant in the province. 
</P>
<P>
	After the fall of authoritarian President Suharto last year,  
Wiranto announced an end to a nearly decade-long operation against 
the rebel Free Aceh Movement. But anti-military violence escalated 
and troops resumed operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiranto said he hoped that the riot police force would be able  
to create a peaceful environment ahead of parliamentary elections 
on June 7. Some separatists plan to boycott the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to take precautions to prevent further violence,''  
Wiranto said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, about two dozen troops removed pro-independence  
banners and cleaned graffiti from streets and walls. 
</P>
<P>
	Other troops dismantled two ``humanitarian-posts'' where  
students solicited money and collected testimony about the 
shooting. The students had rebuilt the posts after authorities took 
them apart for the first time on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Aceh, about 1,100 miles northwest of Jakarta, is one of three  
provinces where separatists are active. The other two are the 
former Portuguese colony of East Timor and Irian Jaya, a former 
Dutch colony in western New Guinea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
