<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Next on `Springer': Knicks vs. Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	There is no truth to the rumor that Jerry Springer put in a  
last-minute bid for the the television rights to the NBA's 
first-round playoff series between the Knicks and Heat. For one 
thing, Springer couldn't keep a straight face long enough to utter 
the disclaimer Miami coach Pat Riley did. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think,'' Riley said Wednesday night, ``both teams have  
matured, hopefully, out of past transgressions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said this right after New York beat Miami 101-88 in a  
regular-season finale that proved absolutely nothing. Both Riley 
and Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy held important big and little men 
out of the game -- Alonzo Mourning and Tim Hardaway for the Heat, 
Patrick Ewing and Chris Childs for the Knicks. And even before it 
ended, Philadelphia beat Detroit in overtime to guarantee a New 
York-Miami postseason meeting for the third year running. 
</P>
<P>
	Considering the history of the matchup -- a 1997 melee resulted  
in six suspensions; the 1998 version produced three more and a 
priceless clip of Van Gundy clinging to Alonzo Mourning's leg and 
being dragged across the floor like a well-dressed mop -- Riley was 
smart enough to hedge his bets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now the fun starts,'' he said. ``You can never say something  
crazy isn't going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA and its network broadcast partner, NBC, would love to be  
able to say as much about the rest of their playoff series. The 
best chance for that to happen, at least in the opening round, will 
take place on the opposite coast, where the Lakers play host to the 
Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	Los-Angeles-Houston is the antithesis of New York-Miami. While  
the Heat and Knicks are ranked Nos. 1 and 3 in defense -- think of 
either squad as the Detroit Pistons of ``Bad Boys'' fame, but 
without the offense -- the Lakers are the NBA's best percentage 
shooting team at .467 and the Rockets are close at .437. 
</P>
<P>
	Needless to say, somebody is going to be very unhappy at the end  
of this series. The Rockets threw $13 million at Scottie Pippen to 
bring some of the Chicago Bulls mystique to Houston, but so far 
he's wound up on the outside of the offense looking in. The Lakers 
imported Dennis Rodman to do the same, but that chemistry 
experiment blew up in their face. What neither team figured out was 
that what put the Bulls over the top year after year was defensive 
prowess, and so the question running through this series, and the 
whole Western Conference side of the bracket, will be whether 
anybody has any real stopping power. 
</P>
<P>
	The obvious choice is Utah, since the Jazz were taken to school  
the last two finals by Michael Jordan and the Bulls. The Jazz, who 
drew Sacramento in the first round, continue to have trouble 
defending at the guard spot and could once more with rookie 
sensation Jason Williams matched up against John Stockton. But with 
Chris Webber, the Kings' most serious threat, hampered by a bad 
back, that one weakness won't cause Utah a serious problem. Neither 
will the guard tandem of Avery Johnson and Mario Elie at San 
Antonio, the only team in the West that figures to seriously extend 
the Jazz. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of watching the early rounds in the East, you might do  
yourself a favor and tune in to the NHL playoffs. The Detroit Red 
Wings and Colorado Avalanche will do just as much fighting as the 
Knicks and Heat, and chances are good that you'll even see more 
scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time you tune back to the NBA, you'll find the rested and  
ready Indiana Pacers, who actually did themselves a favor by 
failing to live up to expectations. By fading into the No. 2 seed, 
they drew a Milwaukee side just glad to be back in the playoffs for 
the first time since 1991 and ready to head for the exit. With a 
chance to catch its breath, Indiana will rediscover and rebuild the 
defense that extended Chicago to seven games in the conference 
finals last year. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the brackets are narrowed to two teams, expect the  
Jazz and Pacers -- just about everybody's preseason favorites -- to 
be there. Because of the lockout, the NBA had to cram a 50-game 
regular season into 89 nights, but all that concentrated effort 
proved is something that was apparent the last half-dozen seasons: 
The way to win a championship is to build a veteran squad and learn 
from the mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	What could ultimately determine the winner is homecourt  
advantage. The Pacers' Larry Bird, as shrewd a coach as he was a 
player, has been putting that message out all season and he argued 
his case in the newspapers in recent days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been hearing from these guys that it doesn't bother them  
to go on the road in the playoffs,'' Bird said. ``We'll see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So we will.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
