<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:53:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel: Sales Over Security Pushed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China gained valuable missile-related  
technology from U.S. contractors because of weak oversight and a 
permissive export policy during the Clinton administration, a 
bipartisan Senate report concludes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Intelligence Committee report also said the Reagan  
and Bush administrations contributed to policies that allowed space 
technology to flow to China. The report was to be released Friday. 
A copy was obtained Thursday by The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	During the Clinton administration, the report said, U.S.  
contractors conducted detailed technical reviews of Beijing rocket 
technology with little or no U.S. national security supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Such (technology) transfer enables the Peoples Republic of  
China to improve its present and future technical know-how,'' the 
report concluded. ``The committee further finds that improvements 
to the PRC's space launch capability increases the PRC's ability to 
use space for military reconnaissance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee said it reviewed intelligence reports dating to  
the 1980s that said China ``has had a strategic, coordinated effort 
to collect technological products and information from the U.S. 
government and private companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel was careful to say it has found no evidence that China  
has incorporated technology gained from U.S. contractors into its 
current ICBM force, which predates the policies allowing export of 
U.S. satellites to China. 
</P>
<P>
	But the report said revenue from U.S. companies buying Chinese  
launch services funded improvements in Chinese rockets which were 
virtually interchangeable for military or commercial purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. intelligence, meanwhile, is closely monitoring expected  
deployment within a few years of new Chinese missile systems with 
improved capability. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman David Leavy said President Clinton has  
already approved steps recommended by the committee to strengthen 
security oversight of satellite exports. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have strong controls to monitor the commercial satellite  
launches but we are concerned, as is the committee, that 
unauthorized transfers could assist China,'' Leavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that allegations regarding those transfers and the  
possible role of U.S. contractors is under investigation by the 
Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The 45-page report, which was approved in a near-unanimous vote  
by the committee, contains a short section on China's efforts to 
influence U.S. political campaigns with illegal campaign 
contributions. It said China's efforts were targeted at both 
Republicans and Democrats. U.S. intelligence developed reliable 
information on the Chinese campaign but was unable to conclude the 
level of coordination among the Chinese leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	While finding no specific wrongdoing by the Clinton  
administration, the report cited ``inadequate communication and 
coordination'' within U.S. agencies about the Chinese effort. 
</P>
<P>
	On satellite issues, the report found that decisions easing  
export rules by both Clinton and Bush ``emphasized commercial 
interests over national security.'' Both administrations failed to 
adequately fund satellite export security teams that would monitor 
interaction between U.S. contractors and Chinese officials, the 
panel concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Its report Hughes Electronics provided China with valuable  
technical information without U.S. government oversight following 
the 1995 crash of a Chinese rocket. 
</P>
<P>
	Loral Space &AMP; Communications did the same following a Chinese  
rocket crash the following year, also without U.S. government 
monitoring, the report said. The information given China ``applies 
equally to space launch vehicles and ballistic missiles,'' it 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of inadequate U.S. security prior to the failed Loral  
launch in 1996, ``certain key facilities were not guarded,'' the 
report said. ``Classified materials were left unattended (and) 
security officials did not adequately determine the nationality of 
foreign technicians working in sensitive site areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Martin Marietta engineers helped China address problems  
with satellite ``kick motors'' that can power satellites into a 
higher orbit but may also be used to propel missile warheads, the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for Loral and Lockheed Martin Corp., successor to  
Martin Marietta, did not immediately return calls seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes spokesman Richard Dore said, ``Hughes does not believe it  
was ever in the position of passing on any type of security 
information or anything that would compromise a national security 
situation'' to China. 
</P>
<P>
	Dore said Hughes abided by rules in effect at the time it  
conducted its technical reviews on Chinese space issues. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
