<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA, Union OK Limit on Free Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Free airline flights that some air traffic  
controllers used for personal trips will have new controls under an 
agreement between the government and the nation's largest air 
traffic controller union. 
</P>
<P>
	The cornerstone of the deal between the Federal Aviation  
Administration and the National Air Traffic Controllers' 
Association is that ``familiarization'' flights must now be 
proposed in writing, approved by a supervisor and meet a defined 
training objective. 
</P>
<P>
	On such trips, controllers are allowed to fly in airline  
cockpits, ostensibly to observe flight crews and see the other end 
of air traffic control conversations. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, there had been no such controls on the flights,  
leading to criticism that controllers were using them to take 
vacations, visit relatives or conduct other personal business. 
</P>
<P>
	Other elements of the agreement, which takes effect May 31, are:  
</P>
<P>
	--The number of flights will be limited to six roundtrips  
annually, down from a current maximum of nine. 
</P>
<P>
	--Controllers can take no more than two trips to the same  
airport, as opposed to the previous limit of eight. 
</P>
<P>
	--All flights must be made on duty time, unlike the previous  
limit of five trips on duty time. 
</P>
<P>
	--In order to take an international flight, a controller must  
handle international departures or oceanic airspace as part of his 
normal duties. 
</P>
<P>
	--The FAA and the controllers union will meet annually to ensure  
that there is adequate tracking and adherence to the new 
procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although there were problems with the program in the past, all  
parties agreed that the FAM program is a legitimate and valuable 
training tool,'' FAA spokesman Fraser Jones said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the new rules ``meet the training requirements as well  
as the test of ethics laws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Randy Schwitz, executive vice president of the controllers  
union, believes the program is a valuable one and he is pleased 
with terms of the new agreement, according to union spokeswoman 
Maureen McGaffin. 
</P>
<P>
	In February 1996, the inspector general of the Transportation  
Department released an audit saying that FAA personnel took 247,840 
free flights in the cabins or cockpits of commercial airliners 
between January 1993 and April 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The office estimated that 62 percent of the evaluators and 35  
percent of safety inspectors used their free-flight privileges to 
take vacations or visit families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
