<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Players Insist They Overslept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Six retired players who missed a flight returning  
the Cuban delegation from Baltimore following this week's game 
against the Orioles said today they simply overslept and never had 
any intention of trying to remain in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	One said U.S. officials tried to convince them to stay in the  
United States and criticized the only member of the 300-plus 
delegation who asked for asylum. All said they had not been 
pressured into returning, but they were not allowed to answer 
questions from reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I speak English, and they insisted that I stay in Washington  
and told me I wouldn't have any problems,'' said former player Juan 
Vives, describing conversations with U.S. immigration officials. 
``I told them I didn't have any problems in Cuba, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The six spoke during a news conference in Havana. They left  
Washington on Wednesday, and arrived in Havana from Jamaica on 
Thursday, three days after the Cuban team beat the Orioles 12-6 in 
an exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitching coach Rigoberto Betancourt was the only member of the  
300-person delegation who requested asylum in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I'm concerned, he's crazy, he's sick in the head,''  
Vives said. 
</P>
<P>
	Former catcher Evelio Hernandez was a bit more forgiving.  
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing happens when somebody stays behind'' on trips abroad,  
Hernandez said. ``We're not attacking anybody because they returned 
or didn't return.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez said the group that missed the flight got an extra  
bonus -- they got to see the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``We came out winning because we got to tour Washington, but I  
am bothered by the speculation that circulated about us wanting to 
stay,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
