<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Family Tragedy Recounted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Beverly Arthur saw that her mother got a  
rose in a crystal vase the night the tornado came. It was important 
to her, and it was one of the last things she did before she was 
killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Arthur was one of the 38 people to die in Monday's tornado  
outbreak in Oklahoma. She had gathered her family together for 
dinner, first giving her mother the rose that husband Melvin Arthur 
had cut in the back yard. Her mother, Lois Madden, lived in the 
Arthur home. 
</P>
<P>
	The family watched the warnings on television before taking  
cover, fearing the tornado could hit their neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we heard it, we got the pillows and headed for the  
hallway,'' Mrs. Madden recalled Wednesday as she recovered in a 
hospital. After the storm, Mrs. Madden said she was left with only 
half a pillow under her head. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I came to, I could hear the glass and wood still whirling  
around my head. I could hear the sucking,'' Mrs. Madden said. ``I 
felt I would die there. And that was OK, I was ready to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After regaining consciousness, Mrs. Madden could hear Mrs.  
Arthur, 51, calling to her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said, `I'm OK, I'm OK. Just go see about mother,''' Arthur  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said when he saw rescue workers pulling rubble off of his  
mother-in-law, he went back and found his wife was dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just looked gray. She had blood all over her legs,''  
Arthur said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was going to join her, I really wanted to join her,'' he  
said, his eyes filling with tears. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Madden, 70, talked about her loss from a bed in the same  
hospital where her daughter had a heart transplant two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jody Defehr, chaplain at Integris Baptist Medical Center, said  
he comforted Mrs. Arthur before the operation. Now he is helping 
relatives cope with her death. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before her operation, she was so weak she couldn't walk,'' he  
said. ``She was feeling better and better. Life was beginning to 
expand for her and now she's gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Madden said her daughter got to do many things in the last  
two years that would have never been possible without the 
transplant. 
</P>
<P>
	She wasn't surprised her daughter was more concerned about  
finding her mother in the rubble of their home than with her own 
health: ``That was her last thought: `See about mother.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 18:12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wynette's Widower Dropped From Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The widower of Tammy Wynette was dropped  
from a $50 million lawsuit brought by her daughters alleging he and 
the country music star's doctor were responsible for her death. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, my nightmare has ended,'' George Richey said at a news  
conference. He noted that Wednesday would have been Wynette's 57th 
birthday, and called it ``appropriate that we honored the occasion 
this way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was filed April 5 by three of Wynette's daughters --  
Tina Jones, Jackie Daly and Georgette Smith. Her fourth daughter, 
Gwen Nicholas, later joined the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The daughters have insisted the lawsuit is not motivated by  
money. Wynette left the bulk of her estate to Richey, her fifth 
husband, but her will stipulates it be divided among her four 
children and his two children when he dies. Anyone who challenges 
the terms gets nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	The daughters claim their mother's health wasn't monitored  
closely enough, and that she was given too many painkillers prior 
to her death on April 6, 1998. Dr. Wallis Marsh of Pittsburgh, 
Wynette's personal physician, was named along with Richey in the 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The daughters plan to continue seeking a judgment against Marsh,  
who has denied any wrongdoing and has Richey's support. 
</P>
<P>
	Richey did not pay the daughters to get them to drop him from  
the lawsuit, said his attorney, Robert Ritchie of Knoxville. 
</P>
<P>
	``George Richey did agree that he would not bring suit against  
the daughters for libel, slander or injury to reputation because of 
false statements made by them prior to May 5, 1999,'' Ritchie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richey also agreed he would not share in any damages the  
daughters are awarded if Marsh loses the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Principally, (the daughters) did it because Mr. Richey gave up  
his one-third interest in the proceeds of the lawsuit,'' said Ed 
Yarbrough, an attorney for the daughters. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Richey was a target of the lawsuit, by Tennessee law  
he would have gotten a third of any settlement or damages as an 
heir. 
</P>
<P>
	Yarbrough would not say if the daughters got anything else as  
part of the deal. They have complained in the past that Richey 
would not let them have any of Wynette's personal items. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be reasonable to assume there would be other  
inducements, but I am not allowed to comment,'' Yarbrough said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richey said he never wanted any part of settlement money or  
damages Marsh might have to pay. 
</P>
<P>
	``George believed -- and still believes -- that Dr. Marsh provided  
excellent medical care to Tammy during the last years of her life, 
enabling her to have some quality of life she would not have 
otherwise had,'' Ritchie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wynette, who had 20 No. 1 hits and was perhaps best known for  
``Stand By Your Man,'' was 55 when she died. She had suffered from 
painful medical problems for many years, including scarring from 
several surgeries on her intestines. Marsh prescribed various drugs 
to help her cope with the constant pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Richey discovered Wynette's body in their Nashville home and  
Marsh flew in to sign the death certificate. He listed the cause of 
death as a blood clot to the lungs. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Nashville Medical Examiner Bruce Levy declined a  
request by the daughters to have Wynette's body exhumed for an 
autopsy. But on April 14 the body was exhumed at the request of 
Richey, who said he wanted to resolve any lingering questions about 
the death. 
</P>
<P>
	No autopsy results have been released yet. Levy previously said  
he is confident he could determine what drugs were in Wynette's 
system at the time of her death but not sure he could determine the 
amounts of each drug. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
