<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of England Holds Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The Bank of England kept its base lending rate at  
5.25 percent Thursday, halting a seven-month trend of reductions 
due to concerns that another cut might stoke inflationary 
pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank's Monetary Policy Committee voted to maintain  
its curent base rate for loans to banks. The rate is the lowest in 
five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the European Central Bank left its key interest rate  
unchanged at 2.5 percent at its regular meeting Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank cut the rate by half a percentage point a month ago,  
the first reduction since it took over monetary policy for the 11 
European Union nations that adopted the euro currency on Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain has not adopted the euro.  
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of England policymaking panel based its decision on  
data showing signs of renewed growth and forecasts that inflation 
will remain in line with the targeted level of 2.5 percent, the 
bank said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank made ``the right decision,'' said Neil Parker, an  
economist with The Royal Bank of Scotland. 
</P>
<P>
	Parker expressed concern about the central bank's suggestion  
that it might lower rates in the future if the British pound does 
not weaken against other currencies. A strong pound makes British 
exports more expensive than goods from other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Bank of England's decision drew criticism from a  
major industrial union, the Manufacturing, Science and Finance 
union. 
</P>
<P>
	The MSF said the bank's committee members made ``a fatal error''  
by raising interest rates a year ago -- a decision that many blame 
for retarding economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their action this time around, by failing to lower rates, may  
turn out to be as serious an error,'' the union's general secretary 
Roger Lyons said. 
</P>
<P>
	``MSF will count every job lost during the summer, and we will  
not allow the bank to forget this disastrous mistake,'' Lyons said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank last changed the base lending rate on April 8, reducing  
it by a quarter of a percentage point to 5.25 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
