<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cable &AMP; Wireless Offer Hostile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- International Digital Communications Inc. is  
apparently sticking for the time being with a buyout bid by a 
Japanese company instead of accepting a more lucrative offer by 
Cable &AMP; Wireless. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for IDC, one of Japan's largest international phone  
companies, said the company had not decided on an official response 
to the offer by London-based Cable &AMP; Wireless, announced Thursday 
evening. 
</P>
<P>
	But Japanese media reports said IDC executives view Cable &AMP;  
Wireless' unsolicited takeover bid as hostile, raising the 
possibility they may try to resist. 
</P>
<P>
	IDC said in a statement that its board has already decided to  
recommend to shareholders that they sell the company to Nippon 
Telegraph &AMP; Telephone Corp. But it said the board would meet again 
to discuss the new offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless' cash offer is worth $460 million, or $895 a  
share, and is aimed at topping NTT's bid of $880 in stock per 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released Thursday night, Cable &AMP; Wireless  
executive director Stephen Pettit said his company was offering IDC 
``a competitive future as part of a worldwide communications 
group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a hostile bid. They believe the new offer has lots of  
benefits compared to the NTT offer,'' Sachiko Hasegawa, a 
spokeswoman for public relations firm Gavin Anderson and Co., which 
represents Cable &AMP; Wireless in Japan, said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless is already one of IDC's biggest shareholders  
with 17.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	While the British telecommunications giant said it ultimately  
wants complete ownership, its initial goal is to double its stake 
to 33.4 percent -- enough to give it a veto over board decisions and 
effective control of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	IDC is privately held by about 120 Japanese companies, and it is  
unclear how they will react to the offer. Unsolicited takeovers are 
rare in Japan, and previous attempts by foreigners have met with 
failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Attention is focused on the reaction of Toyota Motor Corp., one  
of IDC's three largest shareholders along with Cable &AMP; Wireless and 
Itochu Corp., a trading company. 
</P>
<P>
	With 17.7 percent of IDC's shares, Toyota's holdings would be  
enough to give Cable &AMP; Wireless the controlling stake it seeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota has reportedly said it would sell its holdings to the  
highest bidder. But accepting the bid by Cable &AMP; Wireless would 
risk drawing the ire of NTT, one of corporate Japan's most 
influential players. 
</P>
<P>
	The reaction of Toyota and other companies is being seen here as  
a test of just how much corporate Japan has changed. 
</P>
<P>
	Much ado has been made recently about steps to end the collusive  
ways companies here have done business and place more emphasis on 
the bottom line and shareholder return. 
</P>
<P>
	But old habits die hard, and criticism remains that Japan Inc.  
is as impenetrable as ever to outsiders. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, when Texas corporate raider T. Boone Pickens became the  
largest shareholder of Japanese auto parts maker Koito 
Manufacturing Co., Toyota, Koito's largest shareholder and 
customer, blocked his efforts to gain even a seat on the board 
until he eventually gave up and sold his stake. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
