<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> France Privatizing Defense Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The French Finance Ministry said today it would  
launch the privatization of aerospace group Aerospatiale Matra 
starting tomorrow. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came after shareholders of Aerospatiale and  
Lagardere, the parent company of Matra, voted earlier in the day to 
approve an Aerospatiale-Matra merger. 
</P>
<P>
	The privatization process, which will start with the offering of  
shares to institutional investors, will lead to the sale of 17 
percent of the new company on the stock market, the ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matra, through its subsidiaries, is a leading manufacturer of  
tactical missiles. Aerospatiale, which owns 37.9 percent of the 
European aviation consortium Airbus Industrie, also has strong 
missiles activities. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for transferring Matra to Aerospatiale, Lagardere  
will gain a 33 percent stake in the combined company. 
</P>
<P>
	The French government has said it will remain the largest  
shareholder in the merged group. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger and privatization may accelerate the pace of  
restructuring in the European defense sector, analysts have said. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's DaimlerChrysler Aerospace and France's Thomson-CSF are  
seen as the next likely movers following British Aerospace's 
takeover of General Electric PLC's Marconi division earlier this 
year. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
