<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 23:55:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fatal Racing Accident Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- A short piece of videotape showed  
investigators how a fatal accident ended at Lowe's Motor Speedway. 
Now they're hoping technology can help them determine how it 
started. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators plan to use a crane to aid them in their attempts  
to re-enact the flight of a wheel that broke off a car and went 
into the stands, killing three spectators and injuring eight. 
</P>
<P>
	A crane will be one of several tools used in the coming days by  
investigators for K&AMP;K Insurance, the speedway's insurer, to try to 
find out how the wreck occurred in Saturday night's Indy Racing 
League event. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want to make sure you've got it right,'' Doug Hamm, senior  
vice president of Fort Wayne, Ind.-based K&AMP;K, said Thursday. 
``They'll confer with all the experts. It could be a week or two 
before we know anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators decided to bring a crane to the speedway because  
of a 10-second piece of videotape that shows the wheel descending 
into the stands, officials said. The videotape, shot by a spectator 
who refused to identify himself when he dropped it off at the track 
late Monday night, does not show the crash or the ascent of the 
wheel over the speedway's 15-foot catch fence. 
</P>
<P>
	But investigators believe the tape shows enough for them to try  
to re-enact the wheel's flight by using a crane and working 
backward from the top of the flight path, possibly telling them 
more about the source of the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of times you find out that three or four things had to  
have happened for this all to take place,'' Hamm said. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash, which occurred at speeds near 215 mph, sent the wheel  
and suspension parts rocketing into the fourth-turn grandstands. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators believe the tape can help them estimate such  
things as the top height of the wheel and its angles of both ascent 
and descent. Based on those variables, investigators are hopeful of 
then matching information from the re-enactment with the IRL's 
timing and scoring tapes from the race, possibly helping them 
pinpoint the crash's origin. 
</P>
<P>
	Since investigators have no video of the start of the wreck,  
they are still uncertain whether the wheel flew directly into the 
stands or was catapulted over the fence by making contact with 
another car. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of people scratching their heads right now  
trying to think these things through,'' Hamm said. 
</P>
<P>
	The height of Charlotte's safety fence conforms with industry  
standards, but speedway engineers have drafted plans to both raise 
its height and extend the 35-inch-long canopy that extends from the 
top of the fence. 
</P>
<P>
	Learning more about the path of the wheel's upward flight from  
the racing surface could factor into the track's plans for altering 
the fence around the 1.5-mile, high-banked superspeedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The only one of the eight injured people still hospitalized,  
Haley McGee, 9, of Conover, N.C., remained in critical condition 
Thursday at Carolinas Medical Center in Charlotte. McGee, who has 
swelling on her brain, also has developed pneumonia, her family 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway reopened Wednesday for two days of what were  
supposed to be private tests for Winston Cup cars. But so many fans 
showed up Wednesday and Thursday and asked to come in that General 
Motors, which booked the test, finally allowed the speedway to open 
the gates. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans filtered in and out Thursday, relaxing in the frontstretch  
grandstand while the cars, many of them lacking paint jobs or 
numbers, turned lap after lap. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
