<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves $13.1B for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Republicans saying President Clinton has  
``gutted the American military,'' the House overwhelmingly approved 
$13.1 billion Thursday for the fight with Yugoslavia and to 
buttress U.S. forces around the globe. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would more than double the $6.05 billion Clinton  
requested last month to wage the air war through September and care 
for hundreds of thousands of refugees who have fled Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The additions include $1.1 billion to buy missiles and bombs,  
$1.3 billion for spare parts, $1.8 billion to improve troops' pay 
and pensions, and $1.1 billion to modernize military bases, mostly 
in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Final passage was by 311-105, with sound majorities of both  
parties supporting the package. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate has not produced its own version of the legislation.  
GOP leaders there have said they prefer a package closer in size to 
Clinton's request, and a House-Senate compromise of about $9 
billion is expected to emerge next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Just eight days after the House refused to voice support for the  
U.S.-led NATO air campaign, many members of both parties were eager 
to demonstrate their support for U.S. troops by approving the 
funds. But many Republicans wanted to go further by pinning the 
need for extra money on Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without any coherent international blue print, the White House  
has bombed its way around the globe while dropping troops far and 
wide for ill-defined peacemaking duties,'' said House Majority Whip 
Tom DeLay, R-Texas. ``This policy has gutted the American military 
-- which now must be rebuilt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said the extra money was largely a GOP effort to  
relieve a spending crunch looming next year by shifting projects 
into this year's budget. And they accused Republicans of using the 
war to try to embarrass Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last week's amendment was clearly intended to simply pin the  
label on the war of being Clinton's war, unfortunately politicizing 
the situation,'' said Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, ranking 
Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	A Democratic attempt to pare back the measure was rejected,  
260-164. The proposal would have left the measure at $11.6 billion 
-- including Clinton requests for $962 million for Central American 
victims of Hurricane Mitch and $374 million for U.S. farmers, 
proposals that have languished in Congress for weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement underlining the difficulty of opposing defense  
spending while American troops are in combat, the White House 
budget office did not threaten a presidential veto of the House 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	It did, however, urge lawmakers ``to avoid confrontation'' by  
cutting the bill and adding aid for U.S. farmers and Central 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	The House effort came amid the sixth week of the air campaign as  
diplomatic progress was reported in the effort to ease the Kosovo 
crisis. Russia has embraced NATO demands that Serb troops be 
removed and that an armed international force be allowed to keep 
the peace. 
</P>
<P>
	Highlighting legislators' desires to be seen as supporting the  
troops, the House voted 301-117 to reject an amendment by 
conservative Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla., that would have blocked 
use of any of the bill's funds for a ground war without Congress' 
consent. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight days ago, the House voted 249-180 for nearly identical  
language requiring congressional approval for a ground campaign. 
But that was a symbolic measure because lawmakers knew Clinton 
would veto it. With Democrats warning of a veto of the entire 
spending bill if Istook's language was attached, his proposal was 
defeated. 
</P>
<P>
	Tempers flared during the House debate. Without mentioning  
names, Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas, criticized ``members of this 
body who don't care about our military and the future of the safety 
and security of this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That prompted an angry Obey to call the remarks ``meaningless,  
nasty rhetoric that discredits this entire institution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On a voice vote, lawmakers approved language by Rep. Tom Latham,  
R-Iowa, adding nearly $110 million in assistance to American 
farmers hurt by low commodity prices. A provision by Rep. Nancy 
Pelosi, D-Calif., adding $67 million in refugee aid was also added 
by voice vote. 
</P>
<P>
	An effort by conservatives to pay for the measure with spending  
cuts in many domestic programs failed, 322-101. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the bill will be paid for from this year's expected $111  
billion federal surplus. That is a sensitive point for many 
lawmakers, especially Republicans, because this year's surplus will 
come entirely from Social Security, whose surpluses GOP leaders 
have repeatedly pledged not to touch. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill includes $453 million for ongoing U.S. military  
operations against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
