<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Stops Gun Exports to Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department, citing a sharp increase  
in the flow of firearms and ammunition to Venezuela, has 
temporarily suspended licenses for such exports to the South 
American nation, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials said licenses were issued for the sale of more  
than 80,000 handguns from the United States to Venezuela last year, 
a threefold increase over 1997 and sevenfold over 1996. Licenses 
for the sale of 49 million rounds of ammunition also were approved. 
</P>
<P>
	The moratorium, instituted on April 1, will remain in place  
while the U.S. and Venezuelan governments review the situation. The 
officials said they did not know where the weapons and ammunition 
ended up. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also is contacting arms exporters to  
determine whether the increase in license applications is also 
translating into an increase in actual exports. 
</P>
<P>
	A New York Times account of the issue said the ban was imposed  
out of concern that many of the guns were ending up in the hands of 
narcotics gangs and guerrilla groups in neighboring Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
