<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Greenspan Hails Productivity Gains  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan called  
the economy's strong growth and low inflation ``truly phenomenal'' 
today but also expressed worries about ``imbalances in our 
expansion'' -- and that sent jitters through Wall Street. Investors 
and analysts saw Greenspan's comments as a warning signal that even 
though America is currently enjoying the best combination of rapid 
growth, low unemployment and low inflation in three decades, the 
central bank is worried. Greenspan voiced oncern that the 
high-flying stock market might fall, but most especially he worried 
about tight labor markets that could trigger inflationary trends. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Ends Off 8.59  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices fluctuated again today and ended  
lower, unable to shake off growing worries about inflation that 
were fed by cautionary remarks from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan. The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 8.59 at 
10,946.82. The Dow followed the same path it took in yesterday's 
session, changing direction several times. It fell as much as 103 
points during afternoon trading today before regaining ground. 
Broader market indicators also were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP; 
Poor's 500 index was down 15.23 at 1,332.08, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 61.27 at 2,473.18. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,946.82  -  8.59
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1485  Declines 1485  Unchgd  573
NYSE Volume:         858,986,630
Most Active NYSE issue:         AT&AMP;T Corp61 15/16 + 5
