Gold(final) -    $289.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, AT&AMP;T Form Alliance  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft and AT&AMP;T announced a major deal today.  
Microsoft said it will invest $5 billion in AT&AMP;T and AT&AMP;T said it 
will increase its use of Microsoft's software. AT&AMP;T is the nation's 
No. 1 long-distance telephone company and is becoming the top cable 
TV business. Microsoft is the dominant maker of software for 
personal computers and is seeking to widen its role in the 
Internet. The news sent AT&AMP;T stock up 5 to 61 15/16; Microsoft was 
down 1 3/16 at 77 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales Strong in April  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sales at many of nation's biggest retailers  
soared to better-than-expected levels in April as the continued 
strength of the U.S. economy encouraged Americans to do lots of 
shopping last month. It was the third straight month of 
surprisingly strong sales, boding well for earnings reports. A 
number of chains -- including the Limited and Ann Taylor -- have said 
they will top forecasts. The big winners in April were specialty 
clothing chains, while department stores also fared well. 
Discounters were strong, as shoppers turned to stores like Wal-Mart 
and Kmart for their wide selection and affordable prices. 

</P>
<P>
	FCC Staff Mulls SBC-Ameritech Merger  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- SBC Communications' planned takeover of  
Ameritech, which would create the nation's largest local phone 
company, should be subject to conditions to protect consumers and 
competition, a top FCC official said today. If such conditions are 
not imposed, the Federal Communications Commission staff reviewing 
the planned merger had tentatively concluded that it ``flunks the 
public interest test,'' said Thomas Krattenmaker, one of the key 
staff involved in the commission's review. FCC staffers were 
holding a hearing today to gather information from the merger's 
supporters, opponents and others on what possible conditions should 
be. The meeting is to continue tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate OKs Consumer Privacy Measure  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today overwhelmingly adopted a  
measure aimed at protecting consumers' privacy by making it a 
federal crime for anyone to misrepresent himself to obtain 
someone's private financial data. The vote was 95-2 for the 
amendment to sweeping legislation the Senate is considering that 
would let banks, securities firms and insurance companies get more 
deeply into each other's businesses. The measure, proposed by Sen. 
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, 
responded to Americans' growing concern over privacy in an era of 
consolidations creating huge financial institutions selling 
everything from checking accounts to mutual funds. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan: Robbers Pose Y2K Threat  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan is not  
worried that the world's financial markets will come crashing down 
because of the Year 2000 computer problem. His fear is more basic -- 
a rash of robberies spawned by people keeping too much cash lying 
around. In a speech to a Chicago audience, Greenspan worried that 
the news media will so dramatize the dangers of computer system 
meltdowns on Jan. 1, 2000, that the fears will affect the real 
economy. ``I know the evening news is going to play it as though we 
are looking at an asteroid which is about to hit us,'' said 
Greenspan. He said he is concerned that people will become 
vulnerable to robbers who see an opportunity to get their hands 
``on real cash.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Leads Satellite Venture  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lockheed Martin is leading a $3.6 billion  
satellite venture that will beam high-speed, high-capacity Internet 
and multimedia services to customers with small satellite dishes. 
The joint venture with TRW and Telecom Italia, named Astrolink, 
plans to launch the first of four satellites in 2002, providing 
service in Europe and North and South America beginning in 2003. 
The next three satellites are to be launched at six-month 
intervals, expanding the network worldwide, the companies said. The 
initiative by aerospace contractor Lockheed follows a similar 
project started by Hughes Electronics, a unit of General Motors 
Corp. 

</P>
<P>
	Seagram Loses $199M in 3rd Quarter  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Seagram Co., the media and liquor company, lost  
$199 million in its third quarter as more disappointments at the 
box office wiped out profits in other divisions. The company blamed 
the loss on several poorly performing movies, incluing ``EdTV'' and 
``Virus.'' Another poor set of movie releases in the quarter before 
that also resulted in lower revenues from home video rentals, which 
kick in several months after theater releases. The $199 million net 
loss, which translated to 50 cents per share, compared to net 
profits of $461 million, or $1.32 per share, in the same period a 
year ago. 

</P>
<P>
	France Privatizes a Defense Firm  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The French Finance Ministry said today it would  
launch the privatization of aerospace group Aerospatiale Matra 
starting tomorrow. The announcement came after shareholders of 
Aerospatiale and Lagardere, the parent company of Matra, voted 
earlier in the day to approve an Aerospatiale-Matra merger. The 
privatization process, which will start with the offering of shares 
to institutional investors, will lead to the sale of 17 percent of 
the new company on the stock market, the ministry said. 

</P>
<P>
	New Guidelines for Disabled on Web  
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- The Internet would be more user-friendly  
for the blind and deaf under new guidelines that Web site designers 
are being encouraged to use. The World Wide Web Consortium, which 
oversees the programming language used in Web page publishing, 
released the new guidelines. The Web Content Accessibility 
Guidelines establish principles for design, such as the need to 
provide text alternatives for audio and video information. Common 
accessibility problems include images without alternative text, 
uncaptioned audio or undescribed video, tables that are difficult 
to decipher when linearized and sites with poor color contrast, the 
W3C said in a statement. 

