<HEADLINE> Spurs Riding High in Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The party's over. It's back to work today for  
the San Antonio Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	After winning the Midwest Division title and securing the No. 1  
seed in the Western Conference, the Spurs face No. 8 Minnesota in a 
best-of-5 series beginning Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a couple of days of good practice and we'll work  
hard,'' said San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich. ``We realize as a 
team everything we've done to date, you can put that aside now. It 
doesn't matter anymore. We've got to start from scratch and prove 
it all over again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs were pretty convincing down the stretch with four huge  
victories in five days, capped by Wednesday's 88-81 win at Golden 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Saturday, the Spurs beat Portland in overtime in the  
Alamodome, then defeated Utah the next day in the dome. On Tuesday 
the Spurs beat the Trailblazers in Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	Had the Spurs lost to the Warriors in the final game, San  
Antonio would have been seeded No. 3 in the Western Conference 
behind Utah and Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio and Utah each went 37-13 this season, but the Spurs  
claimed the Midwest Division crown and the conference title because 
they won their season series against the Jazz 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still think Utah with their experience is still the team to  
beat. But, boy, right now I wouldn't want to be any other team than 
us,'' said Spurs center David Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, a 10-year veteran who has often been disappointing in  
the postseason, has been playing his best basketball of the season 
lately. 
</P>
<P>
	In three of the final four games he scored more than 20 points.  
He had a season-high 29 points Tuesday night at Portland, and 23 
points and 20 rebounds in Wednesday night's finale in Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team is farther along than any team I've ever been on,''  
said Robinson. ``I'm excited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of jubilant San Antonio fans, cheering and carrying  
signs saying ``Go Spurs Go,'' greeted the players on a warm, 
cloudless afternoon as the team arrived at the airport Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty awesome,'' said forward Sean Elliott. ``I wonder  
what's going to happen if we win this series. They're going to rip 
the roof off this city. That'd be cool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing shirts proclaiming ``Midwest Division Champions,'' the  
players said they were enjoying the moment before practices resumed 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a small feat on a big journey,'' said point guard Avery  
Johnson. ``We still have a long, long, long, long, long way to go. 
But at the same time, we're going in the right direction.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
