<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Guidelines For Disabled on Web </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- The Internet would be more user-friendly  
for the blind and deaf under new guidelines that Web site designers 
are being encouraged to use. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Wide Web Consortium, which oversees the programming  
language used in Web page publishing, on Wednesday released the new 
guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines establish principles  
for design, such as the need to provide text alternatives for audio 
and video information. 
</P>
<P>
	Common accessibility problems include images without alternative  
text, uncaptioned audio or undescribed video, tables that are 
difficult to decipher when linearized and sites with poor color 
contrast, the W3C said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Accessible design also could benefit other users, including  
people who access the Web from mobile phones or if their connection 
speed is too slow to support viewing images or video. 
</P>
<P>
	The guidelines are designed to be compatible with current and  
future Web technologies, as well as older browsers. The guidelines 
include a checklist designers are urged to follow to make sure 
their sites are accessible to the disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	The recommendations were a collaborative effort between industry  
and disability organizations, accessibility research centers and 
governments. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Wide Web Consortium is an international industry  
consortium with more than 320 members jointly run by the 
Massachusetts Institute of Technology Laboratory for Computer 
Science in Cambridge, the National Institute for Research in 
Computer Science and Control in France and Keio University in 
Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:12:17 </DATE_TIME>
