<HEADLINE> Marine Claims Camp Lejeune Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Four Marines were thrown in the brig,  
accused of kicking a fellow enlisted man while he was wrapped in a 
blanket and rupturing his spleen. 
</P>
<P>
	Lance Cpl. Brian Edward Haynes, 20, of Lexington, Ky., said he  
was pulled from his bunk and attacked without provocation April 19. 
He was hospitalized for five days and is on medical leave, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marine Corps officially prohibited hazing in 1997. But  
Marine spokesman Lt. Nick Ritzcovan said of the alleged incident: 
``It looks like a simple assault case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In March, a Marine was given seven months in jail for binding a  
fellow serviceman by the hands and ankles in a hazing on Okinawa. 
In 1998, four Marine trainees pleaded guilty to beating an enlisted 
man in a hazing at Fort Knox, Ky. 
</P>
