<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Staff Mulls SBC-Ameritech Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumers and competition must be protected  
before SBC Communications and Ameritech are allowed to merge into 
the nation's largest local phone company, a top FCC official said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Communications Commission staff opened a two-day hearing  
Thursday on what possible conditions could be placed on the $57 
billion merger to satisfy their concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Krattenmaker, who is leading the staff review, believes  
that the companies, whose local phone territories abut, -- probably 
would eliminate their biggest potential competitor -- each other -- 
by merging. 
</P>
<P>
	Staff members also raised concerns that an SBC-Ameritech would  
be so powerful it would discourage other companies from invading 
the merged companies 13-state local phone territory to provide 
competing services. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC and Ameritech attorneys rejected both concerns, contending  
that the merger would benefit consumers and competition. The 
companies, they said, must merge to become more efficient and 
financially able to do business in markets outside their region, 
which they said the companies cannot do separately. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies also need to merge to become major players in the  
global telecommunications market, the attorneys said. AT&AMP;T and 
other rivals are merging for the same reasons, they added. 
</P>
<P>
	``This merger is about growth,'' said Ameritech's counsel,  
Richard Hetke. 
</P>
<P>
	But Krattenmaker said FCC staff members are looking into  
possible conditions because they had tentatively concluded that the 
merger ``flunks the public interest test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The current mission ... is to devise conditions that can  
transform the merger to one that is on balance beneficial,'' 
Krattenmaker added. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's five commissioners hope to make a decision this summer  
on the $57 billion merger, which has been approved by the Justice 
Department. The merger must be supported by at least three FCC 
commissioners to be approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman Bill Kennard indicated he would like to see the deal  
move forward, saying he has asked the agency's staff to continue 
work on ``a set of conditions designed to address the public 
interest concerns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for SBC and Ameritech said their companies don't  
believe any conditions are warranted but indicated they are willing 
to make some concessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Atkinson, another key figure in the FCC's review, said  
the commission staff had three goals to guide possible conditions: 
</P>
<P>
	--Ensure a combined SBC-Ameritech aggressively competes outside  
its 13-state local region, particularly for residential and small 
business customers, who now have little choice of local providers. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ensure other companies that own their own telecommunications  
networks can compete inside the combined company's 13-state region. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hold SBC and Ameritech to any commitments they make.  
</P>
<P>
	SBC and Ameritech, supported by major telephone unions, say the  
merger will spur local phone competition and possibly lower prices, 
accelerate the roll-out of high-speed Internet access and data 
services and create jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer groups, AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom, Sprint and others want the  
FCC to block the merger, contending it would thwart local phone 
competition and the prospect of lower prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The 13 states involved in the proposed merger are Arkansas,  
California, Connecticut, Kansas, Missouri, Nevada, Oklahoma, Texas, 
Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990506.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SuperSonics End Sour Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- How far did the Seattle SuperSonics fall this  
season? To put it bluntly, they were the most disappointing team in 
the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Lakers and New York Knicks were disappointing,  
too, but at least made the playoffs. For the first time in nine 
years, the Sonics didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the presence of All-Stars Gary Payton and Vin Baker, the  
Sonics dropped from being a championship contender in the West. 
Like a rock. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take the responsibility that we are where we are,'' general  
manager Wally Walker said. 
</P>
<P>
	After firing George Karl, who has the best winning percentage  
among Sonics coaches in the franchise's history, Walker watched in 
horror from his courtside seat. 
</P>
<P>
	He saw a few good things. And a lot of bad things.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've just got to take our lumps and not make excuses,''  
Walker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Payton would have been in the All-Star game again this season --  
if the lockout hadn't canceled the game. The out-of-shape, injured 
Baker would not. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of Baker's lackluster season and subpar seasons by  
Billy Owens and Hersey Hawkins, the Sonics finished ninth in the 
Western Conference with a 25-25 record. 
</P>
<P>
	They had to beat the Clippers 107-105 Wednesday night in Los  
Angeles to avoid having a losing season. Minnesota also was 25-25 
this season, but made the playoffs over Seattle because of a 
tiebreaker. The Timberwolves won two of three from the Sonics. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we can do is to make sure it never happens again like  
this,'' first-year coach Paul Westphal said. 
</P>
<P>
	How could a team that won 61 games and its third straight  
Pacific Division in Karl's final season in Seattle last year fall 
so far so fast? 
</P>
<P>
	And what will be Barry Ackerley's reaction, especially if Walker  
and Westphal don't right the Sonics' ship next season? 
</P>
<P>
	Remember, this is the owner who complained about Karl before the  
playoffs last season that he didn't have a championship ring. Now, 
Ackerley finds himself with a lottery team and he can't be happy 
about that, especially if home attendance falls off dramatically 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
	In Milwaukee, where Karl landed with a $20 million coaching  
contract, the Bucks are in the playoffs. In Portland, where former 
Sonics team president Bob Whitsitt wound up after being fired by 
Ackerley, the Trail Blazers are hoping to make a title run. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seattle, the Sonics are trying to live down the most  
disappointing season in franchise history. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never expected to be where we are,'' Walker said.  
</P>
<P>
	Before the season finally began following the lockout three  
months ago, Walker signed free agents Owens and Olden Polynice from 
Sacramento and traded Jim McIlvaine to New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	The McIlvaine trade was an excellent one -- addition by  
subtraction -- but Polynice, Seattle's starting center, and the 
oft-injured Owens did not work out. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker said he won't talk specifics until next week about the  
Sonics' future, but the team isn't expected to retain Polynice, who 
played this season under a one-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Payton carried the Sonics on his shoulders this season and got a  
lot of help from Detlef Schrempf, 36. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Sonics liked the development of their trio of rookies;  
Jelani McCoy, Vladimir Stepania and Rashard Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hawkins, 32, slowed considerably and the Sonics could not  
maintain the high level of play they had under Karl. 
</P>
<P>
	Not too much blame should be heaped on Westphal, though. It  
wasn't his fault that Owens and Baker didn't expect a season and 
weren't in shape before becoming injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paul came into a tough situation,'' Walker said. ``I respect  
the way he handled it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Out of coaching after being fired in Phoenix during the 1995-96  
season, Westphal said he enjoyed his season as a coach in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coaching in the NBA is great,'' he said. ``It's definitely got  
its ups and downs. It makes you appreciate the ups all the more 
when you have to go through a few downs. And you don't want those 
downs to last too long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics are expected to try to re-sign Baker, a four-time  
All-Star power forward who came to them, in effect, in a trade for 
Shawn Kemp before last season. 
</P>
<P>
	In order to avoid losing Baker as a free agent, the team will  
have to pay a harsh price. Under the league's new labor agreement, 
he can demand $87 million for seven seasons. Baker hardly looked 
like an $87 million player this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker and Westphal also are expected to try to bring back  
Schrempf for a 15th NBA season -- if they can convince him that he 
won't have to go through another season like this one. 
</P>
<P>
	McCoy, Stepania and Lewis will have a full summer to work out  
and the Sonics hope they will make major contributions next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Another key in the offseason for the Sonics will be trying to  
convince Payton that things will improve in Seattle. An unhappy 
Payton could cause Walker and Westphal fits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics don't expect Payton to demand a trade this summer.  
</P>
<P>
	``Gary's going to be here,'' Walker said. ``He's a huge part of  
this franchise. He knows how we feel about him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
