<DOCNO> APW19990506.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 14:35:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fatal Racing Accident Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Investigators studying an accident at  
Lowe's Motor Speedway will try to reenact the flight of a wheel 
that broke off a car and went into the stands, killing three 
spectators and injuring eight. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the investigation by the speedway's insurer, K&AMP;K  
Insurance Group, involves using a crane to try to retrace the 
flight of a wheel that snapped loose during a three-car wreck at 
Saturday's Indy Racing League event, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash, which occurred at speeds near 215 mph, sent the wheel  
and suspension parts rocketing into the fourth-turn grandstands. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of people scratching their heads right now  
trying to think these things through,'' said Doug Hamm, senior vice 
president of Fort Wayne, Ind.-based K&AMP;K. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators decided to bring a crane to the speedway in the  
coming days because of a 10-second piece of videotape that shows 
the wheel landing in the stands, officials said. The videotape, 
which was shot by a spectator who refused to identify himself when 
he dropped it off at the track late Monday night, does not show the 
crash or the ascent of the wheel over the speedway's 15-foot-high 
catch fence. 
</P>
<P>
	But investigators believe the tape shows enough for them to try  
to reenact the wheel's flight by using a crane and working backward 
from the top of the flight path, possibly telling them more about 
the source of the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of times you find out that three or four things had to  
have happened for this all to take place,'' Hamm said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators believe the tape can help them estimate such  
things as the top height of the wheel and its angles of both ascent 
and descent. Based on those variables, investigators are hopeful of 
then matching information from the reenactment with the IRL's 
timing and scoring tapes from the race, possibly helping them 
pinpoint the crash's origin, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since investigators have no video of the start of the wreck,  
they are still uncertain whether the wheel flew directly into the 
stands or was catapulted over the fence by making contact with 
another car. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want to make sure you've got it right,'' Hamm said.  
``They'll confer with all the experts. It could be a week or two 
before we know anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The height of Charlotte's safety fence conforms with industry  
standards, but speedway engineers have drafted plans to both raise 
its height and extend the 35-inch-long canopy that extends from the 
top of the fence. 
</P>
<P>
	Learning more about the path of the wheel's upward flight from  
the racing surface could factor into the track's plans for altering 
the catch fence around the 1.5-mile, high-banked superspeedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The only one of the eight injured people still hospitalized,  
Haley McGee, 9, of Conover, N.C., remained in critical condition 
Thursday at Carolinas Medical Center in Charlotte. McGee, who has 
swelling on her brain, also has developed pneumonia, her family 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway reopened Wednesday for two days of testing for  
Winston Cup cars. No spectators were allowed in the stands 
Wednesday because the session, booked by General Motors for its 
teams, was considered a private test. 
</P>
<P>
	But numerous fans came to the track Wednesday asking if they  
could come in, sit in the stands and watch. They were turned away, 
but when more showed up Thursday and made the same request, GM 
allowed the speedway to open its gates. Dozens of fans filtered in 
and out throughout the day, relaxing in the seats above the 
frontstretch while the cars, many of them lacking paint jobs or 
numbers, turned lap after lap. 

</P>
</TEXT>
