<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Still Seeking Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization's efforts to appoint  
a new chief again sank deeper into procedural wrangling Thursday, 
nearly a week after its outgoing leader officially stepped down. 
</P>
<P>
	The 134-member WTO General Council ended its fourth session  
since Friday with no signs of progress toward breaking the deadlock 
over a new secretary-general to succeed Italy's Renato Ruggiero, 
diplomats said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We, the members, should be ashamed of the spectacle before  
us,'' Mexican ambassador Alejandro de la Pena told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	European Union ambassador Roderick Abbott, who left the 5 1/2-hour  
meeting early, said: ``We are going round and round in circles. We 
have to take a good break and calm down and start talking 
substance, because what is going on here is useless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The council was expected to meet again next week or early the  
week after. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO is in the embarrassing situation of trying to put its  
own house in order with only months remaining before a conference 
in Seattle meant to open the way for a new round of trade 
liberalization talks, and with just days until the possible start 
of another transatlantic trade war. 
</P>
<P>
	Former New Zealand Premier Mike Moore looked set to win last  
week after the council chairman proposed Moore formally. The 
chairman said he considered the other candidate, Thai Deputy 
Premier Supachai Panitchpakdi, to be out of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	But Supachai's supporters, led by Japan and the ASEAN group of  
countries, refused to concede defeat. They said the chairman, 
Tanzanian Ambassador Ali Mchumo, had no authority to exclude any 
candidate and insisted the consultation process had been flawed. 
</P>
<P>
	Supachai supporters say more than 50 of the WTO's 134 members  
are holding out for the Thai candidate. Kenya has proposed that 
Mchumo try to reach a consensus around Supachai. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO chooses its secretary-general by consensus rather than  
by election. Supachai's backers insist a consensus over Moore is 
unreachable. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore's supporters, which include the United States and many  
Latin American countries, said they still believe consensus is 
possible and called for Supachai to withdraw with dignity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
